<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Appeals Court Backs AP in Ad Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A federal appeals court has upheld the dismissal  
of a lawsuit accusing The Associated Press of trying to monopolize 
the electronic delivery of newspaper advertising. 
</P>
<P>
	The 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals concluded the AD/SAT  
delivery company had failed to prove there was a threat the AP 
could achieve monopoly power in the marketplace. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-judge appeals panel also found that much of the  
conduct challenged by AD/SAT's lawsuit was the kind of activity 
that previous rulings have made clear should not be deterred, much 
less punished. 
</P>
<P>
	``That is, it is not unlawful for an existing firm, entering a  
new product market, to promote its product by touting the benefits 
afforded by that product's association with the firm,'' the appeals 
court wrote in its ruling Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nor is it unlawful for employees of one division of a firm to  
promote products produced by another division,'' it said. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Peter K. Leisure in 1996 tossed out the  
lawsuit, deciding there were other competitors in the market and 
advertisers were beginning to develop their own electronic delivery 
systems. 
</P>
<P>
	The AP started its AdSEND service in September 1994, using  
satellites to deliver advertising to newspapers in minutes, in a 
form ready for pagination. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit claimed AdSEND unfairly utilized the AP's network of  
member newspapers to enter the market, drive out competitors and 
become dominant. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorneys for the AP said it was untrue that its prices were  
meant to drive others out of business. They said AdSEND could 
charge less than AD/SAT because it planned to carry a larger volume 
of advertising. 
</P>
<P>
	Daniel R. Shulman, a lawyer for AD/SAT, said the business was  
forced to close its doors after 10 years when the earlier ruling 
went against it. 
</P>
<P>
	Other defendants in the lawsuit included the Newspaper  
Association of America; the National Newspaper Network; Cox 
Enterprises Inc.; Advance Publications Inc.; AP board member Donald 
E. Newhouse, who is president of Advance and The Star-Ledger of 
Newark, N.J., and was chairman of the NAA when AdSEND was 
developed; and AP member newspapers The Birmingham (Ala.) News, The 
Oakland Press of Pontiac, Mich., The News &AMP; Observer of Raleigh, 
N.C., and The Daily Oklahoman of Oklahoma City. The Lexington (Ky.) 
Herald-Leader was dismissed by the judge as defendant in 1995. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
