<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> San Diego Mayor's Conduct Targeted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Claims that the mayor used her influence  
improperly seem almost secondary to residents of this easy-going 
coastal city compared to debate the accusation has revived: whether 
a downtown ballpark is really a good idea. 
</P>
<P>
	A San Diego County grand jury has accused Mayor Susan Golding of  
improperly using her influence to gain a business group's support 
for a new Padres ballpark. 
</P>
<P>
	The accusation, made public Thursday, did not bring criminal  
charges. It recommended that District Attorney Paul Pfingst pursue 
a civil misconduct case. He said he would decide within a month. 
</P>
<P>
	``The mayor doesn't have anything to worry about,'' said Virgil  
Jackson, 44, the owner of a downtown shoe shine business. ``Most 
people are behind her and the ballpark.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps not.  
</P>
<P>
	``I was absolutely opposed to it in November, and I'm absolutely  
opposed to it now,'' said Lee Chiles, 36, a clerk in a downtown law 
firm. 
</P>
<P>
	If Golding is found to have committed misconduct, she could be  
removed from office. However, her term expires next year and she is 
already barred from seeking a third term. 
</P>
<P>
	``The allegations are groundless,'' Golding said Thursday. ``I  
sleep very well at night.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The grand jury said Golding offered to support a $4 million  
allocation for a San Diego Hotel-Motel Association advertising 
program in exchange for the organization's support of a ballpark 
ballot measure. 
</P>
<P>
	Rick Mansur, president of the hotel-motel association, said the  
grand jury was off the mark because his group does not market San 
Diego -- the San Diego Convention and Visitors Bureau does. 
</P>
<P>
	He said his organization asked Golding for an increase in  
marketing dollars for the bureau, but before the City Council voted 
to put the baseball stadium proposal on the ballot. 
</P>
<P>
	``The grand jury is trying to make it out like we hoodwinked  
everybody and got this big check,'' Mansur said. ``That never 
happened. At no time did the mayor try to influence us. Our budget 
request and our support of the ballpark were never linked.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The ballpark and downtown redevelopment was approved by 60  
percent of the voters last November. The $411 million venture is to 
be financed in part with $225 million in municipal bonds secured by 
hotel-room tax revenue. The ballpark is set for completion by 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	Ballpark opponents believe the city's contribution to the  
project would be better spent on a new library, school 
improvements, or other projects, and that the Padres should 
continue to share Qualcomm Stadium with the National Football 
League's Chargers. 
</P>
<P>
	Mike Hardy, co-owner of a tattoo shop, voted for the stadium,  
mostly because he's a lifelong Padres fan. But lately he's had 
doubts about the benefits and the cost of the project. The grand 
jury allegations only deepened his suspicions. 
</P>
<P>
	``If everything was laid on the table, the vote might be  
different,'' Hardy said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
