<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Coke Recall Cost Estimate: $60M </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The world's leading bottler of Coca-Cola  
beverages estimates the price tag of the European soft-drink health 
scare is at least $60 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Coca-Cola Enterprises Inc. said Thursday that about 14 million  
cases, made up of 24 eight-ounce servings, were affected by the 
product recall in Belgium, less than 1 percent of its annual 
volume. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides the $60 million one-time-only pretax expense of the  
recall, the bottling company said it expects reduced sales and 
lower operating profits and earnings per share in the second 
quarter as a result of the health scare. Some of the recall costs 
will be reimbursed by insurance and other sources. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Coca-Cola Enterprises, the leading worldwide bottler,  
distributor and marketer of Coca-Cola beverages, fell 2.1 percent, 
or by 68 3/4 cents, to $31.68 3/4 Thursday on the New York Stock 
Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Coca-Cola Co. holds a 40 percent stake Coca-Cola Enterprises,  
which owns and runs the plants at the center of the crisis. Belgian 
health officials say 249 cases of illnesses have been reported in 
Belgium since June 9 by people who drank Coke products. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, Belgium authorized the resumption of production.  
</P>
<P>
	``As we reintroduce our products into the marketplace, the most  
important issues to Coca-Cola Enterprises are the quality of our 
products and earning the trust and confidence of our consumers, our 
customers, and all European officials,'' said Henry Schimberg, 
president and CEO of the Atlanta-based bottling company. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said it couldn't estimate sales losses in Belgium  
and other European countries where sales were affected until after 
it sees the response to marketing efforts meant to revitalize 
demand. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe that we can minimize the short-term impact on sales  
and we are confident that this situation will not materially affect 
financial results in the year 2000 and beyond,'' Schimberg said. 
</P>
<P>
	Coca-Cola Co., also based in Atlanta, was ``still working on our  
assessment'' of the costs of the crisis, spokesman Rob Baskin said 
Thursday. ``It's premature for us.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
