<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore On California Fund-Raising Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Al Gore concedes that Americans probably  
aren't ready for the 2000 presidential campaign, but he is. 
</P>
<P>
	At one campaign appearance after another, the vice president  
returned to the same themes: Stay the economic course that has 
brought prosperity. Improve public schools. Stiffen gun control 
laws. 
</P>
<P>
	In four back-to-back TV interviews and two speeches Wednesday,  
the vice president stayed relentlessly ``on message,'' hammering 
those themes from San Diego to San Francisco and often using them 
to extract himself from uncomfortable questioning. 
</P>
<P>
	When a reporter asked him whether he is paying a political price  
for President Clinton's scandals, Gore responded he knew ``how to 
keep the prosperity going.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Questioned about attempts to shed his wooden image, Gore said he  
wasn't about to change his style -- and then added, ``I know how to 
keep the prosperity going.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In both speeches and all four interviews, Gore made it clear he  
will seize on gun control as a defining campaign issue. He also 
took aim at Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican front-runner. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to make sure that the agenda for America's future is  
set by the American people, not by organizations like the National 
Rifle Association,'' he told 600 donors in San Francisco who 
responded with a standing ovation. 
</P>
<P>
	``Instead of shielding gun manufacturers against being held  
responsible for their activities, we should be shielding children 
and families against violence,'' Gore said. 
</P>
<P>
	His comments were references to a bill Bush signed into law last  
week that makes it harder for municipalities and counties to sue 
firearms makers. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore steered the conversation to gun control at every pass.  
</P>
<P>
	Asked whether a Bush-Gore general election race would be a dull  
contest between two men of privilege, he said: ``If that's how it 
turns out, you'll see a major debate about whether or not we should 
shield children and families from gun violence, or shield gun 
manufacturers with special protection.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The vice president acknowledged to another interviewer that ``a  
lot of people aren't ready'' for the presidential race. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most people don't have time to worry about this right now  
because they know the election's a long way off,'' he said. ``As we 
get closer to it, you'll see a lot more attention paid to it, and 
then they'll see who is for shielding the gun manufacturers and who 
is for shielding children and families against gun violence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore spoke on the first day of a two-day fund-raising blitz  
through California that aides said would bring in $1.1 million. 
</P>
<P>
	He was scheduled today to tour a gay and lesbian center in  
between fund-raising stops in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	California voters are likely to face a ballot measure on  
same-sex marriage on primary day next year. The proposal would 
declare that only heterosexual marriages are legally binding. Gore 
said in San Francisco he favors certain legal protections for 
domestic partners but opposes ``a change in the institution of 
marriage as we now know it between men and women.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
