<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 23:00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Neighborhood Fights Yuppie Invasion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- In a city where neighborhoods coexist like  
tightly nestled countries -- each with a distinct personality and 
culture -- people don't sit quietly when one begins to invade 
another. 
</P>
<P>
	And so San Francisco's Mission district, historically a haven  
for Hispanic immigrants and artists, has become a battlefield for 
yuppies, activists and one eccentric anarchist. 
</P>
<P>
	``The yuppie takeover can be stopped,'' reads one of his fliers.  
``Vandalize yuppie cars ... Break the glass. Scratch the paint. 
Trash them all. Don't get caught.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All sides are scrambling madly for affordable housing as the  
thriving high-tech economy, coupled with the usual lure of 
attractive living in the Bay Area, has pulled 60,000 new residents 
into the city since 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	With stock options to burn, these tech workers are buying  
properties and driving up rents. ``Live-work'' lofts built in the 
1980s as crash pads for struggling artists are selling for 
$400,000. Tiny one-bedroom apartments start at $1,200 a month. 
</P>
<P>
	The self-appointed voice for the displaced artists and  
blue-collar workers, operating under the alias Nestor Makhno in 
homage to an obscure Ukrainian anarchist, was unmasked by police 
recently as Kevin Keating. 
</P>
<P>
	Keating, 38, was caught with his hands covered with wallpaper  
paste and a backpack full of fliers from the ``Mission Yuppie 
Eradication Project.'' He has been charged with malicious mischief. 
</P>
<P>
	The fliers, like Makhno's letters to one of the city's free  
weekly papers, advocate trashing sushi restaurants and other 
symbols of the yuppie invasion. 
</P>
<P>
	Police say they haven't seen any increase in vandalism in the  
neighborhood. But Keating is quick to portray the Mission as an 
angry underclass about to be crushed by an indifferent aristocracy. 
</P>
<P>
	``Working class neighborhoods are being destroyed for profit,''  
he said. ``We need a militant organization of tenants.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Newcomers who have invested in older homes and opened  
fashionable restaurants and stores in the Mission claim they're 
being unfairly vilified. 
</P>
<P>
	``When people are saying things like, 'We don't want a certain a  
group to come into our neighborhood,' it's the same thing as a 
white group not wanting blacks,'' said new Mission resident Robert 
Cort Jr. ``Who are they to judge what the flavor of the city should 
be?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Behind the diatribes is a more complex picture of a neighborhood  
that many would like to call home. 
</P>
<P>
	A Hispanic outpost since a Catholic mission was founded in 1776,  
the neighborhood has retained its Latin feel. Salsa music blares 
from storefronts; elderly women stroll past family-owned markets 
with fresh vegetables tucked under their arms. Walls are painted 
with madly colorful murals, celebrating images of Aztec warriors 
and mother goddesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Increasingly, the salsa sounds are being replaced by the  
clashing and banging of new construction as industrial tracts are 
bulldozed for lofts and new nightclubs and eateries. 
</P>
<P>
	While Keating and his supporters decry the gentrification of the  
neighborhood, some longtime Mission residents aren't too worried. 
</P>
<P>
	``There hasn't been any trouble at all from the yuppies,'' said  
Anita Mercado, a volunteer at the Mission Cultural Center for 
Latino Arts and lifelong neighborhood resident. ``It's not owned by 
one race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But others feel the changes undermine the very thing that makes  
San Francisco special: its quirky characters and ethnic 
neighborhoods, such as North Beach, Chinatown and Japantown. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think it's a crime to make money, but I do think it's  
a crime for the yuppies to come here and take all our apartments 
and drive up the rent,'' said Natalie Dillon, 24, who sings in a 
disco-funk band. ``All that 'Die yuppies' stuff is kind of harsh, 
but do they have to take our neighborhood?'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
