Gold(final) -    $262.00    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Thu.
Silver(final) -   UNCH    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Wed.

</P>
<P>
	Microsoft Trial Testimony Ends  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- After 76 days, testimony ended today in the  
landmark Microsoft antitrust trial. The final witness, economist 
Richard Schmalensee of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, 
argued forcefully that the $14 billion Microsoft Corp. isn't the 
entrenched monopolist that illegally wields extraordinary 
influence, as portrayed by the government. But the company's 
witness was challenged in a piercing cross-examination by David 
Boies, a Justice Department lawyer. Microsoft shares were at 84 5/8, 
down 1 3/8. 

</P>
<P>
	Durable Goods Orders Rise  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Demand for autos and aircraft led orders for  
big-ticket manufactured goods up 1.4 percent in May, a sign that 
the nation's battered manufacturing sector could be headed for a 
revival. The Commerce Department said today that orders for durable 
goods -- items expected to last at least three years -- increased 
$2.8 billion last month to a seasonally adjusted $197.6 billion. 
May's increase was the ninth in the last 12 months and followed a 
2.3 percent decline in April, the government said. Analysts 
expected May's turnaround. 


</P>
<P>
	Arco, BP Amoco Defend Merger Plan  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two corporations planning a merger that would  
create the world's second-largest oil company spent hours today 
trying to assure U.S. senators the deal would benefit consumers and 
encourage competition. Atlantic Richfield Chairman Mike Bowlin told 
a Senate committee that the $25.6 billion stock deal to marry his 
firm to BP Amoco would create a company that would invest in the 
latest and best technology and use it to develop new energy 
resources. Even after hearing from Bowlin and Richard Olver, a BP 
Amoco group managing director, however, members of the Senate 
Energy and Natural Resources Committee questioned them closely on 
whether the merger would reduce competition and increase prices. 

</P>
<P>
	Foreign Steel Shipments Rebound  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Steel imports to the United States jumped 30  
percent in May, the Commerce Department said today, two days after 
the Senate rejected a quota bill partly on grounds that imports 
were headed down. Whether the May numbers will give new life to 
quotas is unclear. Commerce Secretary William Daley, who had argued 
that U.S. quotas could start an international trade war, said the 
latest figures should not be cause for worry. ``One month is not 
reason to suddenly believe it's a trend,'' he told reporters. 

</P>
<P>
	Morgan Stanley Earnings Up 35 Pct.  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co. reported today  
it earned $1.15 billion in the second quarter of its fiscal year, 
handily beating analysts' estimates and marking a 35 percent 
increase over the same period a year ago. The big investment firm 
attributed the strong showing to healthy results across the broad 
range of its businesses, including equity underwriting, merger 
transactions, and overseas operations. The earnings were equivalent 
to $1.95 per share in the quarter ended May 31, easily surpassing 
the $1.54 per share expected by analysts surveyed by First Call 
Corp. In the same period a year ago, the company earned $852 
million, or $1.37 per share. Morgan Stanley stock was up 7/16 at 93 
11/16 today. 

</P>
<P>
	GTE Sells Airfone Unit  
</P>
<P>
	IRVING, Texas (AP) -- The manufacturer of a widely used in-air  
telephone will be sold to a private equity investment firm, parent 
corporation GTE Corp. announced today. It will sell its in-flight 
communications unit, GTE Airfone, to Oak Hill Capital Partners LP. 
Terms of the deal were not disclosed. GTE said the deal is expected 
to close in the third quarter, pending approval by federal 
regulators. 

</P>
<P>
	CMGI May Buy Compaq's AltaVista  
</P>
<P>
	ANDOVER, Mass. (AP) -- Internet investment company CMGI Inc.  
confirmed today that it is in talks with Compaq Computer Corp. to 
buy its popular AltaVista search engine and portal. In a statement, 
CMGI said ``discussions are in a preliminary stage and there can be 
no assurance that a transaction will be consummated.'' CMGI also 
said it was talking to Compaq about establishing a strategic 
relationship between the two companies. Compaq confirmed it was in 
talks, but also cautioned that a deal may not be reached. Compaq 
stock was down 13/16 at 22 5/8 today. 

</P>
<P>
	CompUSA To Cut Up to 1,500 Jobs  
</P>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- The personal computer retailer CompUSA Inc. plans  
to cut 1,000 to 1,500 jobs, or up to 7 percent its work force, as 
part of an overhaul designed to boost profitability. CompUSA, which 
operates 211 stores in 79 cities, also said today that it will 
close four stores soon and was considering closing as many as 10 
others. It currently employs about 21,000 people. The moves result 
from an evaluation of its business and will result in 
``fundamentally redefining CompUSA's entire business concept,'' 
said James F. Halpin, president and chief executive. 

</P>
<P>
	France Lifts Coke Production Ban  
</P>
<P>
	DUNKIRK, France (AP) -- France followed the lead of Belgium and  
lifted a ban on Coca-Cola products today. The recall that followed 
hundreds of reports of illnesses by people who drank Coca-Cola 
products is estimated to have cost at least $60 million, and could 
be much higher. But Coca-Cola's main bottler said ``the crisis is 
over.'' Production in France will resume early tomorrow, said Henry 
A. Schimberg, president and chief operating offer of Coca-Cola 
Enterprises Inc., the world's leading bottler and distributor of 
Coca-Cola. Coca-Cola Co. stock was up 3/4 at 62 1/2. 

</P>
<P>
	Merger of 3 Unions Is Delayed  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- The proposed merger of the International  
Association of Machinists and Aerospace Workers with the United 
Auto Workers and United Steelworkers of America has been put on 
hold, pending talks between the UAW and Steelworkers unions to 
merge first. In a statement, the presidents of the three unions 
said the UAW and Steelworkers unions were more comparable in their 
organizational structures and would ``take the next step in the 
unification process by conducting immediate discussions to join 
their two unions together. 

</P>
<P>
	Tektronix To Split In Two  
</P>
<P>
	WILSONVILLE, Ore. (AP) -- Tektronix Inc. plans to split into two  
separate, publicly traded companies and sell its video and 
networking division. One company will be based on the electronic 
and scientific measurement equipment that has been Tektronix's core 
product since it was founded in 1946 to make oscilloscopes. The 
other will be based on the color printers and imaging equipment 
that has fueled expansion for Tektronix during the growth of the 
desktop computer market. The decision to split came as Tektronix 
announced fourth quarter earnings of $24.9 million, or 53 cents per 
share, down more than 41 percent from the $42.5 million, or 83 
cents per share, earned during the fourth quarter in 1998. 
Tektronix stock was up 3 1/4 at 29 13/16. 

</P>
