<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Congressmen Urge 1972 Games Justice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A new confession to a decades-old terrorist  
assault is stirring activity on Capitol Hill, where some lawmakers 
want to encourage arrest of a mastermind of the deadly 
hostage-taking at the 1972 Munich Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Reps. Steve LaTourette, R-Ohio, and Jim Saxton, R-N.J., are  
collecting signatures on a letter urging President Clinton 
``demand'' that Jordan's king honor an Interpol arrest warrant and 
``immediately turn over'' former Palestinian guerrilla Mohammed 
Oudeh for prosecution in Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	In his autobiography published last month, Oudeh, better known  
by the code name Abu Daoud, acknowledged a role in the plan to take 
Israeli weightlifters hostage in order to dramatize the plight of 
Palestinians. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the book came out, Germany has issued an arrest warrant,  
which Palestinian officials are trying to have rescinded; Israel 
has banned Oudeh from returning to his West Bank home; and France 
has turned Oudeh away at its doors. 
</P>
<P>
	LaTourette and Saxton, chairman of the House Task Force on  
Terrorism and Unconventional Warfare, became involved because an 
American was one of the 17 people killed in Munich. 
</P>
<P>
	David Berger of Shaker Heights, Ohio, a Cleveland suburb, held  
dual American and Israeli citizenship, but lived in the U.S. until 
1970, when he moved to Israel and made the Israeli weightlifting 
team. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be reprehensible for the United States to turn its  
back and refuse to do all within its power to see that the assassin 
of an American citizen is brought to justice,'' the lawmakers say 
in their letter. 
</P>
<P>
	Berger's parents still live in Shaker Heights and attend a  
synagogue in LaTourette's district. They and the congressman were 
alerted about the published confession by the Zionist Organization 
of America. 
</P>
<P>
	The Olympic Village raid led to a 20-hour hostage standoff, a  
bungled rescue attempt and 17 deaths. Two Israeli athletes were 
killed in the village. Nine others, including Berger, died during 
the attempted rescue at Munich's airport. A German policeman and 
five Palestinians also died. 
</P>
<P>
	Oudeh was arrested in France in 1977 then expelled to Algeria.  
Since then, he has lived in exile in Lebanon, Jordan, Eastern 
Europe and the West Bank. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
