<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Artist' Wins Copyright Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The Artist formerly known as Prince has won a  
lengthy copyright infringement case surrounding his symbol-shaped 
guitar. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Court Judge Rebecca Pallmeyer last week found no  
merit in the fraud and copyright infringement claims filed by 
guitar designer Ferdinand Pickett. 
</P>
<P>
	Pickett said he created the guitar -- which incorporates the  
symbols for man and woman -- in 1993 and showed it to the musician, 
hoping he would buy it. The Artist denied ever meeting Pickett. 
</P>
<P>
	Pickett sued for fraud in 1994 after learning the Artist was  
performing with a similarly shaped instrument. He amended the 
lawsuit in 1996 to charge copyright infringement. 
</P>
<P>
	The Artist first used the symbol in the early 1990s and in 1992  
dropped his name in favor of using the symbol to identify himself. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
