<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House GOP Offer 'E-Contract' Agenda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Republicans have introduced an  
``e-contract'' agenda aimed at promoting the growth of American 
high tech industries through measures to reduce government taxes 
and regulations. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe a cutting edge society needs a cutting edge  
agenda,'' House Majority Leader Dick Armey said Wednesday. '' We 
had the Contract with America to address a broad range of concerns. 
And we think we need a contract that specifically addresses the 
concerns of high-tech America.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The agenda includes tax cuts that promote investment and  
research, modernizing the education system, preventing frivolous 
lawsuits, removing barriers to Internet commerce, promoting high 
speed Internet access, protecting intellectual property rights and 
reining in excessive federal regulations. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our commitment to high technology begins with the notion that  
Congress must first do no harm,'' said Rep. J.C. Watts, R-Okla., 
chairman of the House Republican Conference. ``It is largely thanks 
to the absence of government interference that new technologies 
have been able to prosper and benefit us all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	House Democratic leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri discounted the  
package, saying it was motivated by the GOP desire to win a bigger 
share of the high tech industry's political contributions. 
</P>
<P>
	``Technology business leaders don't want e-pandering; they want  
a real e-policy which will promote the growth of e-commerce and 
make sure this sector will continue its leadership in our domestic 
and the global economy,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
