<DOCNO> APW19990624.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 06:40:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NYC's Giuliani Walks Out on Press </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Peppered with questions about a canceled  
magazine party at the Brooklyn Navy Yard that might have included 
his potential U.S. Senate rival, Hillary Rodham Clinton, Mayor 
Rudolph Giuliani stonewalled, chided and, finally, walked out on 
the City Hall press. 
</P>
<P>
	The flap ensued when Deputy Mayor Randy Levine admitted Tuesday  
the glitzy August launch party for the new Talk magazine was 
canceled in part because Mrs. Clinton was being considered for the 
first cover and there was speculation she might be invited to the 
party. 
</P>
<P>
	When first asked about the cancellation at the one time he was  
available to meet with the press on Wednesday, Giuliani said, 
``Talk to the Navy Yard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the Navy Yard would have treated me the same way,''  
the mayor said, adding, ``I don't think this is an issue of 
discrimination against somebody from Arkansas.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pushed further on who made the decision, officials of the  
city-owned Navy Yard or his political operatives, the mayor said he 
was sure it was a joint decision and that he personally didn't care 
one way or the other. 
</P>
<P>
	The mayor's pique began showing after the eighth straight  
question and was in full bloom by the ninth when he said: ``I 
imagine there must be something else going on in the life of this 
city that you'd like to ask about. Or have we gotten to the point 
of ultimate frivolity?'' 
</P>
<P>
	When the questions continued, an exasperated Giuliani said,  
``No, no, no. We have exhausted the subject. If there are no more 
questions about another subject, then I can go back to work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A television reporter obliged, asking him about a Jewish  
organization's plans to give Mrs. Clinton an award. ``Are they 
going to have that ceremony at the Navy Yard?'' the mayor jokingly 
asked. 
</P>
<P>
	Told it was happening in Washington, the mayor said, ``Oh, OK,  
well as long as it's not at the Navy Yard, I'll have no comment on 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The meeting with the press was suddenly over.  
</P>
<P>
	``Thank you,'' the mayor muttered and left.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
