<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Family Collects Cow After 311 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ROCHELLE, N.Y. (AP) -- A bunch of out-of-towners who think  
New Rochelle owes them something forced the city to round up an 
innocent farm animal to honor a 311-year-old real estate deal. 
</P>
<P>
	``Where's the beef?'' William Rodman Pell III said Thursday  
before Mayor Timothy Idoni handed over a 6-month-old Holstein named 
Jessie, this year's payment on a never-ending debt. 
</P>
<P>
	Pell is a descendant of Sir John Pell, Lord of the Manor of  
Pelham. Sir John sold 6,000 acres of his holdings in 1688 to French 
Huguenots who had escaped religious persecution. The parcel became 
New Rochelle, now a New York City suburb. 
</P>
<P>
	Sir John received the equivalent of $11,625 and was promised  
``one fatt calfe on every fouer and twentieth day of June yearly 
and every year forever, if demanded.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We are somewhat legally obligated,'' said Idoni.  
</P>
<P>
	The mayor and various Pell descendants turned the occasion into  
a party and family reunion, coinciding with the centennial of the 
city's incorporation. 
</P>
<P>
	The cow-claiming ceremony was followed by a luncheon for 60  
relatives at the Bartow-Pell mansion, also named for the family, in 
the Bronx. Pells, including former Sen. Claiborne Pell of Rhode 
Island, came from all over the country. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pells were major landowners in precolonial days, and the  
Manor of Pelham stretched from City Island, now in the Bronx, 
across a large portion of Westchester County. 
</P>
<P>
	The mayor told the assembled Pells that in selling New Rochelle,  
they had pretty much given away an asset now worth about $4 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The ``fatt calfe'' provision was ignored for centuries as New  
Rochelle grew from a rural outpost to a city of nearly 70,000. But 
in 1952, the Rev. Walden Pell, headmaster of a school for boys in 
Delaware, got word of the family rights and figured he could add to 
the school's herd of dairy cows. 
</P>
<P>
	So he put in the claim, which the city ignored until publicity  
forced its hand and a ritual was born. The calf has also been 
claimed in 1956 and 1988 and at least once was turned over in the 
form of a roast beef dinner. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is wonderful,'' said Claiborne Pell. ``We don't have  
enough traditions of this sort, traditions handed down from the 
past.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As in the past, some of the Pells were not sure the payment was  
satisfactory. 
</P>
<P>
	``The calf is very handsome, but I'm not sure it's fat,'' said  
Mary Leigh Pell Whitmer of Fairfield, Conn. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pell children who thought Jessie was unbearably cute were  
glad to learn she was borrowed for the day from a farm and would be 
nobody's roast beef dinner. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
