<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gannett Bids $1.5B for Newsquest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- British regional newspaper group Newsquest PLC  
said Thursday that U.S. media company Gannett Co. had made a 
``serious and fair'' buyout offer of about $1.5 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Newsquest, which owns 63 daily and weekly newspapers across  
Britain, stopped short of urging shareholders to accept, however. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement, the Newsquest board said it believed ``the offer  
does not represent such a compelling proposal that it could give an 
outright recommendation to shareholders that it is absolutely in 
their best interests to accept.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, the offer has already been approved by shareholders  
owning 51.7 percent of the group, including Newsquest executive 
directors. Two investment groups, KKR and Cinven, are major 
stockholders. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the offer, Gannett valued Newsquest shares at about $7.40,  
compared with Wednesday's close of $6.68. 
</P>
<P>
	Several foreign companies have significant publishing holdings  
in the United States although American company holdings of overseas 
publishers are more rare. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the big foreign players here are Australia's News Corp.,  
which owns the Fox Network and the New York Post. 
</P>
<P>
	Germany's Bertelsmann owns the book publisher Random House and  
the magazines McCall's and Family Circle. Its entertainment arm 
owns numerous record labels including Arista and RCA. 
</P>
<P>
	Gannett owns USA Today and 73 other American daily newspapers  
with a daily circulation of more than 6.7 million, as well as USA 
Weekend and 21 TV stations, and also cable television systems. 
</P>
<P>
	Newsquest's publications including major regional newspapers,  
including the Northern Echo, based in Darlington, north England, 
the Oxford Mail, the Evening Argus in Brighton, south England, and 
Westmoreland Gazette, in the Lake District in north England. 
</P>
<P>
	Newsquest had a pretax profit of $204.3 million last year on  
sales of $483.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``Gannett is a major media company and the prospect of Newsquest  
becoming part of Gannett represents a great opportunity for 
Newsquest and its employees,'' Newsquest executive chairman James 
Brown said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gannett President Douglas H. McCorkindale said Newsquest was the  
``right opportunity to expand our international operations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The acceptance from 51.7 percent of shareholders is irrevocable  
unless a rival bidder offers more than $7.82 per share within seven 
days. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown said a counterbid was highly unlikely as since March the  
company had ``covered many possible buyers and at the end of the 
day Gannett offered the best price.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Newsquest, which has 5,000 employees, will keep its name and  
existing management, the announcement said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
