<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> CMGI May Buy Compaq's AltaVista </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Frustrated in its bid to forge an Internet  
identity through Lycos, an emerging online power is now eyeing 
AltaVista as a flagship for its stable of little-known Web 
properties. 
</P>
<P>
	CMGI Inc., which holds a stake in nearly 40 Internet businesses  
including Lycos, confirmed Thursday it has been talking with Compaq 
Computer Corp. about buying a controlling interest in AltaVista, a 
Lycos rival that offers an array of services and a portal to other 
Web destinations. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement, which came two days after the talks were  
disclosed by columnist Dan Dorfman on the JagNotes investment Web 
site, also said CMGI and Compaq might form a strategic alliance, 
suggesting that Compaq intends to retain a stake in AltaVista. 
</P>
<P>
	CMGI, based in Andover, Mass., declined to provide more details  
or to comment on a report Thursday in The Wall Street Journal 
saying talks to buy the remainder of Lycos had unraveled due to a 
personality clash among top management. 
</P>
<P>
	The source of that friction, of course, might be that it was  
CMGI, with an 18 percent interest in Lycos, which recently scuttled 
Lycos' merger agreement with USA Networks. 
</P>
<P>
	But despite its considerable muscle, which includes the wallop  
of minority backers Microsoft Corp. and Intel Corp., CMGI finds 
itself lacking an established lightning rod to draw visitors and 
direct them to other corners of its far-flung online empire. CMGI's 
holdings include stakes in Ancestry.com, CarParts.com, 
Furniture.com and Raging Bull, a financial investment forum. 
</P>
<P>
	``Part of what these deals are about is acquiring technology and  
money and ad revenues and Internet channels,'' said Jack Staff, 
chief economist for Zona Research. ``But the deals are also about 
acquiring highly specialized technical people in one fell swoop.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But although Compaq may provide a friendlier partner for CMGI  
than Lycos, AltaVista might not provide an Internet hub quite as 
effective as Lycos would. 
</P>
<P>
	While considered by many a superior search tool with which to  
navigate the Web, AltaVista hasn't enjoyed the huge popularity of 
fellow Web portals Yahoo!, Excite and Lycos. 
</P>
<P>
	Those three made their names by helping people sift through an  
ever-exploding number of Web sites for specific information or 
topics of interest. 
</P>
<P>
	Soon enough, however, those companies realized that the hordes  
of people passing through every day on the way to other Internet 
destinations might be valuable to advertisers if their visitors 
stuck around longer. 
</P>
<P>
	So to persuade people to stay, Yahoo! and the others have juiced  
up their Web sites with news, shopping, entertainment, free e-mail 
and chat rooms. 
</P>
<P>
	The results speak for themselves. According to the latest  
rankings from Media Metrix, Yahoo! was the most popular Web site in 
May with 31.1 million visitors. Including affiliated sites, Yahoo! 
placed third after America Online Inc. and Microsoft. 
</P>
<P>
	By contrast the Excite.com Web site placed eighth with 15.1  
million visitors in May, followed by Lycos.com with 14.9 million. 
AltaVista's Web site placed only 15th with 9.5 million visitors. 
</P>
<P>
	For Compaq, which issued a terse statement confirming the talks,  
a deal with CMGI would mark a sharp change of course for the 
computer maker, whose fortunes have spiraled downward since last 
year's acquisition of Digital Equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	The Houston-based company is now trying to chart a new direction  
after a rocky few months dominated by weak profits, layoff 
announcments and the ouster of top management. 
</P>
<P>
	But in the past five months alone, Compaq has announced plans to  
spin off AltaVista through a public stock sale and spent more than 
$500 million to buy online retailer Shopping.com and Zip2, an 
online guide to different cities. Both purchases were folded into 
AltaVista and would likely be included in any deal with CMGI. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
