<HEADLINE> Softbank, Yahoo Plan Toys on Web </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Softbank Corp. and Yahoo Japan Corp. will join six  
toy companies to sell toys over the Internet, the companies said 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The joint-venture company, E-shopping! Toys Corp., will be  
established in July. 
</P>
<P>
	Softbank will have a 52.5 percent stake in the venture, which  
will have capital of 200 million yen ($1.6 million). The second 
biggest partner, Japanese toy wholesaler Happinet Corp., will hold 
a 17.5 percent stake. Bandai Corp., the maker of Tamagotchi toys, 
also will be involved. 
</P>
<P>
	The venture is the second in recent weeks for Softbank that  
focuses on computer commerce. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this month, Softbank and Seven-Eleven Japan Co.  
announced they will form a joint venture to sell books online in 
Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	The Internet toy venture also involve Seven-Eleven Japan. In  
both businesses, Seven-Eleven will take payments for orders from 
customers who prefer not to use credit cards online. 
</P>
<P>
	Using the convenience store is designed to overcome problems  
that have kept computer commerce from becoming popular in Japan: 
the low level of credit card use and concerns about security. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, Softbank President Masayoshi Son confirmed that his  
company will establish a 230 billion yen ($1.89 billion) venture 
capital fund to invest in Internet start-ups. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 95 percent of the fund will be invested in U.S.  
companies, with the balance in Japanese firms. Softbank itself will 
supply 90 billion yen ($738 million) of the venture capital. 
</P>
<P>
	Softbank, a software wholesaler and computer-magazine publisher,  
has become increasingly involved in Internet businesses. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
