<HEADLINE> Snyder Spinning Off Health Care </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Marketing company Snyder Communications Inc.  
is spinning off its health care services business into a new 
publicly traded corporation. 
</P>
<P>
	The new company, Snyder Healthcare Services Inc., will be one of  
the world's largest providers of marketing services to 
pharmaceutical and medical companies, company officials said 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Its customers include Abbott Laboratories, Bausch &AMP; Lomb,  
Baxter, Bayer, Bristol-Myers-Squibb, Eli Lilly, Johnson &AMP; Johnson, 
Merck, Pfizer and Upjohn. 
</P>
<P>
	The change was made to create two independent businesses and  
dissipate confusion in investors' minds, said Daniel Snyder, 
chairman and chief executive of Snyder Communications and also the 
new owner of the Washington Redskins NFL team. ``This confusion is 
now removed completely,'' he said in a telephone interview. 
</P>
<P>
	Snyder Communications, based in Bethesda, Md., earned $22.8  
million last year on revenue of $815 million and has 9,400 
employees. Daniel Snyder founded the company in 1988 and took it 
public in 1996. It has grown in recent years through mergers with 
media and marketing companies. 
</P>
<P>
	The company, which sells market research and advertising  
campaigns tailored to specific audiences, has a roster of big 
clients including Bell Atlantic, British Telecom, Fleet Financial 
Group, GTE, IBM, McDonald's, Proctor &AMP; Gamble and Volkswagen. 
</P>
<P>
	As a subsidiary, Snyder Healthcare Services had revenue of  
$321.5 million in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the plan announced Wednesday, the separate Snyder  
Healthcare Services will trade on the Nasdaq Stock Market while 
Snyder Communications shares will continue to trade on the New York 
Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Eran Broshy, a partner in the Boston Consulting Group, was named  
chief executive officer of Snyder Healthcare Services. Daniel 
Snyder will remain as its chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	Snyder's $800 million offer to buy the Redskins was approved  
last month by the National Football League owners. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
