<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Help Wanted Advertising Rose in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Help-wanted advertising in major U.S. newspapers  
rose in May, and the nation's unemployment rate -- already at a 
nearly 70-year low -- could drop even farther this summer, according 
to a study released Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Conference Board, a private business research group, said  
its monthly help-wanted advertising index climbed to 89 last month. 
That is up two points from 87 in April, although it is below its 
reading of 91 a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The index is used as a non-governmental gauge of changes in  
local, regional and national job supply. 
</P>
<P>
	``Job growth slowed to a crawl in May,'' said Kenneth Goldstein,  
the Conference Board's economist. A net of 11,000 jobs were created 
in May, down sharply from 345,000 in April. 
</P>
<P>
	Goldstein expects job growth to stabilize at about 250,000 per  
month for the next several months. That could bring the nation's 
unemployment rate of 4.2 percent ``down to 4 percent, perhaps by 
Labor Day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fom March through May, help-wanted advertising fell in seven  
regions and rose in two. The biggest increase was in New England, 
up 20.8 percent. The steepest declines took place in the Mountain 
region, which includes Colorado, Arizona and Utah, down 10 percent; 
and East North Central region, including Illinois, Ohio, Michigan, 
Indiana and Wisconsin, down 9.9 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The seasonally adjusted advertising index, which stood at 100 in  
the base year of 1987, is derived from measuring the volume of 
employment ads in 51 major newspapers across the country each 
month. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
