<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Weather News Hurts Grains, Soybeans / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Soybean and grain futures prices fell in trading  
Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade amid forecasts for more 
favorable Midwest weather. 
</P>
<P>
	July soybean futures plummeted 13 cents a bushel.  
</P>
<P>
	Forecasters, who had been calling for unusually hot temperatures  
next week, now say that a high-pressure ridge in the Midwest has 
weakened. Updated forecasts called for scattered showers, which 
would be beneficial for crops. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn and spring wheat had risen in Wednesday's trading due to  
trader concern that hot, dry weather would damage newly planted 
crops. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures closed slightly lower Thursday, following the  
trend in corn and soybeans. Concern over the U.S. hard red winter 
wheat crop provided some support, limiting losses. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery fell 2 cents to $2.50 a bushel; July  
corn fell 3 cents to $2.14 1/2 a bushel; July oats fell 1 3/4 cents to 
$1.12 1/2 a bushel; and July soybeans fell 13 cents to $4.52 3/4 a 
bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, livestock and meat futures were mostly lower in  
trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	August live cattle fell 0.32 cent to 63.15 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle fell 0.43 cent to 77.12 cents a pound; August lean 
hogs fell 2.00 cents to 50.70 cents a pound; and August pork 
bellies fell 1.25 cent to 43.45 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 23:30:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Becker Knocks Out Seeded Kiefer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WIMBLEDON, England (AP) -- Boris Becker knows he doesn't own  
Wimbledon anymore. That doesn't mean he won't ask Pete Sampras for 
his keys back. 
</P>
<P>
	Three-time Wimbledon champion Becker, who made the All England  
Club seem like his own private establishment before five-time 
titlist Sampras came along, shrugged off the distractions of 
semiretirement on Thursday to charge into the third round of this 
year's championship. 
</P>
<P>
	He did it with a straight-set triumph over 15th-seeded Nicolas  
Kiefer, a fellow German Becker has barely spoken to since they 
clashed in a Davis Cup dispute. 
</P>
<P>
	A full house on Centre Court saw some vintage Becker, powering  
sledge-hammer serves and punching away volleys. The only thing they 
didn't get from the 31-year-old star, who first won Wimbledon at 
age 17 in 1985, was one of his trademark sprawling dives across the 
court. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was almost like I won the tournament, but unfortunately it  
was only the second round,'' Becker said after his 6-4, 6-2, 6-4 
victory over Kiefer. ``It was a great feeling to be back on Centre 
Court, and it brought the best out of me. 
</P>
<P>
	``I haven't played for a long time on it and to be able to come  
back after my first round to play perfect grass court tennis was 
very pleasing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On his return to Wimbledon after two years, Becker came back  
from two sets down in his first-round match against Britain's Miles 
Maclagan to win in five. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years ago, Becker said he'd played his last Wimbledon. Now  
he says this is definitely his last. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously the first round was much more than just a tennis  
match and, once I got that over with, I was very much as ease with 
myself and more relaxed today and, especially on Centre Court, 
which is my favorite court. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't say that this is my place anymore. I used to own it,  
but Pete Sampras had taken over the keys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Becker meets Australian teen-ager Lleyton Hewitt for a place in  
the last 16, and the 18-year-old rising star is delighted to share 
the stage with one of the biggest names in the sport. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be great. I suppose I'll get one of the big show  
courts now,'' Hewitt said after his 6-1, 6-4, 4-6, 6-4 victory over 
Karim Alami of Morocco. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's obviously playing great tennis to beat Kiefer in straight  
sets, and it's just a big thrill for me to be out there with Boris 
Becker.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Apart from serving eight double-faults, Becker made few mistakes  
on the court he used to call his ``living room.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kiefer had three break points in the match, but Becker saved all  
three with aces. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-time champion broke a 21-year-old opponent once  
considered his protege in the third game of the match, and Kiefer 
had to save three break points in his next service game to keep it 
at 3-2. 
</P>
<P>
	At 5-4, Becker found himself 0-30 down, but won the next four  
points to take the set. 
</P>
<P>
	Becker broke again in the third and seventh games of the second  
set. 
</P>
<P>
	Becker broke Kiefer in the fifth game of the third set, served  
two love games and, although Kiefer saved two match points, Becker 
earned a place in the third round when Kiefer hit a backhand return 
wide. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 15:00:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latest Developments in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Latest developments concerning Kosovo:  
</P>
<P>
	--The U.S. government puts up a $5 million reward for help in  
arresting and convicting anyone wanted by the U.N. war crimes 
tribunal for the Balkans. Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic is 
among those indicted. 
</P>
<P>
	--In the Kosovo city of Pec, fires level Serb homes and much of  
the city's Gypsy quarter. Local Serbs blame ethnic Albanians. 
</P>
<P>
	--The Yugoslav parliament rescinds the state of war it declared  
after NATO bombing began March 24. 
</P>
<P>
	--Deployment of 3,600 Russian peacekeepers is expected to begin  
as early as Friday alongside American, German and French soldiers. 
NATO's top civilian leader predicts coordination with the Russians 
will be as successful as it has been in Bosnia. 
</P>
<P>
	--Aid officials say the West will have to feed Kosovo this summer  
and on into the winter because the devastation and disruption of 
war have left the region unable to help itself. 
</P>
<P>
	--Ethnic Albanians thronged NATO's civilian and military leaders  
in Kosovo's capital of Pristina, welcoming them with cheers and 
tears of gratitude for the 78-day bombing campaign that forced out 
Yugoslav troops. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
