<DOCNO> APW19990624.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 13:10:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Candidates Take Iowa Poll Seriously </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Dan Quayle is lining up Indiana college  
students for an Iowa ``poll the nation will see.'' Lamar 
Alexander's camp says the straw poll could be the ``last 
opportunity'' for his struggling campaign. George W. Bush has 
enlisted interest groups to bus in backers. 
</P>
<P>
	The 12,000 or so activists who show up for the Iowa Republican  
straw poll Aug. 14 won't pick any delegates, but they could well 
narrow the field of serious candidates for the party's presidential 
nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will give some structure to the field, deciding who is a  
contender and who is a pretender,'' said Brian Kennedy, who runs 
former Tennessee Gov. Alexander's campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it is a do-or-die event for some candidates,'' said  
Greg Mueller, a consultant allied with publisher Steve Forbes. 
</P>
<P>
	The lengths candidates are going to are detailed in campaign  
memos leaked by rivals. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas Gov. Bush is tapping various trade organizations to bring  
in Iowans to increase his showing. 
</P>
<P>
	In a memo to students at Huntington College in Indiana, a Quayle  
supporter offers students from the former vice president's home 
state free travel to Ames, Iowa, 500 miles away, for the poll. 
</P>
<P>
	``All presidential candidates will be there and the Quayles want  
you to be there also to show our support,'' says the memo. 
</P>
<P>
	Only Iowans can vote, however, and state GOP executive director  
Dee Stewart said all IDs will be checked. Quayle spokesman Jonathan 
Baron said students would come as volunteer organizers, not voters. 
</P>
<P>
	Joseph Rodgers, a major Alexander supporter, sent out a  
fund-raising letter saying the campaign needs $1 million ``by the 
end of this month'' to compete in the straw poll. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the last opportunity we will have to give Lamar a  
chance to prove a lot of people wrong,'' Rodgers wrote on campaign 
letterhead. 
</P>
<P>
	With a large and unruly field seeking the GOP nomination,  
there's some hunger for clarity. Those who fare poorly could find 
attention hard to get and money scarce as the contenders move 
closer to February caucuses that open the presidential nominating 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	``The campaigns that finish in the top three are going to be the  
ones who are taken seriously as we move toward the caucus 
process,'' said Stewart. 
</P>
<P>
	The expectations game is under way, too.  
</P>
<P>
	Bush is high atop opinion polls and backed by much of the GOP  
establishment. But his aides initially sought to lower 
expectations, noting that rivals have been organizing in the state 
for months, if not years. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush himself shattered that.  
</P>
<P>
	``It will be a good test for our organization and it will be a  
good test for me,'' said Bush. ``I think we not only ought to 
compete, I think we ought to win the Ames straw poll.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Bush has the most to lose,'' said Kennedy. ``He's set the bar  
at 50 percent and if he doesn't do that he's given new life to his 
competitors.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The conventional wisdom holds that Iowa's caucuses and straw  
polls demand painstakingly built organizations. If Bush wins the 
straw poll so soon after jumping in, it will be yet another sign of 
his strength. 
</P>
<P>
	That's not lost on rivals.  
</P>
<P>
	``He clearly, basically, wants to end the race for the  
Republican nomination on Aug. 14,'' complained candidate Pat 
Buchanan. 
</P>
<P>
	While many eyes are on Bush, others face even greater risks.  
</P>
<P>
	Alexander has languished in the polls, but remains credible  
because he has enlisted a cadre of talented organizers and 
convinced many he has a solid field organization. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a lot of talk about what a great organization he has,  
but sooner or later it's put up or shut up,'' said Drake University 
political scientist Dennis Goldford. 
</P>
<P>
	The same could be said for others who have been quietly  
organizing. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are living off the land, but if they aren't able to come  
in in the top three, all of those campaigns go into cardiac 
arrest,'' Mueller said. 
</P>
<P>
	Others say the consequences won't be so dramatic. A similar  
straw poll in the last campaign saw Texas Sen. Phil Gramm tie 
eventual nominee Bob Dole, with no lasting damage to Dole. 
</P>
<P>
	``It ended up being a three-day story,'' said Quayle campaign  
chairman Kyle McSlarrow. ``I view it as one step in the process.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 14:50:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Labonte Looks To Keep on Rolling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Bobby Labonte isn't nervous about a few  
right turns getting in the way of his recent success. 
</P>
<P>
	Fresh off his second victory of the season, Labonte arrived in  
Northern California for the Save Mart/Kragen 350 on Sunday. In the 
rolling hills of the wine country, Sears Point Raceway is one of 
just two road courses on the NASCAR Winston Cup circuit. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not something I'm as comfortable with as going to  
Charlotte Motor Speedway, say,'' he said. ``But it is something 
that's really neat and I enjoy doing it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Labonte is in the midst of his best season ever. Along with his  
two wins, he has claimed four poles. He has 12 top-10 finishes, 
including consecutive top-fives in each of his last seven races. 
</P>
<P>
	That has put him in second place in the Winston Cup point  
standings, 89 behind Dale Jarrett. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been creeping up on this thing over the past couple  
years, finishing seventh in points, sixth in points, just getting 
closer and closer,'' Labonte said. ``It just seems like things are 
clicking a little bit better right now. It's team chemistry and 
teamwork.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His most recent win came last weekend, when he beat Jeff Gordon  
by six-car lengths in the Pocono 500. 
</P>
<P>
	Sears Point poses a special challenge. In addition to those  
somewhat unfamiliar right turns, Labonte has just two top-10 
finishes on the road course. Last year, he had his best showing, 
placing fourth. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got a lot of notes, of course. We go back and look at  
what we did last year, and the year before, and the year before, 
then compile it all together and don't do the thing that we did 
wrong, and try to do what we did right an improve upon it,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	He'll also be using a new road-course version of his Pontiac.  
The cars that have given him recent success on ovals won't be a 
factor. 
</P>
<P>
	``A road course is awful tough,'' he said. '' I'd be pretty  
ecstatic to win on a road course, but I'll take whatever I can get. 
'' 
</P>
<P>
	In San Francisco to draw attention to this weekend's race,  
Labonte greeted drivers who stopped at a local gas station. An 
invited ``pit crew'' pumped gas and cleaned windows. 
</P>
<P>
	He was greeted by a small but loyal contingent of fans, who  
quickly clued into what was happening and pulled their cars into 
the station for a chance to meet Labonte. 
</P>
<P>
	Lanette Lucia had arrived from her home in Tracy, Calif., three  
hours before the event just to make sure she could meet her 
favorite driver. Labonte signed her Interstate Batteries jacket as 
she caught the moment on videotape. 
</P>
<P>
	``He wrote on me! He wrote on me and I got to shake his hand!''  
she exclaimed. ``I'm so excited!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Labonte was as ``pumped'' as the fans.  
</P>
<P>
	``Hey, it's part of the deal,'' he said. ``We're awfully excited  
about what we're doing in NASCAR racing, and know that by doing 
what we're doing, we're helping the sport grow.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 15:50:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reno Readies New Prosecutor Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Attorney General Janet Reno said Thursday that  
the Justice Department will be ready to take on the job of 
appointing special prosecutors to investigate misconduct by high 
government officials when the independent counsel law expires next 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	Reno said the department is nearly finished crafting new rules  
it will follow in naming special investigators. ``Our regulations 
will be ready by July 1,'' she said at her weekly news briefing. 
</P>
<P>
	Barring any last-minute attempts to keep it alive, the  
independent counsel law, which spawned Kenneth Starr's 
investigation of President Clinton and 20 other probes of 
high-level officials over the past two decades, will expire June 
30. 
</P>
<P>
	A few lawmakers are drafting legislation to revive the law, but  
most believe the statute will be allowed to die. 
</P>
<P>
	One key Senate Republican has urged Congress to seize some  
authority over the naming of special prosecutors by making Justice 
Department rules for their appointment, conduct and removal subject 
to the approval of Congress and the president. 
</P>
<P>
	The department does not now need congressional approval to  
change its regulations. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., chairman of the Senate Governmental  
Affairs Committee, said Tuesday that he plans to introduce the 
legislation in the next week or two. 
</P>
<P>
	When asked to comment on the proposal, Reno said she wanted to  
work with Thompson and other lawmakers ``to address the concerns 
that have been raised,'' but asserted that appointing and removing 
special prosecutors should be left to the attorney general alone. 
</P>
<P>
	``The attorney general gets held responsible for it one way or  
another,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Under new rules crafted by the Justice Department, the attorney  
general would appoint a special prosecutor when he or she 
determines that the investigation of a top government official 
presents a conflict of interest for the department. 
</P>
<P>
	According to an outline of the new regulations submitted to a  
House subcommittee, the prosecutor would be subject to budgetary 
and investigative limitations that do not exist under the 
independent counsel law, including the following: 
</P>
<P>
	--An annual budget would be submitted for the attorney general's  
approval. 
</P>
<P>
	--A progress report would be required at the end of the first  
year. 
</P>
<P>
	--Some indictments might need the approval of the attorney  
general. 
</P>
<P>
	--The investigation would be limited to the issue that led to the  
appointment. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the expiring independent counsel law, prosecutors had  
broad powers and no limits on how much they could spend. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 07:30:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Morning Is Hot New Time Slot in TV </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Assigned to a 5:30 a.m. newscast on New York's  
WNBC-TV, anchorman Maurice DuBois thought, only half-jokingly, that 
it was ``the end of the world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Who was going to watch him at an hour only farmers could love?  
</P>
<P>
	Plenty of people, much to his surprise. Early morning represents  
the new -- and perhaps only -- boom time for television viewership as 
programmers wake up to the fact that more Americans are climbing 
out of bed early these days. 
</P>
<P>
	Local news broadcasts are coming on earlier and earlier and more  
people are tuning in. A little later, at 7 a.m., ABC, CBS and NBC 
news shows are getting the special attention of network executives 
who suddenly see them as cash cows. 
</P>
<P>
	America is becoming a nation of early risers, as people get a  
jump on the morning commute, work out in a gym or get the kids off 
to school. A study by the National Sleep Foundation this year found 
51 percent of Americans say they get up at 6 a.m. or earlier, an 
increase of 5 percent over 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a whole sociological shift,'' says early riser Jeff  
Zucker, executive producer of NBC's ``Today'' show. ``We see it in 
the way people are getting their news.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This spring, for the first time, more people watched the first  
half-hour of ``Today'' than one of the evening news programs, in 
this case ``CBS Evening News.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As recently as a decade ago, many local stations ran 30 minutes,  
maybe an hour, of local news before the network morning show. Some 
didn't even bother. That's changed. 
</P>
<P>
	A study of TV stations two years ago found that the  
fastest-growing time of day for viewership was 5:30 a.m., says Bob 
Papper, telecommunications professor at Ball State University in 
Muncie, Ind. He suspects that 5 a.m. has now supplanted that. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know if any stations are doing 4:30 news,'' Papper  
says, ``but I can guarantee that some are thinking about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The flip side, he says, is that ratings for local newscasts  
starting at 11 p.m. are slipping as people go to bed earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Nielsen Media Research has no national statistics to measure  
early morning viewership, since most of the programming is turned 
over to local stations. But some of the regional trends are as 
eye-opening as a strong cup of coffee. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York in 1990, Nielsen found 772,203 households had TV  
sets on at 6 a.m. By early 1999, that number had gone up to 1.6 
million, a 120 percent increase. Viewership during other parts of 
the day, particularly prime-time, has slipped during the same 
period. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, WNBC-TV expanded its morning news show to 90 minutes,  
starting at 5:30 a.m. In September, the news will start at 5 a.m. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you build it, they will come,'' says Paula Madison, WNBC-TV  
vice president and news director. ``If we air a local newscast 
early, we find there is an audience.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boston's WBZ-TV, a CBS affiliate, debuted a three-hour morning  
show starting at 5 a.m. a year ago, after its research showed this 
was the best time of day in which to invest, spokeswoman Michele 
Walsh says. 
</P>
<P>
	It's not clear whether these stations are responding to a demand  
or creating one. Why didn't they try this before? 
</P>
<P>
	``It might be something as simple as we didn't think of it,''  
says Phyllis McGrady, the ABC executive who oversees ``Good Morning 
America.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McGrady, who worked on the show in the 1980s and recently  
returned, has noticed a difference in the audience. The morning 
shows used to be softer, considered strictly women's territory, but 
are now much newsier, she said. More men are watching. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're more in the habit of turning on the TV generally,'' Ball  
State's Papper says. ``Whether they are watching it is another 
issue. Maybe they're just listening to it, using it like a radio.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For TV executives, this trend has opened an important new source  
of revenue. It's virgin territory: Local stations can now sell ads 
for time periods not really used before. 
</P>
<P>
	It's the same bright financial picture at the networks. Last  
month, when advertisers bought commercial time for the upcoming 
fall shows, all three network morning shows saw sharp increases in 
advertising revenues. 
</P>
<P>
	At a time the networks are scrambling to make money, ``Today''  
racked up an impressive $100 million in profits for NBC last year. 
That's why ABC and CBS are investing heavily to cut in to NBC's 
dominance for that time period. 
</P>
<P>
	Diane Sawyer and Charles Gibson were brought in as ``Good  
Morning America'' hosts in January, and Bryant Gumbel starts at CBS 
in the fall. Both networks are also spending millions on new 
Manhattan studios. 
</P>
<P>
	``As prime-time television struggles for its identity,'' NBC's  
Zucker says, ``I believe the most competitive time slot in 
television is not 7 to 9 p.m., but 7 to 9 a.m.'' 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 20:08:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clapton Auctions Guitars for Charity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Eric Clapton parted with 100 stringed beauties  
Thursday, including a beloved Fender guitar he called ``Brownie'' 
that went for a record $497,500 at a charity auction. 
</P>
<P>
	In all, the Christie's sale generated $5 million for a Caribbean  
drug and alcohol clinic the rocker founded in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Clapton used ``Brownie,'' a 1956 sunburst Fender, to record his  
hit ``Layla.'' He played the guitar in other recording sessions and 
in concert. The amount paid for it -- by an unidentified telephone 
bidder -- surpassed the previous record paid at auction for a guitar 
-- $320,000 for one owned by Jimi Hendrix. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't believe it. I am totally overwhelmed,'' Clapton said  
in a statement released by Christie's after the sale. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he wanted to ``say thank you on behalf of all the  
patients who will get free treatment as a result of this sale.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clapton did not attend the auction.  
</P>
<P>
	Actor Michael J. Fox, bidding by telephone, bought a 1949  
Gibson-125 for $36,800 and a circa 1930s National Duolian for 
$42,500. Other buyers included Michael Malone, a Seattle music 
executive, and a Hard Rock Hotel. 
</P>
<P>
	Most other buyers were not identified.  
</P>
<P>
	In addition to ``Brownie,'' Clapton sold a 1954 Fender  
Stratocaster for $211,500 and a 1974 Martin 000-28 for $173,000. 
Both were widely used for recording and stage work as Clapton rose 
to stardom during the 1970s. 
</P>
<P>
	A rare, 1958 Gibson Explorer with a solid-body design went for  
$134,500 and a red, 1991 Gibson Firebird given to Clapton by a fan 
went for $39,100. 
</P>
<P>
	A Christie's spokeswoman would not comment on reports that  
Clapton may have intended to secretly bid on at least one of his 
guitars after having a change of heart about parting with it. None 
of the buyers were identified by the auction house. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 20:08:46 </DATE_TIME>
