<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NASA Launches Ultraviolet Telescope </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- A NASA ultraviolet telescope  
rocketed into orbit Thursday on a three-year quest to learn what 
the universe was like moments after creation. 
</P>
<P>
	The Far Ultraviolet Spectroscopic Explorer, better known as  
Fuse, blasted off aboard an unmanned Delta rocket. An hour later, 
it reached its destination: a 480-mile-high orbit from which it 
will peer into the corners of the Milky Way and beyond. 
</P>
<P>
	Johns Hopkins University developed the telescope for NASA and  
will now control it. 
</P>
<P>
	Fuse will measure the abundance of deuterium, a heavy hydrogen  
created along with the rest of the universe in the Big Bang 12 
billion or more years ago. Every day, deuterium is consumed by 
stars and converted into helium. 
</P>
<P>
	By determining how much deuterium still exists and how much is  
regularly destroyed, astronomers can figure out the original makeup 
of the universe. 
</P>
<P>
	``Deuterium is a cosmic fossil,'' said Warren Moos, the lead  
scientist for the project at Johns Hopkins. ``If we knew the 
primordial abundance of deuterium, if we knew that, then we could 
figure out the average abundance of ordinary nuclear matter, the 
ordinary matter that makes up oceans, that makes up people, that 
makes up stars.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The telescope's observations, expected to begin in about three  
months after the instrument is checked out and fine-tuned, also 
should help explain how stars and galaxies evolve and how the gas 
between galaxies changes over time. 
</P>
<P>
	Fuse will expand on ultraviolet observations by NASA's  
Copernicus observatory, launched in 1972, as well as the Hubble 
Space Telescope and small instruments occasionally flown on the 
space shuttle. 
</P>
<P>
	The $214 million mission will be operated entirely by Johns  
Hopkins, which also designed and made the 18-foot, 3,000-pound 
telescope. It is the most involved a university has ever been in a 
NASA mission. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
