<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> EU, Latin America, Caribbean Talk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- Leaders from the 15 European Union  
nations are trekking to Rio de Janeiro for a summit with almost 
three dozen Latin American and Caribbean nations in pursuit of 
closer political ties and -- a fuzzier, more distant prospect -- free 
trade. 
</P>
<P>
	The stakes are rather substantial, as the EU accounts for 12  
percent of Latin American exports and 17 percent of its imports. 
For many countries, the EU is the second-largest trading partner 
after the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The Europeans face a traditional bind in these discussions: They  
would love more trade, but worry about cheap imports, especially 
agricultural imports. 
</P>
<P>
	South Americans, led by giants Brazil and Argentina, want to  
sell more grain and meat to Europe and will likely insist on 
discussing farm exports at the two-day summit, which opens Monday. 
If the EU doesn't want free trade with this region, Brazilians say, 
the United States does. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Europeans say they won't be dragged into a race with  
Washington, which seeks a Pan-American free trade area by 2005. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not competing with ... hemispheric negotiations on free  
trade which have their own logic,'' EU Latin American Affairs 
Commissioner Manuel Marin said ahead of the summit. 
</P>
<P>
	The draft of an economic communique, a copy of which has been  
obtained by The Associated Press, speaks of a ``strategic 
partnership,'' based on, among other things, respect for democracy 
and human rights, sustainable development and a determination to 
stamp out trade in illegal drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, it condemns Washington for legislation punishing Europeans  
for trading with Cuba, whose president, Fidel Castro, is expected 
in Rio, too. 
</P>
<P>
	On continent-to-continent free trade, however, the draft is  
noncommittal. ``It is tough to come to a meaningful free trade 
because Latin America and the Caribbean are vast regions with 
enormous economic disparities,'' said one EU official, who asked 
not to be named. 
</P>
<P>
	A decade after the crumbling of communism, Cuba remains an  
outsider. Latin America has at least four economic alliances of 
which Mercosur -- Brazil, Argentina, Uruguay, Paraguay and 
associates Chile and Bolivia -- is the most advanced. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, poor Caribbean nations get special treatment. The  
Europeans reward their banana exports by punishing exports from 
U.S. multinationals, such as Chiquita and Dole Foods, in Latin 
nations with a trade regime the World Trade Organization has ruled 
illegal. 
</P>
<P>
	In Rio, the EU and the Mercosur nations are expected to announce  
they will open free trade talks. But France and Spain, fearing 
cheap imports, have set stringent conditions: Cereals, beef and 
sugar have been excluded. 
</P>
<P>
	Talks on tariff cuts and services won't start until mid-2001 and  
an overall deal cannot be concluded until global trade talks, under 
World Trade Organization auspices, have been completed. The WTO 
talks open in November and may last years. 
</P>
<P>
	An EU-Mercosur free trade arrangement would be implemented over  
a 10-year period. The gain in trade, according to the EU executive 
Commission, would be worth $6 billion a year to the Europeans and 
$5 billion to the Mercosur nations, significant amounts compared to 
current trade figures. 
</P>
<P>
	EU figures show capital flows to Latin American nations reached  
$73 billion in 1997, up from $26 billion two years earlier. Direct 
European investments in Latin America doubled from 1996 to 1997, 
going to $17 billion with Spain accounting for 33 percent, followed 
by Britain (20 percent) and France (14 percent). 
</P>
<P>
	EU exports to Latin America reached $52.4 billion in 1997,  
double the 1987 amount, but well above EU imports of $38.1 billion. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
