<HEADLINE> New ABA Plans To Start Play in Jan. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- The red-white-and-blue balls of the American  
Basketball Association may be bouncing again in 12 cities next 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	The new league, known as ABA 2000, unveiled plans for a 40-game  
schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	Indianapolis will be the headquarters, although organizers say  
they have no plans to locate a franchise here. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been asked to compete with the Indiana Pacers, and we  
said, `No, we live here and we're Indiana Pacer fans''', said 
Indianapolis broadcasting executive Joe Newman, one of the league's 
founders. ``We're not looking to put a team here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Newman said the league will use the red-white-and-blue  
basketball made popular by the old ABA, which disbanded in 1976 and 
sent four current NBA teams in the league. 
</P>
<P>
	Newman said one of the unique aspects of the league is that more  
than 50 percent of its ownership will be African-Americans with 
diversified backgrounds in sports, entertainment and business. 
</P>
<P>
	It plans to have a New York team based on Long Island. The  
league declined to identify owners of the 12 franchises, which it 
said would include teams in Chicago, Anaheim, Calif.; Jacksonville, 
Fla.; Tampa, Fla.; Pittsburgh; Raleigh-Durham, N.C.; New Orleans, 
the Tidewater area of Virginia; Hartford, Conn., Nashville and 
Memphis, Tenn. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
