<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Russians Expected in Kosovo Soon  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The 3,600 Russian troops expected to arrive in  
Kosovo as early as tomorrow are being welcomed by NATO officials, 
but those officials also acknowledge problems may arise. NATO 
officials say that discussions are now under way on how best to use 
the Russian contingent. The forces will operate in separate sectors 
controlled by the United States, French and German troops. Army 
Gen. Wesley Clark, the top NATO commander, said today the 3,600 
Russians will join 55,000 troops already committed to the Kosovo 
Force, or KFOR. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Puts Up $5M War Crimes Reward  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The State Department announced today a reward  
of up to $5 million for information leading to the arrest and 
conviction of persons -- including Yugoslav President Slobodan 
Milosevic -- wanted for war crimes in Bosnia and Yugoslavia. Also 
being sought are former Bosnian Serb leaders Radovan Karadzic and 
Ratko Mladic. Milosevic and four Yugoslav colleagues were indicted 
last month for crimes in the Kosovo conflict. The indictments 
against Karadzic and Mladic were handed down in connection with the 
massacre of 6,000 Bosnian Muslims in 1995. 

</P>
<P>
	Poll: Republicans Have Moral Edge  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Though President Clinton was strongly  
supported by the American public during the impeachment process, a 
bipartisan poll released today suggests that concern about the 
nation's moral leadership is growing. That focus may help 
Republicans during the 2000 campaign, the poll indicated. 
Republicans have about a 20 percentage-point edge over Democrats 
when asked which party best represents the values of faith in God, 
personal responsibility, ethics and honesty and knowing right from 
wrong, according to the Battleground Poll. 

</P>
<P>
	Panel: Nuclear Cleanup Inadequate  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Despite billions spent so far, current  
technology is not up to the job of cleaning contaminated soil and 
water at the Energy Department's nuclear weapons sites, a 
scientific advisory panel reported today. ``The technology that 
often is used to remediate contaminated sites is simply ineffective 
and unable to accomplish the massive job that needs to be done,'' 
said C. Herb Ward, chairman of the National Research Council 
committee that studied the issue. The department has spent between 
$5.6 billion and $7.2 billion per year on environmental management 
over the past several years, the report also indicated. 

</P>
<P>
	House OKs Flag Amendment  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House today voted to amend the  
Constitution to protect the safeguard the flag, but the measure is 
likely to die in the Senate. The 305-124 vote was 19 more than the 
two-thirds needed, with supporters saying the flag can be 
safeguarded without violating free speech rights. This was the 
third time in four years that the House has passed the measure. If 
the Senate does pass the amendment, it must also be ratified by 
three-fourths of the states. 

</P>
<P>
	CompUSA in Major Reorganization  
</P>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- With personal computer prices on the decline,  
CompUSA will reduce its reliance on PC sales and turn its focus to 
consumer electronics, packing its stores with everything from video 
cameras to high-tech toys. The changes are part of a major 
reorganization announced today by Dallas-based CompUSA, which has 
struggled recently with sagging profits. The company will also 
slash 1,000 to 1,500 jobs, and it will close four stores. 

</P>
<P>
	Coke Recall Cost Estimate: $60M  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The world's leading bottler of Coca-Cola  
beverages estimates the price tag of the European soft-drink health 
scare is at least $60 million. Coca-Cola Enterprises Inc. said 
today that about 14 million cases, made up of 24 eight-ounce 
servings, were affected by the product recall in Belgium. Besides 
the $60 million one-time-only pretax expense of the recall, the 
bottling company said it expects reduced sales and lower operating 
profits and earnings per share in the second quarter as a result of 
the health scare. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends 132.03 Lower  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks sank today as worries over interest rates  
spread to the outlook for second-quarter corporate earnings. The 
Dow Jones industrial average ended down 132.03 at 10,534.83, the 
fourth-straight decline for the blue-chip index. On the NYSE, 
losers led gainers 1,988-953. The Nasdaq fell 44.04 to 2,554.08. 

</P>
<P>
	Nelson, Marsh Lead Senior Players  
</P>
<P>
	DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) -- An eagle that was almost a double eagle  
helped Larry Nelson tie Australian Graham Marsh for the first-round 
lead today in the Senior Players Championship. Both opened at 
6-under-par 66 over the TPC of Michigan, one stroke better than 
Hale Irwin. Six players were at 68, including George Archer and 
Vincente Fernandez. Jim Albus, who won this tournament in 1991, was 
among five at 69. 

</P>
