<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 12:30 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	House Votes Against Flag Burning  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- For the third consecutive Congress, the House  
voted to amend the Constitution to allow legislation that would ban 
desecration of the flag. The 305-124 vote today was a comfortable 
19 above the two-thirds needed for a constitutional amendment. It 
moves the focus to the Senate, which in the past has resisted what 
supporters say is needed to protect the nation's symbol but 
opponents argue would be an infringement of First Amendment free 
speech rights. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton To Revive Domestic Agenda  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Returning to political battles after the  
conflict in Kosovo, President Clinton will use a speech at 
Georgetown University tomorrow to try to revive his domestic 
agenda, from Medicare and Social Security proposals to an increase 
in the minimum wage. Spokesman Joe Lockhart said today that Clinton 
will also open a new campaign to tighten gun control and adopt a 
patients' bill of rights. A centerpiece of Clinton's program is a 
plan to provide prescription benefits for the elderly under 
Medicare -- a new proposal that will cost billions of dollars. 
Republicans are planning their own proposal but with less generous 
benefits. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Commander Cheered in Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO commander Gen. Wesley Clark  
said today he believes the horrors being uncovered in Kosovo 
provide clear justification for the alliance's punishing bombing 
campaign. ``What you see here is the magnitude of the horror that 
required NATO action,'' said Clark, who was greeted by a cheering 
crowd as he accompanied NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana on 
their first visit to Kosovo. He was referring to mounting evidence 
of mass graves and atrocities found by peacekeepers and forensic 
specialists in the province. 

</P>
<P>
	House GOP Offer 'E-Contract' Agenda  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Republicans have introduced an  
``e-contract'' agenda aimed at promoting the growth of American 
high tech industries through measures to reduce government taxes 
and regulations. ``We believe a cutting edge society needs a 
cutting edge agenda,'' House Majority Leader Dick Armey said 
yesterday. The agenda includes tax cuts that promote investment and 
research, removing barriers to Internet commerce, and reining in 
excessive federal regulations. House Democratic leader Dick 
Gephardt of Missouri said the package is motivated by the GOP 
desire to win a bigger share of the high tech industry's political 
contributions. 

</P>
<P>
	19 Million Pool Toys Recalled  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government today said it is recalling more  
than 19 million pool ``dive sticks'' because they can impale 
children who land on them. Dive sticks are hard, plastic 
cylinder-shaped objects that stand upright on the bottom of pools 
so children can dive down and retrieve them. The Consumer Product 
Safety Commission recommends that parents throw the toys away. The 
commission also said it is recalling an infant carrier because of 
the danger a child could fall out, and some new Star Wars 
lightsabers because they may cause burns to their users. 

</P>
<P>
	China Praises Departing U.S. Envoy  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- China praised departing U.S. Ambassador James  
Sasser today for promoting relations between the two countries, but 
criticized U.S. handling of an investigation into NATO's bombing of 
the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade. Sasser's 3 1/2-year tenure began and 
ended with crises. He arrived during tensions over Taiwan, as 
Beijing launched missiles near the island and Washington responded 
by sending in aircraft carriers. Sasser, who spent four days in May 
trapped inside the walled U.S. Embassy compound by angry mobs, is 
due to leave next week. 

</P>
<P>
	1 Dead, 21 Hurt in French Bus Crash  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- A bus carrying a group of French and U.S.  
schoolchildren crashed into a tree today in eastern France, killing 
the driver and injuring 21 people, including seven Americans from 
Michigan. The accident occurred in Orconte, about 115 miles east of 
Paris, when the driver, who was killed, lost control of the 
vehicle, police said. Thirteen French children from the Vosges 
mountain region and seven American students aged 10-11 from Grand 
Rapids, Mich., were hospitalized. Three of the Americans were in 
serious condition, the U.S. consulate said. 

</P>
