<DOCNO> APW19990624.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 10:40:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Holbrooke Appears at Final Hearing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Richard Holbrooke, President Clinton's nominee  
to be U.N. ambassador, defended his negotiations with Slobodan 
Milosevic on Thursday, saying he was trying ``to avoid war and 
bring peace.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Negotiating with the Yugoslav president ``isn't fun. This isn't  
bridge or tennis,'' the often-blunt veteran diplomat told the 
Senate Foreign Relations Committee. ``This is tough slogging.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Holbrooke, architect of the 1995 peace accords for Bosnia and a  
frequent emissary to Milosevic before the NATO airstrikes, was 
expected to win easy Senate confirmation to the long-vacant post at 
the United Nations. 
</P>
<P>
	This likelihood was signaled by the committee chairman himself,  
Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., who pointedly called Holbrooke ``Mr. 
Ambassador.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't hesitate to call you that, now,'' Helms told  
Holbrooke, the sole witness at a hearing that focused largely on 
U.S. Balkans policy and Holbrooke's role. 
</P>
<P>
	Helms scheduled a committee vote on Holbrooke for next  
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Appearing at his third and final Senate confirmation hearing,  
Holbrooke defended his relationship with Milosevic after Helms 
noted that Holbrooke had ``spent more time with ... Milosevic than 
anyone else in this administration.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We are neither friends nor partners,'' Holbrooke said. He  
characterized Milosevic as ``evil.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But he said he ``no regrets'' negotiating with Milosevic, even  
though the Yugoslav leader had pulled the rug out from under the 
United States on several occasions. 
</P>
<P>
	``The highest goal here was to avoid war and bring peace,''  
Holbrooke said. 
</P>
<P>
	But he said he couldn't conceive of an American negotiating with  
Milosevic again, particularly in light of Milosevic's indictment as 
a war criminal by an international tribunal. 
</P>
<P>
	``The tribunal did the right thing,'' Holbrooke said. ``He's  
been indicted. He should face trial.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked to draw comparisons between Bosnia and Kosovo, Holbrooke  
cited a series of mistakes he said were made in regard to Bosnia. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he ``deeply regretted'' that President Clinton had set  
two deadlines for removing U.S. peacekeepers from Bosnia after the 
1995 peace agreement -- deadlines that were missed and eventually 
had to be discarded. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will not repeat that mistake'' with Kosovo, he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Holbrooke said he also regretted that the West did not move  
quickly in bringing to justice Radovan Karadzic and Gen. Ratko 
Mladic, wartime civilian and military leaders of the Bosnian Serbs 
who have been indicted as war criminals. 
</P>
<P>
	Furthermore, he said NATO should have acted more aggressively  
back in 1991 when it appeared that Milosevic was consolidating his 
Serb-based power in the aftermath of the breakup of the former 
Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Holbrooke said that on the whole, U.S. Bosnia policy has  
been a success. ``Not one NATO soldier was killed or wounded from 
hostile action in Bosnia,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Holbrooke, an investment banker, is a former assistant secretary  
of state and ambassador to Germany. He has served as the 
administration's unpaid special envoy on the Balkans. 
</P>
<P>
	He negotiated the 1995 peace agreement with Milosevic in Dayton,  
Ohio, that ended the war in Bosnia. 
</P>
<P>
	He also negotiated an abortive cease-fire in Kosovo with  
Milosevic last October, and was the last Western diplomat Milosevic 
saw before NATO airstrikes began on March 24. 
</P>
<P>
	Holbrooke made a last-ditch effort to get Milosevic to go along  
with NATO demands on March 23. Looking Milosevic in the eye, 
Holbrooke said he told the Yugoslav leader that NATO bombing would 
be ``swift, severe and sustained.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said Milosevic said he knew that the United States would bomb  
his country -- and that nothing could be done about it. Milosevic 
then asked, ``I wonder if we will see each other again,'' Holbrooke 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Holbrooke told the panel that Milosevic, by his actions, all but  
guaranteed that such a meeting would not take place. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite a year's delay in the confirmation hearings, most of it  
caused by lengthy ethics investigations by the administration, 
Holbrooke seemed headed toward easy confirmation both in the 
committee and by the full Senate. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 11:30:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Koo Koo Roo Director Indicted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A former director of the restaurant company  
Koo Koo Roo Inc. was indicted by a grand jury on four counts of 
securities fraud involving allegations of insider trading. 
</P>
<P>
	The indictment was issued Tuesday, the same day Donald B. Wohl  
settled a complaint by the Securities and Exchange Commission 
concerning the same trading, the U.S. attorney's office said 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	If convicted on the four counts of security fraud, Wohl could be  
sentenced to up to 40 years in prison and be fined $4 million, said 
Assistant U.S. Attorney Paul J. Watford. 
</P>
<P>
	Wohl, 68, of Los Angeles, purchased 50,000 shares of the  
restaurant company's stock March 27, 1998, when he learned former 
Ford and Chrysler executive Lee Iacocca was going to be appointed 
acting chairman of Koo Koo Roo. 
</P>
<P>
	Announcement of the appointment was to be withheld until a  
contract termination was completed with the outgoing chairman, 
Kenneth Berg, the government said. 
</P>
<P>
	Three days later, when Iacocca's appointment was announced, the  
stock price doubled. Wohl sold 45,000 shares of the stock that same 
day, yielding a trading profit of $65,280, Watford said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wohl's attorney, Harriet Leva, said Wednesday that Wohl  
``categorically denies any intentional wrongdoing.'' She said he 
did not violate the law on insider trading, which she said involves 
acting on internal knowledge of a company -- knowing the information 
has not been made public. 
</P>
<P>
	``He will admit that he did trade Koo Koo Roo stock on March 27  
and March 30. But when he bought that stock he believed honestly, 
in good faith, that the news about the change in Koo Koo Roo 
management had already become public.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Without admitting wrongdoing, Wohl agreed to pay about $133,000  
in SEC-imposed penalties. The SEC also alleged that Wohl violated a 
1978 order that barred him from acting as an investment adviser. 
</P>
<P>
	Wohl resigned from the Koo Koo Roo board in late 1998, about six  
months before Koo Koo Roo merged with Prandium Inc., based in 
Irvine, said a Prandium spokesman, Robert L. Carl, who would not 
comment on the indictment. 
</P>
<P>
	Iacocca, famed for the Ford Mustang success in the 1960s and the  
financial rebound at Chrysler, has since left the restaurant 
company to head an electronic bicycle concern. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 20:40:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Mariners' Tax Money Request Denied </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- The Seattle Mariners' request for more tax money  
to pay for their new ballpark was rejected Thursday by the state 
panel overseeing construction of Safeco Field. 
</P>
<P>
	The resolution proposed by William P. Gerberding was adopted 6-0  
without discussion by the Washington State Public Facilities 
District board. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the development agreement signed by the Mariners and the  
board in 1996, a disputed claim may be submitted to nonbinding 
mediation. If that fails to resolve the issue, there is a provision 
for submitting some disputes to binding arbitration. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is the position of the PFD that this is not an appropriate  
issue for mediation and we hope the Mariners do not wish to 
litigate,'' the board's resolution said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mariners, who said their are considering a lawsuit to force  
mediation, want another $60 million to help cover $100 million in 
overruns. 
</P>
<P>
	Club officials have argued that higher-than-anticipated revenue  
from special restaurant, bar, car rental and stadium admission 
taxes enacted to finance the $517 million project should be applied 
to the overruns. 
</P>
<P>
	The County Council earmarked the extra tax revenue for early  
repayment of $336 million in stadium bonds and unanimously opposed 
further spending. 
</P>
<P>
	The 45,600-seat ballpark, equipped with a retractable roof,  
opens July 15. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 17:21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  France Lifts Coke Production Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DUNKIRK, France (AP) -- France followed the lead of Belgium and  
lifted a ban on Coca-Cola products Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The recall that followed hundreds of reports of illnesses by  
people who drank Coca-Cola products is estimated to have cost at 
least $60 million, and could be much higher. But Coca-Cola's main 
bottler said ``the crisis is over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Production in France will resume early Friday, said Henry A.  
Schimberg, president and chief operating offer of Coca-Cola 
Enterprises Inc., the world's leading bottler and distributor of 
Coca-Cola. 
</P>
<P>
	Production had been expected to resume Thursday in Belgium, but  
was delayed as Coca-Cola worked to assure compliance with strict 
sanitary conditions imposed by the government on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``In Belgium we are taking very deliberate steps to ensure  
perfect quality. Production will begin in a matter of days,'' said 
Coca-Cola spokeswoman Jennifer McCollum. 
</P>
<P>
	Since June 9, there had been 249 cases of illnesses reported in  
Belgium by people who drank Coca-Cola products. In France, hundreds 
of people who drank from cans produced in Dunkirk had reported 
illnesses in the same period. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, France ended its limited ban on production of  
Coca-Cola canned products here, saying government tests determined 
there no longer is a public health threat. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today, it seems that the product and its packaging are safe,  
so the sales can start up again,'' Finance Minister Dominique 
Strauss-Kahn said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dominique Reiniche, president of Coca-Cola France, said the  
illnesses were caused by odors stemming from traces of disinfectant 
on the bottom of some cans. 
</P>
<P>
	She said the disinfectant, containing carbolic acid, or phenol,  
was used to clean pallets on which the cans were standing at the 
bottling plant. She said the contamination was due to ``logistical 
malfunctioning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Belgium announced on Wednesday it would allow Coca-Cola to  
resume operations at factories in Antwerp and Ghent, if new 
production safeguards are imposed. Without determining the cause of 
hundreds of illnesses reported in Belgium, the country's top health 
official termed them an accident. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today, the crisis is over and we're happy with the French  
government's decision,'' Schimberg told a news conference at the 
Dunkirk bottling plant in northern France. 
</P>
<P>
	Reiniche acknowledged that Coca-Cola's image in Europe has been  
tarnished and said the company would launch a promotion campaign in 
France and Belgium this weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Douglas Ivester, Coca-Cola Co.'s chairman, has said it will take  
about two weeks to build up full distribution. 
</P>
<P>
	Coca-Cola Enterprises said the cost of the recalling 14 million  
cases, each containing 24 eight-ounce servings, was about $60 
million. In addition, it said there would be lost sales. 
</P>
<P>
	But the bottler said it was confident the health scare would not  
hurt financial results after this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Coca-Cola Co., which owns 40 percent of Coca-Cola Enterprises,  
was ``still working on our assessment'' of the costs of the crisis, 
spokesman Rob Baskin said Thursday in Atlanta. ``It's premature for 
us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In trading Thursday on the New York Stock Exchange, Coca-Cola  
Enterprises fell 2.1 percent, or by 68 3/4 cents, at $31.68 3/4 a share, 
while Coca-Cola was up 1.5 percent, or by 93 3/4 cents, at $62.68 3/4 a 
share. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 17:21:01 </DATE_TIME>
