<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cowens Back To Talk With Cavs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- The Cleveland Cavaliers might be closer to  
hiring a head coach than they want to admit. 
</P>
<P>
	Dave Cowens arrived in town Wednesday for his second interview  
with the team, which is trying to keep its coaching search a 
secret. 
</P>
<P>
	With less than a week remaining before the NBA draft, the Cavs  
are finding it difficult to hide their prospective coaching 
candidates from the media. 
</P>
<P>
	That difficulty heightened when the 6-foot-9, red-headed former  
Boston Celtics center and coach of the Charlotte Hornets was 
spotted at Cleveland Hopkins International Airport. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm really thrilled and hope everything works out,'' Cowens  
told WKYC-TV upon arrival. ``I'm just happy to be considered for 
the position.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cowens appears to be the front-runner in a search the Cavs have  
conducted without much fanfare. Cowens was reportedly in for an 
initial interview with new Cleveland general manager Jim Paxson 
last week, but didn't get to meet with owner Gordon Gund. 
</P>
<P>
	A second visit seems to indicate the Cavs could be close to  
signing Cowens, who resigned unexpectedly as coach of the Charlotte 
Hornets last March. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to do it right,'' Gund said following a news  
conference for former GM Wayne Embry, elected Wednesday to the 
Basketball Hall of Fame. ``That's why it's taking time. We want to 
do this right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Embry, who earlier this month was replaced by Paxson, was  
elected to the Hall of Fame along with Kevin McHale and John 
Thompson. All three played on NBA championship teams with the 
Celtics, as did Cowens. 
</P>
<P>
	Paxson, who was to meet with the media today to discuss next  
week's NBA draft, didn't want to go into much detail about his 
coaching search. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let's just say we're continuing and making some progress,''  
Paxson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cowens, 50, and Minnesota assistant Randy Wittman are believed  
to be the only candidates brought in so far for interviews. 
</P>
<P>
	Gund, in New York earlier this week as a member of a special  
committee appointed by the NBA to study ways to improve play, said 
the Cavs' coaching search could still be ``a week or two'' from 
completion. 
</P>
<P>
	After the Hornets started last season 4-11, Cowens, who coached  
the team to their two most successful seasons, resigned in part 
because he was upset with being the lowest-paid coach in the 
league. 
</P>
<P>
	Cowens wants another shot as a head coach, but didn't get the  
job after interviews in Washington and Orlando. 
</P>
<P>
	Raised in Cincinnati, he has a brother living in a Cleveland  
suburb and has enough familiarity with the city and the Cavs to 
know he'd be a good fit. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've got a good team and this is a great sports town,'' he  
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
