<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 20:40:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Mariners' Tax Money Request Denied </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- The Seattle Mariners' request for more tax money  
to pay for their new ballpark was rejected Thursday by the state 
panel overseeing construction of Safeco Field. 
</P>
<P>
	The resolution proposed by William P. Gerberding was adopted 6-0  
without discussion by the Washington State Public Facilities 
District board. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the development agreement signed by the Mariners and the  
board in 1996, a disputed claim may be submitted to nonbinding 
mediation. If that fails to resolve the issue, there is a provision 
for submitting some disputes to binding arbitration. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is the position of the PFD that this is not an appropriate  
issue for mediation and we hope the Mariners do not wish to 
litigate,'' the board's resolution said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mariners, who said their are considering a lawsuit to force  
mediation, want another $60 million to help cover $100 million in 
overruns. 
</P>
<P>
	Club officials have argued that higher-than-anticipated revenue  
from special restaurant, bar, car rental and stadium admission 
taxes enacted to finance the $517 million project should be applied 
to the overruns. 
</P>
<P>
	The County Council earmarked the extra tax revenue for early  
repayment of $336 million in stadium bonds and unanimously opposed 
further spending. 
</P>
<P>
	The 45,600-seat ballpark, equipped with a retractable roof,  
opens July 15. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
