<DOCNO> APW19990624.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 02:00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Plane Makes Landing in L.A. Street </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The damage included a shattered plane,  
spilled fuel and two school buses with smashed front ends. It could 
have been much worse. 
</P>
<P>
	Elementary school students and the plane's pilot were unhurt  
Wednesday when the small plane crash-landed at a busy intersection, 
ripping away its fuel tanks as it barreled between the approaching 
buses. 
</P>
<P>
	``In my 14 years on this job I have never seen a miraculous  
incident like this. There must have been divine intervention,'' 
said Los Angeles Fire Department spokesman Brian Humphrey. ``It was 
like passing through the eye of the needle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The twin-engine Cessna 402 was headed for nearby Van Nuys  
Airport about 2:45 p.m. when it was forced to make an emergency 
landing on Hayvenhurst Avenue, airport spokeswoman Stacy Geere 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	As the plane reached Hayvenhurst and Parthenia Street, it  
collided with the buses as they entered the intersection from 
opposite directions. The impact tore the wing tips off the plane 
and wrecked the front ends of the buses. The plane rolled for 1,500 
feet before coming to a stop. 
</P>
<P>
	The pilot was uninjured, and more than 40 children emerged  
unscathed from the buses to sit on the curb and sip soft drinks 
before they were taken away to wait for their parents. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought the plane wasn't going to hit us, but it hit us,''  
said Sasha Medina, a 10-year-old girl on the bus. ``I was like 
scared ... because I thought some of us were hurt.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One student was treated at a hospital for a possible head  
injury, then released, and one bus driver was hospitalized in fair 
condition with back and neck injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	The buses carried 42 students from Parthenia Street Elementary  
School and six from Lassen Elementary School, said Socorro Serrano, 
spokeswoman for the Los Angeles Unified School District. 
</P>
<P>
	``It could have been a catastrophe,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	The pilot, who was alone in the plane, was questioned by  
investigators from the Federal Aviation Administration and the 
National Transportation Safety Board. Authorities said he works for 
Sunshine Airlines, a Van Nuys charter firm. 
</P>
<P>
	Firefighters led children off the buses one at a time, with some  
children looking dazed and others among the mostly 6- to-10 year 
olds skipping and hopping. 
</P>
<P>
	They were later taken to their schools to be reunited with their  
parents. One unfazed child checked in via television camera. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to say `Mom, I love you,''' 9-year-old Luigi Escobar  
said. ``And I think you better come pick me up.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 15:00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Navy Pays for Admirals' Home Fixups </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Senate committee is criticizing the Navy for  
diverting $5.5 million from its operational budget to refurbish the 
residences of three four-star admirals. The Navy defended the 
spending on Thursday, but suggested the diversion would not happen 
again. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result of the dispute, the Senate voted to require the  
Pentagon to notify Congress in the future anytime it spends more 
than $25,000 on fixing up the quarters of an admiral or general. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate Appropriations Committee said the Navy's decision to  
spend the money from its ``operation and maintenance'' account 
instead of from housing funds appeared to be ``an attempt to 
circumvent congressional controls'' on spending on the quarters of 
admirals and generals. 
</P>
<P>
	It asked congressional auditors at the General Accounting Office  
to look into the matter. 
</P>
<P>
	The Navy took money for repairs from the operation and  
maintenance budget because the houses are used for official 
functions such as receptions, a Navy spokesman, Lt. Cmdr. Lydia 
Robertson, said. 
</P>
<P>
	``In any of these houses, only a floor or two is actually used  
for the family,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the three residences, that of the chief of naval  
operations at the Washington Navy Yard, is not being used as a 
residence by the current Navy chief, Adm. Jay Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
	The other two residences cited in the report were those of the  
superintendent of the U.S. Naval Academy in Annapolis, Md., and the 
Pacific Fleet commander at Pearl Harbor, Hawaii. 
</P>
<P>
	The criticism was included in an Appropriations Committee report  
that accompanied an $8.3 billion measure financing military 
construction in the fiscal year that begins Oct. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel added to the bill a provision requiring the Pentagon  
to notify Congress about any future housing renovations to top 
officer's quarters in excess of $25,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The overall measure was approved 97-2 on June 16. The House has  
yet to act on its version of the spending bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Planned work includes new plumbing, an elevator for handicapped  
access, removal of lead paint and other repairs or upgrades that 
the government routinely makes to other public buildings, the Navy 
spokeswoman said. 
</P>
<P>
	The work is complicated, and often made more expensive, by the  
age and historic value of the homes, Robertson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, when an internal audit early this year turned up  
the expenditures, Navy officials had second thoughts. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Navy came forward and said, 'this is what happened. We  
don't think it's right and we're going to change it,''' Robertson 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, the Navy is using ordinary housing budgets to pay for  
the ongoing work, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee report said that the use of ``operation and  
maintenance'' funds to renovate family housing was ``totally 
inappropriate, irrespective of the rank of the individual who 
occupies these quarters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Furthermore, the Navy has systematically failed to notify the  
Congress that these renovations and other family housing 
improvements were planned and ongoing,'' the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	It is the second time this month the Pentagon has come under  
fire from senators for heavy spending on the military's top 
commanders at a time when money for the armed services is tight. 
</P>
<P>
	During debate on military spending earlier this month, some  
senators complained that the Pentagon was leasing, for about $50 
million a year, six new business jets for the use of its top 
admirals and generals. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is S1205  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 14:47:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Skater Elvis Stojko To Stay Amateur </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Elvis Stojko wants a fourth world championship.  
</P>
<P>
	The Canadian figure skater said today he will continue competing  
as an amateur to try for it. 
</P>
<P>
	``My decision is to compete again, going once again for the  
world championship,'' Stojko said at a news conference this 
morning. ``I want to keep pushing myself as an athlete.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stojko will go after another world title in Brisbane, Australia,  
in March. 
</P>
<P>
	The 27-year-old has battled through injury the last year and a  
half, from a seriously pulled groin muscle that hampered his 
efforts at the 1998 Winter Olympics to a broken collarbone suffered 
in a practice spill 1 1/2 months ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Stojko is a two-time Olympic silver medal winner, three-time  
world champion and five-time Canadian senior champion. 
</P>
<P>
	But Stojko finished fourth at the world championships in  
Helsinki three months ago, and dropped longtime coach Doug Leigh 
last month. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 02:00:10 </DATE_TIME>
