<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Average Rate on Mortgages Falls / National Mortgage Survey  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The average interest rate on 30-year  
fixed-rate mortgages, which has been rising for two months, edged 
down to 7.63 percent this week. 
</P>
<P>
	The average was down from 7.65 percent last week, according to a  
weekly survey released Thursday by Freddie Mac, the mortgage 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	Mortgages rates have been on an upward climb for the past two  
months and have fluctuated from their low for this year of 6.74 
percent set at the end of January to 7.65 percent last week, the 
highest level in two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Fifteen-year mortgages, a popular option for refinancing,  
averaged 7.28 percent this week, up from the average of 7.26 
percent last week. 
</P>
<P>
	On one-year adjustable-rate mortgages, lenders were asking an  
average initial rate of 5.93 percent, slightly down from 5.94 
percent the previous week. 
</P>
<P>
	The rates do not include add-on fees known as points, which  
averaged at or just over 1 percent of the loan amount for all three 
types of mortgages. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 17:30:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sun Reiterates Microsoft Charge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Sun Microsystems Inc. reiterated  
accusations of copyright infringement Thursday in federal court 
against Microsoft Corp., arguing that the software maker distorted 
a popular Sun programming language so that it works only on Windows 
computers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Granted, Microsoft has the money to pay a million monkeys to  
program for a million years, but they still wouldn't come up with 
something identical to our Java,'' said Sun's attorney Rusty Day. 
``This was massive, verbatim, literal copying of our code.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sun, a Palo Alto, Calif.-based computer company, sued Redmond,  
Wash.-based Microsoft in Oct., 1997, claiming that the leading 
software maker had deceived customers and software developers into 
believing that Microsoft's version of the Java language was good 
for programs that ran on all computers. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, attorneys for Microsoft and Sun argued their cases  
in U.S. District Court in San Jose. Sun is seeking a finding of 
copyright infringement without a trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft attorney Charles Quackenbush said his company simply  
used Java to innovate, and that they were allowed to develop an 
independent version. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had a license to use their material in our products, and  
that's what happened,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	If someone condensed factual information from a historical novel  
into a small pamphlet, that pamphlet would not be copyright 
protected, said Quackenbush. 
</P>
<P>
	He said that analogy holds up for the way Microsoft used Java,  
``taking a portion of the code and running it through a compiler to 
come up with a completely different output.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a tentative ruling issued in May, Judge Ronald Whyte said  
that several Microsoft Corp. products, including Windows 98, 
infringed Sun's copyrights. 
</P>
<P>
	However, he said, Microsoft can develop and distribute  
``independently developed'' tools that do not comply with a 
contract with Sun, so long as such products do not infringe any Sun 
copyright, patent or other intellectual property right. 
</P>
<P>
	Whyte is expected to make a final ruling within the next few  
weeks. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
