<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Congress Asked To Aid Extradition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A man suspected of shooting a Florida mother  
in the face, slitting her throat and leaving her four toddlers 
crawling in her blood is putting up a vigorous fight against 
extradition from Mexico, Clinton administration officials say. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida prosecutors are frustrated with the delay, but each of  
Jose Luis Del Toro Jr.'s appeals and legal challenges must be heard 
in the Mexican courts, Deputy Assistant Attorney General Mary Lee 
Warren and Jamison Borek, a State Department deputy legal adviser, 
told a House subcommittee on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	They spoke after James Bellush, the victim's husband, asked  
Congress for help in pressuring the Mexican government to hand Del 
Toro over to the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	His voice at times quaking with emotion, Bellush said he and his  
children have waited since November 1997 to see Del Toro brought to 
trial in the death of his wife, Sheila Bellush, 35. 
</P>
<P>
	``Please do not allow Sheila to have died in vain,'' Bellush  
asked members of the House Government Reform criminal justice, drug 
policy and human resources subcommittee. 
</P>
<P>
	Saying he was angry about the delay, subcommittee Chairman John  
Mica, R-Fla., ordered the staff to write to the Justice and State 
departments asking what they had done on the case and urging them 
to do more. He said he might subpoena Attorney General Janet Reno 
and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright to testify before the 
subcommittee. 
</P>
<P>
	Warren and Borek said the extradition is working its way slowly  
through the Mexican court system. The Mexican legal system gives 
defendants many more opportunities for appeals and objections than 
the U.S. system does. But each of Del Toro's challenges so far has 
been rejected by the Mexican courts, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	During the hearing, Bellush brought subcommittee members close  
to tears as he told them how his 13-year-old stepdaughter 
discovered her 35-year-old mother lying dead on the kitchen floor 
of their Sarasota, Fla., home on Nov. 7, 1997. Her 23-month-old 
quadruplets were huddled together, crying. Police said they 
apparently had been alone with their mother's body for long as six 
hours. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators believe she was killed by a hired murderer. Two  
people have been convicted for their roles in the crime, and 
authorities say they have compelling evidence against Del Toro, a 
U.S. citizen who was arrested in Monterey, Mexico, weeks after the 
slaying. He was in Mexico illegally. 
</P>
<P>
	Mexican authorities first said they would deport Del Toro to the  
United States, local prosecutor Earl Moreland said. But the day he 
was supposed to be handed over at the Texas-Mexico border, the 
Mexican government said he had been taken to Mexico City instead 
and U.S. officials should seek extradition. 
</P>
<P>
	``The U.S. Department of Justice informed me that the Mexican  
government would not extradite Del Toro unless I would give 
assurance that Del Toro would not receive the death penalty if 
extradited,'' Moreland said. ``We agreed to waive the death penalty 
after talking with Mr. Bellush and filed the necessary papers with 
the Justice Department.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bellush said the quadruplets -- now 4 years old -- still remember  
the scene. 
</P>
<P>
	``I tell Timmy, Joey, Frankie and Courtney that Mommy is in  
heaven with Jesus,'' he said. ``They ask me if she is still 
bleeding.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
