<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	House Backs Flag Amendment  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House today voted 305-124 to allow  
legislation that would ban desecration of the flag, 19 votes more 
than the two-thirds needed to amend the Constitution. The focus now 
moves to the Senate, which in the past has resisted what supporters 
say is needed to protect the nation's symbol but opponents call an 
infringement of First Amendment free speech rights. Both sides 
agreed that backers of the amendment are one or two votes short of 
the 67 Senate votes needed for approval. 

</P>
<P>
	Holbrooke Defends Milosevic Talks  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Richard Holbrooke, President Clinton's nominee  
to be U.N. ambassador, defended his negotiations with Slobodan 
Milosevic today, saying he was trying ``to avoid war and bring 
peace.'' Holbrooke, architect of the 1995 peace accords for Bosnia 
and a frequent emissary to Milosevic before the NATO airstrikes, is 
expected to win easy Senate confirmation to the long-vacant post at 
the United Nations. This likelihood was signaled by the committee 
chairman himself, Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., who pointedly called 
Holbrooke ``Mr. Ambassador.'' 

</P>
<P>
	World Bank OKs Chinese Farmers Loan  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The World Bank today approved a $40 million  
loan to resettle poor Chinese farmers on land Tibetans claim as 
their own. But it put off paying out any funds until the bank's 
independent inspection panel examines the project. A statement 
released after the meeting of the bank's 24-member executive board 
said the project, which has three parts and a total value of $160 
million, was designed to benefit 1.7 million of the poorest people 
in China. 

</P>
<P>
	Paper: Lewinsky Questioned on Tripp  
</P>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Maryland prosecutors have questioned Monica  
Lewinsky as part of their wiretapping case against Linda Tripp, 
whose tapes of telephone conversations with the former White House 
intern triggered the presidential sex scandal, The Baltimore Sun 
reported today. Maryland forbids anyone from taping phone 
conversations without the other party's consent. Prosecutors turned 
over Ms. Lewinsky's answers last week to a Howard County grand jury 
investigating Ms. Tripp, the newspaper said. 

</P>
<P>
	Guilty Plea in Ala. Gay Death Trial  
</P>
<P>
	ROCKFORD, Ala. (AP) -- One of two men accused in the beating  
death of a homosexual man who allegedly made a pass at one of them 
pleaded guilty to capital murder today. In exchange for the plea, 
prosecutors said they will recommend a sentence of life without 
parole for Steven Eric Mullins rather than death in Alabama's 
electric chair. Mullins entered his plea as the parents of Billy 
Jack Gaither stood nearby. ``I kidnapped Mr. Gaither, forced him 
into the car and killed him intentionally,'' he said. 

</P>
<P>
	FTC Battling Internet Health Fraud  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Trade Commission today announced  
efforts to combat fraudulent health products on the Web and alert 
consumers, who increasingly are using the Internet as a major 
source of health information, to be discerning. ``We hope Americans 
continue to use the Internet for truthful information, but we also 
want them to have their antennas up to be careful about those 
claims that are exaggerated,'' said Jodie Bernstein, director of 
the FTC's bureau of consumer protection. More than 22 million U.S. 
adults searched online for medical information as of December 1998. 

</P>
<P>
	Protestants Hold IRA Abuses March  
</P>
<P>
	LONDONDERRY, Northern Ireland (AP) -- Protestants protesting  
suffering inflicted by the Irish Republican Army began a 10-day 
march today across Northern Ireland. About 150 silent Catholic 
protesters picketed the start of the 117-mile march. Critics say 
the protest is designed to raise sectarian tensions ahead of a June 
30 deadline to establish a Protestant-Catholic government. There 
was no trouble as the Protestants, led by maimed survivors of IRA 
attacks and relatives of IRA victims, walked through Londonderry. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Falls 172, Nasdaq Down 44  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 2 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
down 172.24 points at 10,494.62. Declining issues on the New York 
Stock Exchange led advancers 1,930-857. The Nasdaq was down 44.64 
at 2,553.48. 

</P>
<P>
	Dokic, Agassi Win at Wimbledon  
</P>
<P>
	WIMBLEDON, England (AP) -- Following her upset win over Martina  
Hingis, Australian teen-ager Jelena Dokic followed through with a 
6-0, 4-6, 8-6 victory over Katarina Studenikova at Wimbledon today. 
Andre Agassi, still riding the momentum of his French Open triumph, 
swept Guillermo Canas 6-3, 6-4, 6-3. No. 7 Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario 
lost to Lisa Raymond 7-6 (7-4), 6-1, but No. 3 Lindsay Davenport 
beat Karina Habsudova 6-2, 6-2. 

</P>
