<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Commander Cheered in Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO commander Gen. Wesley Clark  
said today he believes the horrors being uncovered in Kosovo 
provide clear justification for the alliance's punishing bombing 
campaign. ``What you see here is the magnitude of the horror that 
required NATO action,'' said Clark, who was greeted by a cheering 
crowd as he accompanied NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana on 
their first visit to Kosovo. He was referring to mounting evidence 
of mass graves and atrocities found by peacekeepers and forensic 
specialists in the province. 

</P>
<P>
	House To Vote on Flag Amendment  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House will vote today on whether to amend  
the Constitution and allow legislation banning desecration of the 
flag. The House's near certain approval will move the focus to the 
Senate, which in the past has resisted the amendment. During debate 
yesterday, backers argued that the flag is such a unique symbol of 
the nation that it should be protected. The White House, in a 
statement, said it was committed to protecting the flag but 
``efforts to limit the First Amendment to make a narrow exception 
for flag desecration are misguided.'' 

</P>
<P>
	19 Million Pool Toys Recalled  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government today said it is recalling more  
than 19 million pool ``dive sticks'' because they can impale 
children who land on them. Dive sticks are hard, plastic 
cylinder-shaped objects that stand upright on the bottom of pools 
so children can dive down and retrieve them. The Consumer Product 
Safety Commission recommends that parents throw the toys away. The 
commission also said it is recalling an infant carrier because of 
the danger a child could fall out, and some new Star Wars 
lightsabers because they may cause burns to their users. 

</P>
<P>
	Ocalan Defense Warns of Violence  
</P>
<P>
	IMRALI ISLAND, Turkey (AP) -- Defense lawyers for Abdullah Ocalan  
wrapped up their final arguments today, warning a Turkish court 
that new rebels will take up the struggle if the Kurdish guerrilla 
leader is hanged. Judge Turgut Okyay ordered a recess until 
Tuesday, when the panel of three judges will announce its verdict, 
the Anatolia news agency reported. If Ocalan is convicted, a death 
sentence is automatic. The lawyers' claims echoed Ocalan's chilling 
statements yesterday, in which he spoke of massive bloodshed if he 
is executed, but offered to fight for peace if his life is spared. 

</P>
<P>
	Mother Loses Home As Son Jumps Bail  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- A federal judge approved the seizure of a woman's  
home and another house she had pledged as bail for her son, who cut 
off his electronic home-monitoring bracelet and disappeared. ``I've 
lost my son, I've lost everything,'' Spomenka Lunic said yesterday 
as U.S. District Judge Harry Leinenweber gave prosecutors 
permission to confiscate the property put up for her son's $500,000 
bond. Slobodan Lunic, 41, was to go on trial Monday on charges of 
defrauding investors in a pay telephone scheme. 

</P>
<P>
	Cell Phones Top '90s Stamps Voting  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Americans have chosen cellular phones,  
``Titanic,'' recovering species and the Special Olympics among the 
subjects for a set of stamps to commemorate the 1990s. The Postal 
Service announced the results of the voting today, with cellular 
phones taking first place with 214,449 votes. The blockbuster movie 
``Titanic'' came second with 210,154 votes. The 1990s stamp set 
will be released next April. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Drops 55, Nasdaq Down 19  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 11 a.m. EDT, the Dow industrials  
were down 55.72 points at 10,611.14. Declining issues on the New 
York Stock Exchange led advancers 1,343-986. The Nasdaq was down 
19.02 at 2,579.10. 

</P>
<P>
	Judge Orders Lewis Jury To Continue  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A judge ordered a deadlocked jury this morning in  
the Reggie Lewis medical malpractice case to make a ``last good 
effort'' to reach a verdict. After more than 30 hours of 
deliberations, the jurors said last night they were at an impasse 
concerning the lead physician who treated the former Celtics 
captain before he collapsed and died shooting baskets. The jury 
said they had reached decisions on two consultants, but could not 
decide whether Dr. Gilbert Mudge was negligent in his care of the 
late Celtics star. 

</P>
<P>
	Dokic Wins Again at Wimbledon  
</P>
<P>
	WIMBLEDON, England (AP) -- Australian teen-ager Jelena Dokic came  
through with a successful sequel to her upset of Martina Hingis, 
edging Katarina Studenikova 6-0, 4-6, 8-6 at Wimbledon today. No. 7 
Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario joined Hingis as the only seeded women on 
the sidelines, losing to Lisa Raymond 7-6 (7-4), 6-1. No. 9 Mary 
Pierce reached the third round by beating Rita Grande 6-1, 6-3. 

</P>
