<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Skater Elvis Stojko To Stay Amateur </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Elvis Stojko wants a fourth world championship.  
</P>
<P>
	The Canadian figure skater said today he will continue competing  
as an amateur to try for it. 
</P>
<P>
	``My decision is to compete again, going once again for the  
world championship,'' Stojko said at a news conference this 
morning. ``I want to keep pushing myself as an athlete.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stojko will go after another world title in Brisbane, Australia,  
in March. 
</P>
<P>
	The 27-year-old has battled through injury the last year and a  
half, from a seriously pulled groin muscle that hampered his 
efforts at the 1998 Winter Olympics to a broken collarbone suffered 
in a practice spill 1 1/2 months ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Stojko is a two-time Olympic silver medal winner, three-time  
world champion and five-time Canadian senior champion. 
</P>
<P>
	But Stojko finished fourth at the world championships in  
Helsinki three months ago, and dropped longtime coach Doug Leigh 
last month. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
