<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Religion Today  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOUNT HOPE, Ohio (AP) -- On a recent weekday, workers at the  
glass-and-steel headquarters of Wayne-Dalton Corp.took a break from 
their jobs and went outside: A mare was foaling in a nearby field. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the company has annual sales of $300 million as a  
leading garage-door maker, CEO Willis Mullet keeps it close to the 
cultural and religious roots of his family's Mennonite background. 
One employee in four at the company's Mount Hope plant is Amish or 
Mennonite. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's Willis' way of giving back to the Amish-Mennonite  
community,'' said David Osso, spokesman for the family-owned 
company, a farming community about 60 miles southwest of Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
	That community is associated with horse-drawn buggies,  
traditional farming methods and simple, old-fashioned clothing, and 
yet more and more Mennonites are, like Mullet, working in 
multimillion-dollar businesses, said Conrad Kanagy, a Mennonite who 
is an associate professor of sociology at Elizabethtown (Pa.) 
College. 
</P>
<P>
	Wealth can cause members of the religion that prizes a simple  
life to wonder whether they are following ``the biblical principles 
in their stewardship of money and possessions,'' as called for in 
the Confession of Faith adopted in 1990 by the Fellowship of 
Concerned Mennonites. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's still a relatively new thing for Mennonites to be  
wealthy,'' Kanagy said. ``They're humble people and some feel 
uncomfortable having so much money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He added: ``Mennonites in general take Jesus' life very  
seriously and try to live that life. Christ didn't exhibit a lot of 
wealth and didn't even have a place to live. We're taught to be 
responsible with our wealth and be sure to use it to serve man.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Mennonite Church is an outgrowth of the Protestant  
Reformation and takes its name from Menno Simons, a Catholic priest 
in Holland who joined the Anabaptists in 1536. His work was so 
influential that those who followed his faith were called 
Mennonites. The group splintered in 1693 when a Swiss bishop named 
Jacob Amman left, and his followers became known as Amish. 
</P>
<P>
	For centuries, the two groups quietly made their living through  
farming. But as land becomes more expensive and scarce, some 
Mennonites are leaving the farm and entering the business world. 
Unlike the Amish, the Mennonites do not shun modern conveniences 
such as electricity, cars and telephones. 
</P>
<P>
	For years, rich Mennonites clashed with church leaders who were  
concerned that the business world was eroding their principles, 
Kanagy said. 
</P>
<P>
	James Herr, 75, was something of a pioneer among Mennonite  
businessmen. When his Pennsylvania potato chip business, Herr Foods 
Inc., started taking off in the 1950s, he said he tried not to let 
reaction from some church members bother him. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had to overcome whether I could be in business and be a good  
Christian,'' he said. ``The church grew in that area, too. The 
church now recognizes that they need business people as well as 
farmers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Herr said he is still amazed by the success of his company,which  
he bought in 1946 for $1,750. The company now employs 1,250 people 
and generates about $150 million in sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Daryl Thomas, marketing director and Herr's son-in-law, said  
Herr regards the business in the context of his faith, ``as a means 
to a greater end. It's a way to serve his community. At the same 
time, he continues to spread the gospel.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other successful Mennonite businesses include:  
</P>
<P>
	--Sauder Woodworking Co., Archbold, Ohio: maker of  
ready-to-assemble furniture; 3,200 employees, $500 million annual 
sales. 
</P>
<P>
	--Palliser Furniture, Winnipeg: Canada's largest household  
furniture manufacturer; 3,600 employees, $325 million in sales. 
</P>
<P>
	--The Dutch Corp., Walnut Creek, Ohio, owner of eight  
restaurants, two hotels and several gift shops; $33 million in 
sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Charity among wealthy church members fits with church tradition.  
Mennonite Mutual Aid based in Goshen, Ind., is a major beneficiary. 
It distributed $25 million in grants last year, mostly to needy 
Mennonite congregations. 
</P>
<P>
	``They really want to give back to the church and believe in  
living out their faith every day,'' said Judy Martin Godshalk, 
spokeswoman for MMA in Goshen, Ind. 
</P>
<P>
	They live it in other ways, too. The religion teaches abstinence  
from alcohol and tobacco, and so Mennonite retailers typically 
don't sell these products. Their stores are closed on Sundays. 
</P>
<P>
	A group called Mennonite Economic Development Associates helps  
its members bridge the gap between business and faith, said John 
Longhurst, communications director of the Winnipeg-based group. It 
helps Mennonites handle business decisions that carry an ethical 
component, such as whether to lay people off, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The 2,600 MEDA members donate money so the organization can make  
loans to low-income entrepreneurs worldwide. Their efforts create 
or sustain 10,000 jobs every year. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're running the businesses not to make themselves rich but  
because they have a responsibility to the community, to the poor 
and to the environment,'' Longhurst added. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 16:30:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Real Quiet Favorite in Gold Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INGLEWOOD, Calif. (AP) -- Real Quiet, who came within a nose of  
winning the Triple Crown last year, drew the No. 2 post position 
Thursday and will face three rivals in Sunday's $1 million 
Hollywood Gold Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	Real Quiet was installed as the 7-5 morning-line favorite for  
the 1 1/4-mile race. Probable favorite Old Trieste was scratched 
Tuesday due to a foot abscess. 
</P>
<P>
	Puerto Madero, second to Skip Away in last year's Gold Cup, was  
made the 2-1 second choice, followed by Budroyale at 5-2 and Malek 
at 7-2. 
</P>
<P>
	Real Quiet will be ridden Sunday for the first time by Jerry  
Bailey. He takes over for Gary Stevens, who is riding in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Trainer Bob Baffert dismissed Real Quiet's third-place finish to  
Behrens in the Massachusetts Handicap on May 29. 
</P>
<P>
	``He got into a little bit of a speed duel and was racing  
between horses,'' Baffert said. ``He didn't like that. The 
mile-and-one-quarter of the Hollywood Gold Cup, he'll like that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Trainer Richard Mandella said he would add blinkers on Puerto  
Madero to get the 5-year-old Chilean-bred more focused. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've had to get after him a little in his recent races,''  
jockey Kent Desormeaux said. ``The blinkers will make him do it on 
his own.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Gold Cup field with jockeys: Malek, Alex Solis; Real Quiet,  
Bailey; Budroyale, Garrett Gomez; and Puerto Madero, Desormeaux. 
All starters will carry 124 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	Sempra Energy sponsors the Gold Cup.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 11:10:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Steel Shipments Rebound </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Steel imports to the United States jumped 30  
percent in May, the Commerce Department said Thursday, two days 
after the Senate rejected a quota bill partly on grounds that 
imports were headed down. 
</P>
<P>
	Whether the May numbers will give new life to quotas is unclear.  
Commerce Secretary William Daley, who had argued that quotas could 
start an international trade war, said the latest figures should 
not be cause for worry. 
</P>
<P>
	``One month is not reason to suddenly believe it's a trend,'' he  
told reporters. ``We didn't gloat on the month-to-month basis when 
a one-month statistic showed a drop in imports.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Rep. Ralph Regula, R-Ohio, chairman of the House steel  
caucus, said of the report, ``This just demonstrates that 
predictions that the steel crisis is over were premature at best. 
... I hope the White House now understands that relief is 
necessary.'' 
</P>
<P>
	May's increase was the second in seven months. The Commerce  
Department said it was driven primarily by shipments from Brazil, 
Mexico and Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	Foreign countries shipped 3 million metric tons of steel to the  
United States in May, according to the preliminary figures. That is 
30 percent higher than the final 2.3 million figure for April, but 
still 18 percent below November's levels. 
</P>
<P>
	From Jan. 1 through May, steel imports totaled 12.4 million  
metric tons, only a slight increase from the 12.3 million metric 
tons imported during the same period in 1997, before the Asian 
economic crisis lowered demand for steel abroad and forced foreign 
producers to find outlets in a healthy U.S. economy. In the same 
period of 1998, the imports totaled 13.2 million metric tons. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. steel mills buy some foreign steel as raw material for  
higher-value products. Such imports totaled 931,000 metric tons in 
May, more than twice the April level. They represented nearly a 
third of all imports last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Domestic producers and their steelworkers have blamed low-priced  
imports for bankruptcies at three U.S. companies and for thousands 
of layoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	The industry has filed numerous trade complaints accusing Japan  
and other countries of illegally pricing products in the U.S. 
market below production costs. The industry already won punitive 
tariffs on shipments of the industry's core product from Japan. 
Other cases are pending. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commerce Department reported that shipments from Japan,  
Russia and Brazil, the three targets of the initial round of 
complaints, all posted one-month increases in May -- Russia by more 
than six times. Steel shipments from Indonesia and South Korea also 
rose. 
</P>
<P>
	The industry sought stronger sanctions, such as quotas, but the  
Senate rejected that Tuesday, voting 57-42 against a motion to 
restrict debate on the quota bill, effectively killing any chances 
for passage. Supporters said afterward they had no plans to try 
again. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 00:20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Puffy' Apologizes To Record Exec </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Rap impresario Sean ``Puffy'' Combs has  
apologized to the record executive who claimed he suffered a broken 
jaw and arm in a beating by Combs and two other men. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was embarrassed,'' the Grammy-winning rapper said Wednesday  
about the April 15 incident. ``That's not a normal action for me. I 
thought, `How could you be so stupid? This is not like you.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Combs, 29, said he has ``talked everything out'' with the  
executive, Steven Stoute. 
</P>
<P>
	According to Combs, Stoute has approached the Manhattan district  
attorney about dropping the charges. Stoute's attorney, Thomas 
Puccio, issued a statement Wednesday: ``The matter has been 
amicably resolved to the satisfaction of the parties.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Combs said no money was paid to Stoute to resolve the dispute.  
</P>
<P>
	Combs, whose 1998 earnings of $53.5 million ranked him 15th on  
the Forbes magazine list of wealthiest entertainers, was due in 
court today to face charges of assault and criminal mischief. He 
could be sentenced to up to seven years in prison if convicted. 
</P>
<P>
	Combs said the incident was blown out of proportion: ``His arm  
was never broken, his jaw was never broken. I went in to argue, and 
I handled myself in the wrong way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Combs said he was irate that Stoute let MTV air a music video  
with a possibly controversial scene that showed Combs nailed to a 
cross. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
