<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grenada Telephone Monopoly Upheld </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. GEORGE'S, Grenada (AP) -- A judge on Thursday upheld Cable &AMP;  
Wireless Grenada's telephone monopoly as it confronts new 
competitors offering cheap calls between the Caribbean and the 
United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Justice Brian Alleyne ruled Spycecom, a ``callback'' service,  
had infringed on the monopoly guaranteed under a 1989 law. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Public Telecommunications Act unequivocally supports Cable  
&AMP; Wireless' exclusive rights to provide both national and 
international telecommunications services in Grenada,'' Alleyne 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	He also said the company has ``preemptive rights'' over  
communications methods that haven't been introduced to the island 
yet. 
</P>
<P>
	With Spycecom, customers dialed a local number to a computer  
that in turn contacted a computer in the United States. The U.S. 
computer then returned the call so that customers could enjoy the 
U.S. rates -- usually a fraction of the $1.20 per minute or more 
charged by Cable &AMP; Wireless. 
</P>
<P>
	Similar callback companies have proliferated in Jamaica,  
Dominica, St. Lucia and other Caribbean countries where the British 
telecommunications giant has legal monopolies. The company has sued 
many of its competitors and is also attacking new Internet 
providers. 
</P>
<P>
	In Dominica, a judge recently ruled the company's monopoly was  
illegal. Cable &AMP; Wireless is appealing the decision. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
