<HEADLINE> Mom in Switched Babies Case Sues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STAFFORD, Va. (AP) -- The mother of one of two newborns switched  
at birth has filed a lawsuit against the maker of the 
identification bands used at the hospital, claiming the product was 
defective. 
</P>
<P>
	Paula Johnson filed the suit Wednesday in Los Angeles against  
Precision Dynamics Corp., the San Fernando, Calif.-based maker of 
the bands. 
</P>
<P>
	The suit claims the bands were so loose they slipped off the  
wrists and ankles of the two blue-eyed, blond newborns in June 
1995, and that nurses inadvertently switched the bands when they 
put them back on the babies. 
</P>
<P>
	The girls were sent home from the University of Virginia Medical  
Center with the wrong parents, who did not learn about the mistake 
until last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, Ms. Johnson filed a $31 million lawsuit against the  
state, the hospital and its staff. The latest suit sets no amount 
for damages, but claims the bands were designed so they could not 
be firmly attached around an infant's wrist or ankle. 
</P>
<P>
	Precision Dynamics called the suit ``totally groundless.''  
</P>
<P>
	``This is a clear-cut case where the hospital staff failed to  
follow well-established procedures to ensure that identification 
bracelets are properly applied and monitored for snugness,'' Walter 
Mosher Jr., the company's president, said in a release. 
</P>
<P>
	The switch was discovered last summer when DNA testing conducted  
for a dispute over child support between Ms. Johnson and her former 
boyfriend showed the couple were not the biological parents of 
Callie Marie Conley, the child Ms. Johnson was raising. 
</P>
<P>
	Further testing showed Ms. Johnson and Carlton Conley were the  
parents of Rebecca Grace Chittum, a child being raised by two sets 
of grandparents because the couple that brought her home three 
years earlier had been killed in a car accident before the 
discovery of the mix-up. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit is just the latest in a series of legal maneuverings  
by Ms. Johnson, who also has filed a petition in Stafford County 
Juvenile Court to gain custody of her birth daughter, Rebecca. She 
is also seeking to legally adopt Callie. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
