<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton To Revive Domestic Agenda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Returning to political battles after the  
conflict in Kosovo, President Clinton will use a speech Friday to 
try to revive his domestic agenda, from Medicare and Social 
Security proposals to an increase in the minimum wage. 
</P>
<P>
	``The president is very much looking forward to returning the  
spotlight on some domestic issues and his domestic agenda,'' 
spokesman Joe Lockhart said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton will push his agenda in a speech at Georgetown  
University, his first public appearance since returning from a 
weeklong trip to Europe. In Colonge, Germany, the president and 
allies celebrated the formal end to the Kosovo battle with the 
departure of the last Serb troops from Kosovo. Even before that, 
Clinton had declared victory. 
</P>
<P>
	The president has been distracted from domestic priorities for  
about 18 months, beginning with the Monica Lewinsky scandal and 
then the impeachment battle, followed quickly by the showdown with 
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and NATO's 78-day bombing 
campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Lockhart, in a brief preview of the address, said Clinton ``will  
talk about the importance of getting things done this year and not 
falling prey to the idea that because of the political environment, 
we can't get important things done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said Clinton would open a new campaign for overhauling Social  
Security and Medicare, raising the minimum wage, tightening gun 
control, adopting a patients' bill of rights to help Americans deal 
with managed-care health programs, and proposals to revive 
economically depressed communities. 
</P>
<P>
	With accelerated calendar for the 2000 presidential race and  
Republicans in control of Congress, it is uncertain how many of 
Clinton's proposals might be enacted. But even if his proposals are 
shelved, they still will arm Democrats with a political platform 
for the elections. 
</P>
<P>
	A centerpiece of Clinton's program is a plan to provide  
prescription benefits for the elderly under Medicare -- a new 
proposal that will cost billions of dollars. Recognizing the 
political attractiveness of such a plan, Republicans are planning 
their own proposal but with less generouos benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	The president is expected to announce details of his Medicare  
plan early next week. 
</P>
<P>
	White House aides also are planning a whirlwind of presidential  
travel. He will appear in New York and Connecticut next Monday for 
political fund-raisers and then travel to Chicago on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Beginning July 5, he will begin a tour of poverty pockets across  
America, stopping in Kentucky, Mississippi, Missouri, South Dakota, 
Arizona and California. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
