<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Haskins Agrees To Quit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Clem Haskins, at the center of allegations of  
academic fraud at Minnesota, has agreed to quit after 13 seasons as 
basketball coach, according to reports. 
</P>
<P>
	``I talked to Clem today and he believes that the president  
(Mark Yudof) would feel more comfortable if the program continued 
on under other leadership,'' athletic director Mark Dienhart told 
WCCO radio on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Saint Paul Pioneer Press reported that Haskins has agreed to  
quit amid allegations of academic fraud and other improprieties in 
the basketball program. 
</P>
<P>
	In a story for Friday's editions, the newspaper said the details  
of Haskins' departure were still being negotiated Thursday night. 
But it said the main framework of the deal, which calls for Haskins 
to receive a buyout of more than $1 million, was finalized earlier 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Yudof, who visited the coach at his home on Wednesday, was  
scheduled to brief the university's board of regents on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	A news conference was planned after the meeting.  
</P>
<P>
	Clemette Haskins, the coach's daughter, would neither confirm  
nor deny the newspaper report when contacted at her father's home 
Thursday night by The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	Talks between university general counsel Mark Rotenberg and Ron  
Zamansky, Haskins' lawyer, which began more than two weeks ago, 
were continuing into the night to hammer out minor details, the 
Pioneer Press said. 
</P>
<P>
	Yudof had authorized Rotenberg to begin talks about a possible  
buyout of the coach's contract three weeks ago. The Star Tribune 
reported a buyout package could cost the university about $2.5 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	Yudof declined to discuss the substance of the discussions,  
saying only he feels ``sad about the whole situation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The investigation began after the Pioneer Press reported in  
March that Jan Gangelhoff, a former office manager in the academic 
counseling unit, said she did more than 400 pieces of course work 
for at least 20 basketball players from 1993 to 1998. The probe 
widened to include allegations of improper payments and travel 
irregularities. 
</P>
<P>
	In a speech to alumni leaders Wednesday, Yudof promised ``some  
self-imposed sanctions'' would result from the investigation. If 
the university's investigation shows ``slam dunk'' wrongdoing, 
Yudof said, ``it's much better for us to act before we pass the 
file over to the NCAA.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Haskins has three years remaining on a 10-year contract he  
signed in 1994 that was retroactive to the start of the 1992-93 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	The contract entitles him to about $423,000 if he is fired with  
just cause. If he is fired without cause, he is entitled to about 
$1.3 million plus benefits, and also could sue for defamation of 
character and for revenue lost from his camps and athletic-shoe 
contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Minnesota hired Haskins away from Western Kentucky in 1986. He  
was widely praised for resurrecting the program, leading the 
Gophers to the NCAA tournament in 1989, his third season as coach, 
and to the Big Ten title and NCAA Final Four in 1997. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
