<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> A Look at 1999 Hoop Hall of Famers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) -- The combative John Thompson and the  
laid-back Kevin McHale are ending up in the same place: the 
Basketball Hall of Fame. 
</P>
<P>
	The outspoken Thompson said Wednesday he felt slighted when he  
was nominated and passed over twice before. ``It is something I 
wanted -- make no bones about it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said his strong political stands apparently hurt his chances  
in the past. ``I'll probably be remembered for all the things that 
kept me out of the Hall of Fame, ironically, more than for the 
things that got me into it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	This year's other hall of famers are Cleveland Cavaliers  
executive Wayne Embry; Billie Moore, who made history by winning 
national championships at both Cal State-Fullerton and UCLA; and 
the late Fred Zollner, an NBA pioneer and Detroit Pistons owner. 
The inductees announced Wednesday enter the hall in Springfield on 
Oct. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson, who endured racial taunts when he first fielded a  
predominantly black team in his early days at Georgetown, became 
the first black coach to win an NCAA title in 1984. Not one to shy 
from a fight, he boycotted two games in protest of NCAA Proposition 
42 in 1989, saying its financial limits hurt minority athletes. 
</P>
<P>
	Julius Erving, the Philadelphia hall of famer, seconded  
Thompson's complaints Wednesday about his delayed entry. But he 
added that Thompson didn't always fight his battles ``in terms of 
the standards of the Hall of Fame -- he didn't turn the other 
cheek.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson, who was the Boston Celtics' backup center for Bill  
Russell on the 1965 and 1966 championship teams, arrived as 
Georgetown's coach in 1972 and inherited a 3-23 program. He quickly 
hired an academic adviser for his players and preached classroom 
success. 
</P>
<P>
	During the next 27 seasons, his Hoyas teams went 596-239 as  
Thompson became an NCAA fixture, stalking courtside with a towel 
draped over his husky torso. Under Thompson, Georgetown made the 
NCAA tournament 14 straight times, played in three Final Fours and 
beat Houston for the national championship in 1984. Patrick Ewing, 
Alonzo Mourning and Dikembe Mutombo went on to the NBA. 
</P>
<P>
	He surprised the basketball world in January, when he retired in  
midseason for personal reasons. 
</P>
<P>
	McHale established himself as a Celtics star for 13 seasons with  
Robert Parish and Larry Bird. With that trio forming one of the 
best NBA frontcourts ever, the team won championships in 1981, 1984 
and 1986. 
</P>
<P>
	McHale acknowledged Wednesday that his election had something to  
do with his teammates. ``If I had played for team `Y' out there 
that had never won a championship, I wouldn't be standing before 
you right now,'' he said at a news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	McHale's low-key style provided relief from Bird's intensity.  
Red Auerbach, vice chairman of the Celtics, said McHale was ``kind 
of easygoing, even though he was a competitor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brought to the Celtics in 1980 with Parish, McHale at first came  
in as the sixth man. The 6-foot-10 forward, whose long arms helped 
him to shoot over the top of defenders, made his early impact in 
the pivot. But he developed an array of nimble offensive moves that 
eventually helped set a standard for big men and reach the Hall of 
Fame. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was never any doubt in my mind he would make it,'' said  
Bird, who now coaches the Indiana Pacers. 
</P>
<P>
	During his career, McHale averaged 17.9 points and 7.3 rebounds  
and shot 55 percent from the field. He made seven All-Star teams 
and three All-NBA defensive teams. 
</P>
<P>
	He is now vice president of basketball operations for the  
Minnesota Timberwolves. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
