<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Compuware Founder Sued </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Two women who worked at Compuware Corp.,  
including a former human relations executive, have claimed that 
founder Peter Karmanos Jr. sexually harassed them, according to a 
published report. 
</P>
<P>
	Business Week magazine said in its July 5 issue that the  
company's board of directors fired the executive, Sheila McKinnon, 
in May 1998 after a report by an outside attorney could not verify 
her allegations. The other employee, Troy Strong, quit and claimed 
Karmanos pressured her to drop her complaint. 
</P>
<P>
	Karmanos denied the allegations to the magazine. ``You sit here,  
running a company for 26 years, and then this,'' he told Business 
Week. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokeswoman for Compuware said Thursday that the company had  
not seen the story and could not comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. McKinnon sued Compuware and Karmanos after she was fired,  
the magazine said. Ms. Strong, who had been Karmanos' secretary, 
left Compuware a few months after Ms. McKinnon and filed her own 
suit against the company. 
</P>
<P>
	The company settled with Ms. McKinnon in April, but Ms. Strong's  
suit is still pending, Business Week said. 
</P>
<P>
	Karmanos, 56, has guided the computer network and software  
company from a $9,000 bet with two friends in 1973 to sales of $1.6 
billion last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Karmanos has been hailed for donating more than $20 million to a  
cancer center named for his first wife, Barbara Ann, who died of 
breast cancer. Karmanos also owns the Carolina Hurricanes National 
League Hockey team. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
