<DOCNO> APW19990624.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 02:10:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Kosovo Kid Makes His Mark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The Kosovo Kid is a fighter whose ``weapons'' are boxing gloves.  
</P>
<P>
	Elvir Muriqi wanted to return to his native land and join the  
Kosovo Liberation Army as his father, Ramiz, and his sister, 
Elinda, have done, but he was told he could call attention to the 
ethnic Albanian cause through boxing. 
</P>
<P>
	Professional and amateur boxers long have been seen, and used,  
as standard bearers for countries and causes. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Soviet bloc nations for many years used major  
international boxing competition such as the Olympics as a 
propaganda vehicles. Cuba still does. 
</P>
<P>
	It's possible that if the Soviet bloc had remained intact,  
Muriqi would be a rising international amateur star as a member of 
the Yugoslavia national team. 
</P>
<P>
	Muriqi boxed as an amateur, but never had a chance to become  
known outside Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Serbs didn't give us an opportunity to fight on the  
national team,'' said Muriqi, who lives in New York's Bronx, where 
his father owned a cafe. 
</P>
<P>
	There was knot of vocal supporters waving Albanian flags last  
Saturday night when the 20-year-old Miriqi, a light heavyweight, 
boosted his professional record to 8-0 in a scheduled four-round 
preliminary bout in The Theater at Madison Square Garden. 
</P>
<P>
	Whether Muriqi has the stuff of champions -- and it doesn't take  
as much stuff as used to -- remains to be seen. He is in the capable 
hands of trainer Teddy Atlas, who helped develop Mike Tyson and who 
guided Michael Moorer to the IBF heavyweight title. 
</P>
<P>
	If Muriqi, who turned pro June 19, 1998, has the talent to  
progress, there is no doubt he will be a saleable fighter. 
</P>
<P>
	Against a taller Thomas Barker (1-1-1) in his last fight, Muriqi  
was the aggressor from the outset, and the fight ended at 2:03 of 
the second round shortly after Barker went down to a knee after 
taking a punch to the body. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he is an entertaining fighter,'' said Lou DiBella,  
senior vice president of HBO Sports. ``He has a straight-ahead 
style. He's a great story. If he can continue to win, he will 
become an attraction. He has the market.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Muriqi's father and mother and two brothers immigrated to the  
United States in 1994. The father then got the papers for Muriqi 
and his sisters to come to the United States on May 13, 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Ramiz Muriqi sold the cafe and returned to Kosovo 18 months ago  
to join the KLA, and sister Elinda returned to join it 4 1/2 months 
ago, according to Muriqi. 
</P>
<P>
	``After I retire, I will go home,'' the younger Muriqi said,  
obviously not contemplating an early retirement. 
</P>
<P>
	A growing number of East European fighters have done well since  
the collapse of the Soviet Union. Henry Maske, an Olympic champion 
from East Germany, became a star in the united Germany by winning a 
light heavyweight title. Konstantin Tzyu, a Russian living in 
Australia, won the junior welterweight title and is in position to 
again win a championship in that division. 
</P>
<P>
	Then there are heavyweight contenders Oleg Maskaev and Vitali  
Klitchko of Ukraine, Zeljko Mavrovic of Croatia and Andrew Golota 
of Poland. 
</P>
<P>
	These fighters, however, honed their skills as state-sponsored  
amateurs in international competition. Muriqi will have to learn in 
the chaotic world of professional boxing. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 09:20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Weather News Pinches Grain, Soybeans / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Soybean and grain futures prices fell in early  
trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade amid word that 
forecasts for a Midwest heatwave were exaggerated. 
</P>
<P>
	In early trading today, July soybean futures fell more than 7  
cents a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn and spring wheat rose had risen in the previous day's  
trading due to trader concern that hot, dry weather would damage 
newly planted crops. 
</P>
<P>
	Forecasters, who had been calling for unusually hot temperatures  
next week, now say that a high-pressure ridge in the Midwest has 
weakened. 
</P>
<P>
	In early trading today, wheat for July delivery fell 2 1/4 cents to  
$2.49 3/4 a bushel; July corn fell 2 3/4 cents to $2.14 3/4 a bushel; July 
oats fell 2 cents to $1.12 1/4 a bushel; and July soybeans fell 7 1/4 
cents to $4.58 1/2 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, livestock and meat futures were mostly lower in early  
trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	August live cattle fell 0.05 cent to 63.42 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle broke even at 77.55 cents a pound; August lean hogs 
fell 0.98 cent to 51.72 cents a pound; and August pork bellies fell 
.60 cent to 44.10 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
