<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tektronix To Split Into 2 Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WILSONVILLE, Ore. (AP) -- Tektronix Inc. plans to split into two  
separate, publicly traded companies and sell its video and 
networking division. 
</P>
<P>
	One company will be based on the electronic and scientific  
measurement equipment that has been Tektronix's core product since 
it was founded in 1946 to make oscilloscopes. 
</P>
<P>
	The other will be based on the color printers and imaging  
equipment that has fueled expansion for Tektronix during the growth 
of the desktop computer market. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision to split came as Tektronix announced fourth quarter  
earnings of $24.9 million, or 53 cents per share, down more than 41 
percent from the $42.5 million, or 83 cents per share, earned 
during the fourth quarter in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales also declined slightly, falling to $541.3 million for the  
quarter, compared with $557.9 million for the same period last 
year. For the fiscal year, sales declined 14 percent to $1.9 
billion from $2.1 billion in fiscal 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Tektronix chairman Jerry Meyer said the split was necessary to  
remain competitive in each market. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, both businesses compete for management focus and  
investment dollars,'' Meyer said. ``This plan will allow each 
business to concentrate on its strengths and to respond with 
greater flexibility and speed to the needs of its customers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The new measurement company will be based in Beaverton and keep  
the ``Tektronix'' name. 
</P>
<P>
	The new color printing and imaging company, which has not yet  
been named, will be based at the current company headquarters in 
Wilsonville, just south of Portland. 
</P>
<P>
	Tektronix is considering an initial public offering for about 15  
percent of the new color printing and imaging company prior to the 
end of its current fiscal year. The remaining shares would be 
distributed, on a tax-free basis, to Tektronix shareholders at some 
time after the offering. 
</P>
<P>
	After the companies are separated, Meyer will become chief  
executive officer of the new color printing and imaging company. 
</P>
<P>
	Carl Neun, senior vice president and chief financial officer of  
Tektronix, will become chief executive officer of the new 
measurement company. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
