<HEADLINE> Speidel To Cut Nearly Half Its Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) -- Hirsch Speidel Inc., a maker of  
watchbands and jewelry, is cutting nearly half its work force 
because of lagging sales. 
</P>
<P>
	About 200 of Speidel's 420 jobs at sites here and in neighboring  
East Providence are being eliminated, the company said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Margaret Foley, Speidel's director of human resources, said  
there were a ``multitude of reasons'' for the action, including ``a 
lack of business and being competitive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``There's been a reduction in orders,'' Foley said. She said she  
couldn't disclose details. 
</P>
<P>
	Speidel makes metal and leather watchbands, along with chains,  
identification bracelets and children's jewelry. Speidel sells to 
more than 10,000 retail jewelry stores and mass merchandise stores 
worldwide. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement comes 18 months after Hermann Hirsch USA Inc.,  
an affiliate of an Austrian firm, acquired Speidel from Textron 
Inc. of Providence. After the deal was closed in January 1998, 
Hirsch transferred a New Jersey sales-and-distribution center to 
East Providence. 
</P>
<P>
	But labor problems erupted last August over contract issues  
involving unionized toolmakers, die casters and machine operators. 
</P>
<P>
	Speidel also faces competitive pressures. The U.S. jewelry  
industry has long protested that foreign jewelry makers pay 
relatively low tariffs to sell in the U.S., while domestic 
producers must pay high assessments when trying to sell in places 
such as Southeast Asia or South America. 
</P>
<P>
	Speidel U.S.A. was formed in 1904 by the Speidel family, jewelry  
makers based in Pforzheim, Germany. It was acquired by Textron in 
1964. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
