<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Marines Kill One Assailant in Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- U.S. Marines killed one person and  
wounded two others after coming under fire Wednesday night. No 
Marines were injured, but the shooting underscored the risks facing 
the NATO troops who are trying to restore security after 17 months 
of ethnic war. Meanhwile, foreign and defense ministers of Britain, 
France, Italy and Germany inspected mass graves and other sites 
Wednesday, seeing first-hand evidence of the brutality that raged 
across Kosovo until Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic accepted 
an international peace plan for the shattered province. 

</P>
<P>
	Fieldrest Cannon Workers OK Union  
</P>
<P>
	KANNAPOLIS, N.C. (AP) -- Textile workers at six Fieldcrest Cannon  
plants in the state voted in favor of union representation on 
Wednesday. Of about 5,100 workers, 2,270 voted for joining the 
Union of Needletrades Industrial and Textile Employees, or UNITE, 
and 2,102 voted against. One weaver said she felt the union would 
give workers job protection in the face of plant modernizations. 
Another employee, Susie Lyerly, said, ``I don't feel we need 
someone to speak for us. I've been with this company for 30 years 
and I've fought this union for the last 25 years.'' Fieldcrest 
Cannon workers rejected organizing efforts four times beginning in 
1974. 

</P>
<P>
	Belgian Coke Plants Resum Production  
</P>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- Coca-Cola is expected resume production  
at two Belgian factories Wednesday, two weeks after the first 
reports of illnesses from children who drank the company's soft 
drinks. But a Coca-Cola plant in nearby northern France remained 
closed as judicial officials opened an investigation to determine 
why hundreds of people who drank from cans produced there fell ill. 
Belgium's health minister, Luc Van den Bossche, said that since 
June 9, there had been 249 cases of illnesses reported in Belgium 
by people who drank Coca-Cola products. 

</P>
<P>
	Nasdaq Chief Envisions 24-Hour Trades  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Nasdaq chief Frank Zarb has a vision of what  
the global stock market will be in a few years: digital, open 24 
hours, letting people make trades instantly anywhere from their 
computers, cellphones, pagers and handheld organizers. In a speech 
at the National Press Club, Zarb -- the chairman of the National 
Association of Securities Dealers, which operates the electronic 
Nasdaq Stock Market -- said officials are examining a number of 
structural shifts to allow it to compete in the market of the 
future. 

</P>
<P>
	Credit Suisse Facing Shutdown in Japan  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's Financial Supervisory Agency will likely  
order Credit Suisse Group to close its Japanese operations as early 
as next month for obstructing a probe into whether it helped 
Japanese companies hide losses, a newspaper said Thursday. The 
agency, which oversees Japan's financial industry, may also revoke 
the operating licenses of some member companies of the Swiss 
financial group, the Nihon Keizai newspaper reported. An official 
at the agency could not be reached for comment. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Close Up  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The Nikkei Stock Average closed at 17,628.32 points  
on the Tokyo Stock Exchange Thursday, up 41.57 points from 
Wednesday. 

</P>
<P>
	Spurs Beat Knicks 96-89  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Closing with a 10-5 run, the San Antonio Spurs  
defeated the New York Knicks 96-89 Wednesday night to take a 3-1 
lead in the NBA Finals. No NBA team has ever recovered from such a 
deficit in the finals. This was a true team effort, not just a 
bunch of guys riding along on the coattails of Tim Duncan and David 
Robinson, who scored 28 and 14 points, respectively. Mario Elie had 
18, Avery Johnson and Sean Elliott scored 14 apiece as all of San 
Antonio's starters reached double figures. 
</P>
<P>
		   Padres Paste Dodgers 6-2  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Eric Owens and Reggie Sanders hit consecutive  
home runs in the fifth inning as San Diego beat the Los Angeles 
Dodgers 6-2 Wednesday night for the Padres' fifth straight victory. 
San Diego, which won the series opener 4-1, will go for a 
three-game sweep Thursday night. The Padres already are assured of 
winning their first road series of the season. Woody Williams 
pitched eight-plus innings, giving up two runs and five hits. 
Trevor Hoffman, who entered in the ninth with runners on first and 
second, got the final three outs for his 17th save. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief By LISI de BOURBON  

  	   	
</P>
