<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 14:50:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Flockhart Returns to Stage Roots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *An AP Entertainment Review    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Before there was Calista Flockhart, star of  
television's ``Ally McBeal,'' there was Calista Flockhart, stage 
actress. 
</P>
<P>
	Now on summer hiatus from her hit TV show, Flockhart has  
returned to the theater in ``Bash,'' a trio of grim monologues 
written by Neil LaBute, director of such disturbing films as ``In 
the Company of Men'' and ``Your Friends and Neighbors.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The plays, on view at off-Broadway's Douglas Fairbanks Theater,  
are a long way from sweet, insecure ``Ally'' -- and not nearly as 
interesting. 
</P>
<P>
	These three one-acts are short, superficial studies of evil with  
pretensions of Greek tragedy. The stories are horrific, but not all 
that compelling, primarily because they seem more like acting 
exercises than plays. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet give Flockhart and her two cohorts, Ron Eldard and Paul  
Rudd, credit for working hard during the star's vacation. Under Joe 
Mantello's astute, sensitive direction, they make the most of the 
works' theatricality. 
</P>
<P>
	Flockhart is up first, in a piece entitled ``Medea Redux.''  
You've guessed the plot already. It's police interrogation time, 
and a chain-smoking woman is giving the facts of her murderous deed 
to authorities. She details her affair, as a 13-year-old, with one 
of her high school teachers, a man who left town as soon as he 
found out she was pregnant. 
</P>
<P>
	The woman -- blue-collar and as she puts it, ``never the queen of  
education'' -- raises the boy herself. Loyal to a fault, she refuses 
to reveal the father's identity, but then, nearly 15 years later, 
goes to visit her long-lost love with their teen-age son in tow. 
The results are more than unsettling, but don't ring true. Wouldn't 
she have developed a bond with the youngster during the intervening 
years? 
</P>
<P>
	Flockhart slums credibly, projecting a realistic low-class  
demeanor. She is not afraid to put herself out on a limb, even to 
the point of transforming herself physically into one scary-looking 
woman, haunted and almost demonlike in her appearance. Her tale is 
not nearly as riveting. 
</P>
<P>
	A similar story of loss, this time the death of a baby girl,  
anchors the equally uncomfortable ``Iphigenia in Orem.'' Eldard 
plays a twangy traveling businessman, talking to an unseen woman he 
has picked up in a hotel bar. 
</P>
<P>
	The man talks about his young daughter's suffocation, which  
supposedly occurred while he was asleep in the living room. 
Intertwined with this tragedy is his employment history, spotty at 
best, which figures prominently in his story and provides one of 
the evening's few surprises. 
</P>
<P>
	Eldard captures the folksiness and ingratiating style of a good  
ol' boy slowly going to seed. He is a man who, underneath the 
smiles and handshakes, is misogynistic, especially toward the women 
who work with him. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet this story's horror also appears contrived, inserted into  
the story more to shock than explain. 
</P>
<P>
	After intermission, Flockhart returns, this time with Rudd, for  
``Bash (A Gaggle of Saints),'' dual monologues whose title has a 
double meaning. Two college sweethearts from Boston are in New York 
City for a big bash with some friends. While the girls celebrate in 
a ritzy hotel, the guys go to Central Park where they participate 
in a gay-bashing. 
</P>
<P>
	It is the most effective of the three pieces, primarily because  
of Rudd. He plays the vicious ringleader, initially with a boyish 
likability that turns sharply into something else. His sudden 
change, after getting laughs and support from the audience, makes 
the piece all the more disturbing. 
</P>
<P>
	LaBute alternates between stark, matter-of-fact descriptions of  
the attack and details of a fun weekend in New York. The contrast 
is effectively pulled off by Flockhart, here buoyantly girlish, and 
Rudd, who finds the right degree of chilly banality to describe the 
man's evil deeds. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the considerable appeal of its actors, ``Bash'' offers  
an unconvincing look at the dark side of human nature. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 16:40:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Textile Union Claims Southern Win </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KANNAPOLIS, N.C. (AP) -- A union claimed the biggest organizing  
victory ever in the Southern textile industry Thursday after an 
election to represent 5,000 workers at six Fieldcrest Cannon mills. 
</P>
<P>
	The apparent victory came in a state and an industry that have  
long been hostile to organized labor. Twenty-five years ago, a 
woman's organizing efforts at a textile mill 200 miles away 
inspired the movie ``Norma Rae.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew it eventually would happen, but I didn't think it would  
happen in my lifetime,'' said Fieldcrest employee Tracy Moody. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fieldcrest Cannon workers voted Tuesday and Wednesday to be  
represented by the Union of Needletrades Industrial and Textile 
Employees. Four previous attempts in the past 25 years to unionize 
the workers had failed. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Labor Relations Board still must validate the  
2,270-2,102 outcome. Both the company and union challenged about 
285 votes each. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is history, it really is,'' said a disappointed Chuck  
Hansen, president of Pillowtex Corp., Fieldcrest's parent company. 
``Someone who writes history will add another paragraph to the 
book.'' 
</P>
<P>
	AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney said it was the largest union  
victory in a Southern textile mill in history. 
</P>
<P>
	North Carolina has one of the lowest percentages of unionized  
workers in the nation, 4.2 percent of wage and hourly employees. 
</P>
<P>
	``The unions, when it came to North Carolina, used to say, `Why  
bother?''' said University of South Carolina history professor Tom 
Terrill, who has written about labor issues in the South. 
</P>
<P>
	North Carolina has more textile jobs than any other state,  
166,800, a number that has been steadily dropping for six decades 
because of modernization, increased imports and the shifting of 
jobs overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1994, UNITED won the right to represent 2,200 workers at the  
Tulex Corp. in Martinsville, Va. 
</P>
<P>
	This election was the first since Fieldcrest was bought by  
Dallas-based Pillowtex, and lacked the rancor of the earlier union 
drives dating to 1974. 
</P>
<P>
	Labor experts said the state's tight labor market might have  
been a big factor. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been talking to a lot of clothing manufacturers and one  
of the problems they bring up all the time is the shortage of 
skilled labor,'' said Ian Taplin, a Wake Forest University 
professor who studies labor-management issues. ``This could make 
management more tolerant about considering a union.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Taplin said UNITE did a good job of sizing up what it needed to  
do to win this time, including picking young, college-educated 
organizers. 
</P>
<P>
	``These ones are good at alerting the public about what is  
happening,'' he said. ``And they let the government know when there 
are violations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 1979 movie ``Norma Rae'' depicted the resistance that  
organizers faced while trying to unionize North Carolina textile 
workers. The movie, starring Sally Fields, was based on the real 
story of Crystal Lee Sutton's efforts to organize a J.P. Stevens 
plant in Roanoke Rapids. 
</P>
<P>
	The top election issues here were $50 million in modernization  
and job changes that have occurred since Pillowtex purchased 
Fieldcrest in 1997 for $700 million. Union organizers said change 
was displacing workers. 
</P>
<P>
	Fieldcrest Cannon makes towels, sheets and comforters under the  
names Royal Velvet, Cannon, Touch of Class and Charisma. Pillowtex 
makes bed pillows, mattress pads, blankets and down comforters 
under the Ralph Lauren, Disney and Martha Stewart names. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 14:20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Sets Aside Disability Ruling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court set aside a ruling Thursday  
that said New York officials had discriminated against a law school 
graduate who failed the state's bar examination five times. 
</P>
<P>
	The justices told a federal appeals court to restudy its ruling  
in light of their decisions this week limiting the reach of the 
federal Americans With Disabilities Act, which bans discrimination 
against the disabled. 
</P>
<P>
	In three rulings Tuesday, the justices narrowed significantly  
just whom the 1990 law protects. People with physical impairments 
that can be treated with medication or devices such as eyeglasses 
or hearing aids generally are not protected by the law, the court 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the New York case acted on Thursday, the law school graduate  
had argued, successfully in lower courts, that her reading disorder 
qualified her for protection under the federal law. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal trial judge and the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals  
agreed with Marilyn Bartlett, a college instructor who earned a 
Ph.D. in educational administration from New York University 
despite her disability but has flunked the New York bar exam five 
times. 
</P>
<P>
	The lower courts ruled that the board of examiners, which  
administers the state bar exam, had discriminated against Bartlett 
by failing to accommodate her and now must pay her monetary 
damages. 
</P>
<P>
	Bartlett, a teacher, had wanted additional time to complete the  
test and the right to mark answers for the multiple-choice portion 
in a question book rather than on a computerized answer sheet. Her 
requests were denied. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal law bans discrimination against a ``qualified  
individual with a disability'' because of that disability. A 
disability is defined as a condition that substantially limits a 
major life activity. 
</P>
<P>
	In its ruling last September, the appeals court said Bartlett's  
disability affects reading and learning, major life activities, and 
was entitled to some accommodations the first four times she took 
the bar exam. 
</P>
<P>
	``Reasonable accommodation of this disability will enable her to  
compete fairly with others in taking the examination so that it 
will be her mastery of the legal skills and knowledge that the exam 
is designed to test -- and not her disability -- that determines 
whether or not she achieves a passing score,'' the appeals court 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The trial judge had ordered the board of examiners to pay  
Bartlett $12,500 in damages, but the appeals court told the judge 
to recalculate the damages in a way that will award her no more 
than $10,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Bartlett, a graduate of the Vermont Law School, began taking the  
New York bar exam in 1991. She sued in 1993, and in July of that 
year was permitted to take the test with the accommodations she 
sought. She nevertheless failed it. 
</P>
<P>
	The damages award, however, was aimed at compensating Bartlett  
for the four times she was forced to take the test without the 
accommodations she had sought. 
</P>
<P>
	In the appeal acted on Thursday, New York Attorney General Eliot  
Spitzer argued that a person ``suffering from a reading impairment 
who has developed self-accommodating techniques which allow her to 
read at a speed and in a manner comparable to that of an average 
person'' should not be covered by the federal anti-bias law. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for Bartlett urged the justices to reject the appeal,  
saying that it does not conflict with the ruling of any other 
appeals court. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is New York Board of Law Examiners vs. Bartlett,  
98-1285. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
