<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Seeks Hispanic Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Improving education and reducing poverty go  
hand-in-hand, Texas Gov. George W. Bush said in a call for unity 
and a bid for Hispanic support. 
</P>
<P>
	Campaigning for the Republican presidential nomination in  
Detroit's Mexicantown, Bush cited his proposals for charter schools 
and school vouchers in Texas as an example of how high education 
standards and accountability can work. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they aren't learning, we ought to blow the whistle on  
failure,'' he said. ``It's important to free parents to make 
choices.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush arrived to the sound of Mexican folk music as he waded  
through about 300 people packed in a small park in a predominantly 
Hispanic neighborhood on Detroit's south side. 
</P>
<P>
	He began in Spanish, then abruptly changed to English.  
</P>
<P>
	``If you address education, you address poverty. The two go  
hand-in-hand,'' Bush said. ``I know if schools fail, the economy 
fails as well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He spent most of the 30-minute visit posing for snapshots and  
autographing signs that read ``Viva George Bush.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush said the Hispanic vote will be important next year, and  
equality and unity will lead to his success on that front. 
</P>
<P>
	``The message has got to be, 'The American dream has got to  
stand for you as well,''' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Maria Elena Rodriguez, president of the Mexicantown Community  
Development Corp., said she was surprised Bush accepted her 
invitation to visit the area so quickly. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's fully aware of the fact that demographics are changing in  
this country,'' Mrs. Rodriguez said later. ``That he has come here 
is significant because he knows we're on the way up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thursday night at a $1,000-a-plate fund-raising dinner in  
Livonia, Bush elaborated on the need for better education, saying 
he wants to give more authority to states to regulate and set 
standards for their schools. 
</P>
<P>
	He also talked about the importance of the presidential office.  
</P>
<P>
	``When I put my hand on the Bible, I will swear not only to  
uphold the laws of the land, I will swear to uphold the dignity and 
honor of the office,'' Bush said. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement, Michigan Democratic Party Chairman Mark Brewer  
called Bush's campaign of ``compassionate conservatism'' a cover-up 
for a ``right-wing, extremist agenda.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said Bush's school voucher plan would ``rob public schools of  
valuable resources.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
