<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rockies' Lansing To Have Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Colorado Rockies second baseman Mike Lansing, out  
since May with back pain, is scheduled to have surgery next week to 
repair a bulging disc. He likely will miss the remainder of the 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is something that I think needs to be done,'' Lansing  
said Thursday, ``because then I take care of it, and I don't have 
to worry in the back of my mind next year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The setback is the latest for Lansing since he was traded to  
Colorado from Montreal on Nov. 18, 1997. He played through the pain 
last season and hit a disappointing .276 with 12 homers. Lansing 
also had a bout with Bell's Palsy in the offseason. 
</P>
<P>
	The outlook appeared better in 1999 as Lansing hit .310 with  
four homers and 15 RBIs in 35 games. He showed more range at second 
base before the bulging disc compressed a nerve, causing loss of 
feeling in his left leg. 
</P>
<P>
	``I tried to look at everything before I decided this -- the big  
picture and everything,'' Lansing said. ``I may not come back this 
year, and that could be the worst thing that happens. But I could 
be 100 percent next year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lansing, 31, is in the second season of a $23.25 million,  
four-year contract. He also had back surgery in 1988 while playing 
at Wichita State. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a different disc,'' he said. ``The MRI showed that my  
disc that I had previous surgery on is fine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Lansing's absence, the Rockies have used Lenny Harris, Kurt  
Abbott, Terry Shumpert, Chris Petersen and Chris Sexton at second 
base. 
</P>
<P>
	Petersen and Sexton are playing at Triple-A Colorado Springs,  
while Shumpert and Abbott have combined for seven homers and 22 
RBIs in 31 games. The pair figure to get the bulk of the playing 
time as Lansing goes through his rehabilitation. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Thursday, the Rockies decided not to place right-handed  
reliever Jerry Dipoto on the disabled list. 
</P>
<P>
	Dipoto has been battling back problems for the past two weeks,  
but an MRI and a bone scan were negative. He will miss Friday 
night's game in San Diego and plans to throw on the side Saturday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
