<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cisneros Lawyer Examines Ex's Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A lawyer defending former Housing Secretary  
Henry Cisneros on conspiracy and obstruction charges sought 
Thursday to show the government's chief witness is motivated to 
cooperate with prosecutors to cut short a prison term. 
</P>
<P>
	The witness, ex-Cisneros mistress Linda Jones, said Thursday the  
government's special prosecutors have pledged to support reducing 
her 3 1/2-year prison sentence if she cooperates fully. But she denied 
that she had gotten prison furloughs, fancy hotel rooms, visitors 
or other special benefits since coming to Washington on June 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Jones signed an agreement earlier this year with Independent  
Counsel David Barrett's office in which she promised complete and 
truthful cooperation in the government's prosecution of Cisneros 
and two former aides. 
</P>
<P>
	In exchange, Barrett has pledged to file a recommendation with a  
federal judge in Texas supporting a reduced sentence. He also will 
consider dismissing two remaining charges against her. 
</P>
<P>
	Cisneros' lawyer, Brendan Sullivan, questioned her about the  
deal. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're going to do your best to cooperate with them in order  
to ensure this agreement remains effective, am I correct?'' 
Sullivan asked. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yes,'' Ms. Jones answered.  
</P>
<P>
	Under questioning from prosecutor Mark Jackowski, Ms. Jones said  
the agreement requires truthful testimony. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Jones, who previously went by her married name Medlar, is  
serving a 3 1/2-year prison sentence at a federal medical facility 
in Fort Worth, Texas. She pleaded guilty last year to 28 counts 
involving fraud, conspiracy, money laundering and obstruction after 
becoming a target of Barrett's investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Her earlier immunity was revoked after prosecutors caught her in  
a series of lies about evidence, including her false claim that 
tapes she secretly made of telephone conversations with Cisneros 
and provided to the government were originals. 
</P>
<P>
	She testified for four days this week at a pre-trial hearing to  
determine whether the tapes can be used at Cisneros' September 
trial on 18 felony counts of conspiracy, obstructing justice and 
making false statements to the FBI. 
</P>
<P>
	Cisneros, a former San Antonio mayor who headed the Department  
of Housing and Urban Development from 1993 to 1996, has pleaded 
innocent. 
</P>
<P>
	He was indicted in late 1997 on charges he conspired with Ms.  
Jones to conceal more than $250,000 in payments to her before and 
during his service in the Clinton administration. 
</P>
<P>
	While on the stand this week, Ms. Jones had to admit repeatedly  
that she lied often during the investigation and in the legal 
proceedings involving her breach-of-contract lawsuit against 
Cisneros. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the lies dealt with the authenticity of the 88 tapes she  
made as her relationship with Cisneros soured and she scrambled to 
obtain proof of his verbal commitment for financial support. 
</P>
<P>
	All 88 are copies, even though she represented the tapes as  
originals to FBI and agents of the Internal Revenue Service; the 
originals were destroyed long ago. 
</P>
<P>
	She testified that as many as 10 tapes were edited to delete  
passages where she threatened to go public with what she later 
conceded was ``hush money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The defense contends the tapes are inadmissible because they  
constitute ``tampered'' evidence. 
</P>
<P>
	Under questioning from prosecutor Jackowski, Ms. Jones said she  
never fabricated conversations by splicing together different 
sections of tape. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only thing that was done was words were taken out,'' she  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cisneros told the FBI agents conducting his Cabinet background  
check that he had given Ms. Jones financial support. But 
prosecutors contend he falsely told the FBI he never paid Ms. Jones 
more than $2,500 at one time or more than $10,000 annually. The 
indictment alleges that he paid her more than $264,000 between 1990 
and 1993, in installments as high as $15,000. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
