<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cisneros' Ex-Lover Admits Lies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Defense lawyers are charging that the  
government's chief witness in the conspiracy case against former 
Housing Secretary Henry Cisneros is lying from the witness stand 
during a pivotal pretrial hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	Cisneros' former lover, Linda Jones, has admitted over three  
days of testimony that she lied repeatedly in the past to federal 
agents investigating the former Clinton Cabinet member, as well as 
under oath during civil proceedings in Texas, to her lawyers and 
various media organizations. 
</P>
<P>
	But the litany of lies hasn't stopped, Cisneros lawyer Barry  
Simon charged Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are going to bring in witnesses to say she is lying today  
from the witness stand,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``From '94, in every way, shape or form, the witness has  
committed perjury, committed obstruction of justice, lied 
repeatedly to the FBI, lied repeatedly to the IRS and is in jail 
for lying,'' Simon said, adding sarcastically, ``and the government 
offers us this witness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Jones, who previously went by her married name Medlar, has  
acknowledged a pattern of lies revolving around the authenticity of 
tapes she secretly recorded during phone conversations with 
Cisneros as their relationship foundered. 
</P>
<P>
	But she testified she had no choice but to repeat those lies to  
successive waves of questioners after her first misrepresentation 
of the recordings as unaltered originals. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had gotten myself into a box and didn't know how to get  
out,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Jones said she altered ``five or six'' of the 88 recordings  
to erase threats she made against Cisneros. After learning from her 
attorneys that the passages could prove legally troublesome, she 
said she edited out the threats -- and then had to lie again and 
again about the tapes' authenticity to protect herself. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Stanley Sporkin, who must rule on the tapes'  
admissibility, expressed amazement at the web of lies. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm astounded when I sit here and listen to what has happened  
in this case. I guess there are people in this country who don't 
know how to tell the truth,'' he said. But, he added, ``What I have 
to determine is: Is she telling the truth in front of me?''' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Jones' current credibility is key as the government presses  
to introduce 34 of the 88 tapes at Cisneros' September trial on 
charges he conspired with her and others to conceal from the FBI 
the scope of his payments to her. Sporkin's ruling will follow the 
hearing, which continues through Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The tapes are key, prosecutor Mark Jackowski conceded Wednesday.  
``They are evidence out of the defendant's own mouth,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Cisneros' team contends the tapes are inadmissible because  
they are copies that have been ``tampered'' with, not originals, 
and because Ms. Jones had an unlawful intent in making them. 
</P>
<P>
	She admitted Wednesday that although she didn't initially  
consider Cisneros' financial support ``hush money,'' she later came 
to see it as that. ``I do believe now that, at the end, it was 
(hush money) because I was threatening him,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cisneros acknowledged to the FBI agents conducting his Cabinet  
background check that he had given Ms. Jones financial support. The 
payments began after their affair was widely publicized, ending her 
marriage and career as a political fund-raiser. 
</P>
<P>
	But prosecutors contend Cisneros falsely told the FBI that he  
never paid Ms. Jones more than $2,500 at one time or more than 
$10,000 annually. The indictment alleges that he paid her more than 
$264,000 between 1990 and 1993, in installments as high as $15,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Cisneros, who served as HUD secretary from 1993 to 1996, pleaded  
innocent after being indicted in December 1997 on 18 felony counts 
of conspiracy, obstructing justice and making false statements to 
the FBI. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Jones' misrepresentation about the tapes landed her in hot  
water with the special prosecutors, who had initially provided her 
immunity. She pleaded guilty last year to fraud, conspiracy, money 
laundering and obstruction, and is serving a 3 1/2-year prison 
sentence at a federal medical facility in Fort Worth. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on her cooperation at trial, she could be freed early from  
prison. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
