<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nuclear Power Plant Stakes Sold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- Niagara Mohawk Power Corp. and New York  
State Electric &AMP; Gas Corp. are selling their interests in the Nine 
Mile Point 1 and 2 nuclear plants to an international power 
conglomerate for $163.2 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Once ranked among the nation's worst-run plants, the two Nine  
Mile Point plants have operated at record levels in recent years. 
Both reactors are located on Lake Ontario, about 45 miles north of 
Syracuse, in a complex that also includes the state-owned James A. 
FitzPatrick nuclear plant. 
</P>
<P>
	AmerGen, a partnership between British Energy PLC and PECO  
Energy Co. of Philadelphia, will pay Niagara Mohawk $63.6 million 
for its 41 percent ownership share of Nine Mile 2 and NYSEG will 
receive $27.9 million for its 18 percent ownership share. Three 
other utilities that own a part of Nine Mile 2 were not involved in 
the sale that was announced Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Niagara Mohawk also will receive $71 .7 million for Nine Mile 1,  
which it wholly owns and operates. 
</P>
<P>
	AmerGen chief executive officer Dickinson M. Smith said the  
company will continue to run both Nine Mile Point plants, which 
employ 1,330 workers. 
</P>
<P>
	``This sale will protect customers and shareholders from  
unforeseen operating and decommissioning costs. In addition, the 
sale to AmerGen puts the plants in the hands of a proven operator 
committed to pursuing growth in the nuclear generation business,'' 
said William E. Davis, Niagara Mohawk's chief executive officer. 
</P>
<P>
	AmerGen was formed in 1997 as a joint venture by PECO Energy,  
one of the nation's largest utilities, and the Edinburgh, 
Scotland-based British Energy, the United Kingdom's largest power 
generator, to purchase and operate nuclear plants in the United 
States. 
</P>
<P>
	The Philadelphia-based AmerGen also has deals pending to buy  
three other nuclear plants: Clinton Power Station in Illinois, 
Vermont Yankee in Vermont and Three Mile Island Unit 1 in 
Pennsylvania. AmerGen's goal is to buy about 20 nuclear plants in 
the next five years. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith said it would take six to nine months to receive the  
necessary regulatory approval for the sale. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to Niagara Mohawk and NYSEG, the other Nine Mile 2  
co-owners are Long Island Power Authority (18 percent), Rochester 
Gas and Electric Corp. (14 percent) and Central Hudson Gas &AMP; 
Electric Corp. (9 percent). Options available to the co-owners 
include matching the AmerGen offer, participating in the sale, or 
retaining their ownership interest. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of the deregulation of the power industry in New York,  
both Niagara Mohawk and NYSEG decided last year to get out of the 
energy production business and energy suppliers. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
