<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reno Announces Anti-Violence Grant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Abused and neglected children are the most  
likely to commit crimes, Attorney General Janet Reno said Thursday 
in announcing a $1.3 million grant to study the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	Children who grow up being abused by family members ``come to  
accept violence as a way of life,'' Reno told more than 150 child, 
health and legal experts here at the close of a three-day national 
summit on children's exposure to violence. 
</P>
<P>
	Not only must communities protect children by counseling abusive  
parents and caretakers, but, she said, ``We have to start teaching 
children ways to resolve conflict without using guns, knives and 
fists. We do not have to be such a violent nation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yale University's Child Study Center will receive the money to  
study the link between abuse and neglect victims and later criminal 
acts and to help communities nationwide come up with ways to 
prevent children from being hurt, protect those who are abused and 
steer them away from committing violence later in their lives. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1998, the Justice Department reported, 2.8 million teens were  
victims of violent crimes such as rape and murder. 
</P>
<P>
	The department also issued guidelines on how police and  
prosecutors can work with community centers and schools to counsel 
and interview young victims and prepare them for court testimony, 
and how to fight Internet users who try to solicit sex from 
children. 
</P>
<P>
	The summit -- called by President Clinton last fall -- mostly  
addressed the issue of child abuse, but the department also 
released figures Thursday showing that a childhood of abuse can 
lead to a life of crime. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, children who were abused or neglected were:  
</P>
<P>
	--50 percent more likely to have a juvenile record.  
</P>
<P>
	--40 percent more likely to become violent adult offenders.  
</P>
<P>
	--33 percent more likely to abuse drugs and alcohol.  
</P>
<P>
	The summit also covered children's exposure to media violence.  
</P>
<P>
	William E. Kennard, the chairman of the Federal Communications  
Commission, announced that 11 newspapers and TV Guide will join 
hundreds of other newspapers in publishing program ratings in their 
television listings. Kennard said these ratings, along with the 
v-chip technology to block programming, would help parents screen 
shows they think are inappropriate for their children. 
</P>
<P>
	Summit participants, such as child psychologists, police  
officers, educators and social workers, produced an ``action plan'' 
that called for grassroots prevention programs, tougher gun control 
and crime legislation and more funding for child protective 
services and mental health care. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Ted Kennedy, the Senate's Democrat leader on education,  
asked participants to help Congress come up with ways to make 
schools safer, adding that child violence was a problem long before 
this spring's school shootings in Colorado and Georgia. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were still losing 13 children a day'' to gun violence, said  
Kennedy, D-Mass. ``They are 25 percent of the population, but 100 
percent of our future. We ought to get it right.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
