<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Justices Reject Pakistani's Appeal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Pakistani man sentenced to death for the  
1993 fatal shootings of two CIA employees outside the spy agency's 
headquarters lost a Supreme Court appeal Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The justices, without comment, rejected an appeal in which Mir  
Aimal Kasi argued he should be allowed to challenge his seizure by 
FBI agents in Pakistan after a global manhunt. 
</P>
<P>
	He said his FBI arrest in his homeland violated the  
Constitution's ban on unreasonable seizures. 
</P>
<P>
	The court ended its 1998-99 term Wednesday when the justices  
left the bench and began a summer recess, but the court's clerk 
Thursday issued scores of orders from the justices. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said Kasi opened fire with an AK-47 assault rifle  
outside CIA headquarters in Virginia during the Jan. 25, 1993 
morning rush hour. CIA employees Frank Darling and Lansing Bennett 
were killed as they sat in their cars at a stop light, and three 
other men were wounded. 
</P>
<P>
	Kasi had been living in Virginia but returned to Pakistan the  
day after the shootings. His roommate soon reported him missing to 
police, who searched Kasi's apartment and found the weapon used in 
the shootings. 
</P>
<P>
	Kasi eluded FBI agents for over four years before they seized  
him in a hotel room in Pakistan and returned him to the United 
States. He confessed to the slayings during the return flight, 
saying he was angry over CIA meddling in Muslim nations. 
</P>
<P>
	Kasi was tried and convicted in a Virginia state court in  
November 1997, and was sentenced to death. The Virginia Supreme 
Court upheld his convictions and sentence last November. 
</P>
<P>
	Kasi's lawyers said his seizure violated his constitutional  
rights and an extradition treaty between the United States and 
Pakistan, and that Virginia courts failed to force the government 
to produce evidence that might weigh in his favor. 
</P>
<P>
	Virginia Attorney General Mark L. Earley urged the justices to  
reject Kasi's appeal, saying the justices ruled in 1990 that the 
Fourth Amendment does not restrain government agents' actions 
against non-citizens outside the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Kasi vs. Virginia, 98-1812.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
