<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Money Funds Fell in Latest Week / Money Market Funds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Assets of the nation's retail money market  
mutual funds fell by $2.03 billion in the latest week to $862.56 
billion, the Investment Company Institute said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Assets of taxable money market funds in the retail category fell  
by $286.5 million to $716.56 billion for the week ended Wednesday, 
June 23, the Washington-based mutual fund trade group said. The 
tax-exempt fund assets fell by $1.75 billion to $146.01 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Assets of the institutional money market funds increased by  
$2.77 billion to $592.03 billion for the same period. Among 
institutional funds, taxable money market fund assets rose by $3.42 
billion to $544.36 billion; assets of the tax-exempt funds fell by 
$647.8 million to $47.67 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Total money market assets stood at $1.455 trillion for the week.  
</P>
<P>
	Assets for the previous week were revised to $1.454 billion to  
reflect reporting errors and a change in the number of funds 
reporting. 
</P>
<P>
	The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds fell in  
the week ended Tuesday to 4.28 percent from 4.31 percent the 
previous week, said IBC's Money Fund Report, a trade journal 
published in Ashland, Mass., by IBC Financial Data Inc. The 30-day 
average yield held steady at the previous week's 4.30 percent, IBC 
Financial Data said. 
</P>
<P>
	The seven-day compounded yield fell to 4.37 percent from 4.40  
percent the previous week, and the 30-day compounded yield was 
unchanged at 4.39 percent, IBC Financial Data said. 
</P>
<P>
	The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was  
58 days, down from 59 days, IBC Financial Data said. 
</P>
<P>
	The online service bankrate.com said its survey of 100 leading  
commercial banks, savings and loan associations and savings banks 
in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the annual percentage 
yield available on money market accounts fell to 2.03 percent as of 
Wednesday from 2.04 percent a week earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based unit of Intelligent Life Corp.  
said the annual percentage yield available on interest-bearing 
checking accounts fell to 0.87 percent from 0.88 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Bankrate.com said the annual percentage yield was 4.15 percent  
on six-month certificates of deposit, up from 4.14 percent the 
previous week. Yields were 4.48 percent on 1-year CDs, up from 4.45 
percent; 4.68 percent on 2 1/2-year CDs, up from 4.66 percent; and 
4.85 percent on 5-year CDs, up from 4.81 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
