<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> North Korea 3, Denmark 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Jo Song Ok scored her second goal in two  
games as surprising North Korea dominated Denmark 3-1 Thursday 
night and put itself in position to advance from Group A into the 
quarterfinals of the Women's World Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	North Korea's quick, physical play frustrated Denmark from the  
first minute of play. The North Koreans scored twice in the first 
half and then held on for their first World Cup victory after 
building their lead to 3-0 late in the game. North Korea lost 2-1 
to Nigeria in its opening match and plays the United States Sunday 
in Foxboro Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	North Korea scored first when Jin Pyol Hui left-footed the ball  
into an untended goal in the 15th minute of the match. Danish 
keeper Dorthe Larson left the box in an attempt to intercept a pass 
by Sol Yong Suk, who set up Jin perfectly on the left side a few 
yards inside the penalty box. 
</P>
<P>
	Jo Song Ok's second goal of the tournament was a beauty, putting  
North Korea ahead 2-0 in the 38th minute. Just outside the penalty 
box she spurted past one defender, slipped the ball between the 
legs of a second and drilled a left-footed shot past Larson into 
the left top corner of the net. 
</P>
<P>
	North Korea led 3-0 in the 72nd minute when Kim Kum Sil  
left-footed a loose ball in front of the goal into an empty net 
after Larson fell down in traffic. The ball came Kim's way after a 
corner kick had bounce off one of her teammates. 
</P>
<P>
	Denmark, which opened with a 3-0 loss to the United States,  
scored its first goal of the tournament in the 74th minute off a 
mistake by keeper Kye Tong Sun, who punched a shot on goal instead 
of catching it. The ball bounced at the feet of Janni Johansen, who 
slipped the ball past a defender and into the left corner. 
</P>
<P>
	Denmark had two near-goals in the first half. Jane Rasmussen's  
header off a cross hit the near-post just below the upper angle in 
the 31st minute. Just before the half, Louise Hansen hit the top of 
the bar just over the hand of keeper Kye. 
</P>
<P>
	The Danes appeared upset by the wet field, which was inundated  
after a downpour occurred for about an hour before the game began. 
Two Danes slipped while kicking the ball during the first minute of 
play, including forward Marlene Kristensen, who appear to injure 
her right knee and was taken from the field by ambulance. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
