<HEADLINE> Senate Remains Deadlocked on HMOs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- For a third straight day, Democrats stymied  
action Thursday on an agriculture spending bill, trying to add 
pieces of their patients' bill of rights. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott set a series of votes for  
Monday that would end the debate. He needs 60 votes to move ahead, 
but will not get them if all 45 Democrats stick together. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers from both parties expressed frustration, saying they  
had compromised again and again only to have the other side refuse 
to be reasonable. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats said Republicans were unwilling to vote on their  
amendments strengthening a GOP bill giving patients new rights when 
dealing with their doctors. 
</P>
<P>
	``They feel all we ought to do is pass this shell bill they've  
got and call it a day,'' said the Senate's top Democrat, Tom 
Daschle of South Dakota. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans said Democrats would never agree to anything because  
Democrats really want to use the issue in next year's election. 
</P>
<P>
	``I begin to wonder, do we want to address this issue or do we  
just want the issue?'' said Lott, R-Miss. ``I've been through that 
before.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
