<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kopp Indicted in Death of NY Doctor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- A county grand jury today indicted James  
Kopp for the slaying of the abortion provider who was gunned down 
through his kitchen window as he was heating soup. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-count indictment charges Kopp with the second-degree  
murder of Dr. Barnett Slepian, first-degree reckless endangerment 
and criminal possession of a weapon. The state charges supersede 
murder charges filed in May by local police. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal grand jury continues to hear evidence in the Oct. 23  
shooting. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this month, Kopp was added to the FBI's Ten Most Wanted  
List. As one of the country's most sought-after alleged criminals, 
his name and picture now appear in post offices and police stations 
all over the world and on the FBI's Internet site. 
</P>
<P>
	FBI agent Bernard Tolbert said investigators had received  
numerous leads since Kopp was added to the most-wanted list, but 
none had panned out. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm confident one day we will get the right tip,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Besides the state charges, Kopp is charged in a federal  
complaint with violating the Freedom of Access to Clinic Entrances 
Act by using deadly force against an abortion doctor. 
</P>
<P>
	The second-degree murder charge against Kopp carries a potential  
prison term of 15 years to life. There is no evidence to warrant a 
first-degree murder charge, Erie County District Attorney Frank 
Clark said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
