<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 20:17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hockey Hall of Famer Ivan Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Chicago Blackhawks vice president Thomas N. Ivan,  
who won Stanley Cups as both a coach and general manager in a Hall 
of Fame career that spanned nearly 60 years, has died. He was 88. 
</P>
<P>
	Ivan died Thursday at Lake Forest Hospital in suburban Chicago  
several days after being admitted for treatment of a kidney 
ailment. 
</P>
<P>
	A native of Toronto, Ivan never played in the National Hockey  
League. His playing career ended with an injury in the 1930s while 
playing on a junior amateur team in Ontario. 
</P>
<P>
	After coaching amateur hockey, he scouted and coached junior  
hockey for the Detroit Red Wings, then coached Omaha in the Central 
League, which had a young player named Gordie Howe. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1947, Ivan was named head coach of the Red Wings. In seven  
seasons, he coached Detroit to six first-place finishes and three 
Stanley Cups. 
</P>
<P>
	He also coached the NHL All Stars to victory over the Stanley  
Cup champion Toronto Maple Leafs in the first official All Star 
Game in 1947. 
</P>
<P>
	Hired as general manager of Chicago, Ivan rebuilt the  
Blackhawks' farm system and skillfully drafted players. He was 
responsible for bringing future Hall of Famers Bobby Hull, Stan 
Mikita and Glenn Hall to the Blackhawks. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1961, Chicago won the Stanley Cup, and from 1962 to 1973 the  
Blackhawks reached the Stanley Cup finals four more times. 
</P>
<P>
	Ivan was inducted into the Hockey Hall of Fame in 1974.  
</P>
<P>
	In 1977, after serving as Blackhawks' general manager for a  
quarter century, Ivan was named vice president and alternate 
governor. 
</P>
<P>
	Ivan is survived by four children, eight grandchildren and four  
great grandchildren. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
