<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sacramento Mayor Has Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Mayor Joe Serna said Thursday he has  
cancer and won't seek a third term. 
</P>
<P>
	``All my life I have been beating the odds and I intend to work  
hard against beating this one,'' Serna, 59, told reporters. ``I am 
now dedicating myself to my healing, my family, and continuing to 
serve the city of Sacramento.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors expect Serna to finish his term, which ends in 2000.  
</P>
<P>
	The mayor's illness is a recurrence of the kidney cancer he was  
first diagnosed with nine years ago. The kidney was removed and 
doctors found no evidence the cancer had spread, Serna said. 
</P>
<P>
	A doctor who examined Serna for pneumonia in mid-February  
discovered that the cancer had spread to the lungs. He has been in 
treatment since March. 
</P>
<P>
	Serna was first elected mayor in 1992 and won a second term in  
1996. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
