<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Slips, Japanese Stocks Rise / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar slipped slightly against the yen today  
when expected action by Japan's central bank to support the 
greenback failed to materialize. Japanese stocks rebounded 
modestly. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 121.90 yen at late afternoon, down from 121.98  
yen late Wednesday in Tokyo and also marginally lower than its late 
New York level of 121.92 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 41.57 points,  
or 0.24 percent, closing at 17,628.32 points. On Wednesday, the 
average fell 190.87 points, or 1.07 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar drifted in a narrow range  
against the yen as traders remained cautious over possible further 
intervention by the Bank of Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	Eisuke Sakakibara, Vice Finance Minister for International  
Affairs at the Finance Ministry, reiterated that Japanese finance 
authorities' were determined to prevent the yen from rising 
further. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bank of Japan has intervened four times over a two-week  
period to stem the yen's rise, with the latest action taken Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan fears a strong yen would make its exports more expensive  
abroad and thus potentially hamper the economy's ability to recover 
from its worst recession since World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	Some short-term speculators bought the U.S. currency aiming to  
ride it higher if the central bank were to sell yen today. But 
those expectations were not realized. 
</P>
<P>
	``The BOJ wasn't in the market today, so the dollar's topside  
was limited,'' said Shuji Takano, assistant manager of foreign 
exchange at ABN AMRO Bank in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar moved in a range between 121.80 yen and 122.13 yen in  
today's trading. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 126.30 yen, up from  
126.06 yen late Wednesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, foreign investors continued to buy Japanese  
stocks, while domestic institutional investors took profits and 
unwounded some cross shareholdings, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	Trading remained in a narrow range in the absence of fresh  
incentives for much of today's trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the Nikkei's advance, overall, declines outnumbered  
advances 801 to 422, with 103 issues unchanged. Volume on the 
exchange's first section was estimated at 554 million shares, down 
from Wednesday's turnover of 627 million shares. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section rose 1.95 points, or 0.14 percent, to 1,411.13. The 
TOPIX fell 16.46 points, or 1.15 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 213 10-year Japanese government  
bond fell to 1.6950 percent from Wednesday's finish of 1.7400 
percent, driving its price up to 100.91 yen from 100.51 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
