<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Renaming the Superdome Sparks Debate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- What's in a name? Millions of dollars if it's  
attached to a stadium, and that is sparking debate about adding 
former Gov. John McKeithen's name to the Superdome's official 
title. 
</P>
<P>
	A decision by the Legislature to rename the Superdome after the  
late governor, at a time corporations are willing to spend millions 
to add their names to stadiums, could be costly and possibly 
endanger retaining the city's NFL franchise, the New Orleans 
Saints. 
</P>
<P>
	Saints owner Tom Benson told the Superdome Commission Thursday  
that renaming the stadium could mean a loss of corporate revenue 
and, consequently, the team. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not against McKeithen,'' Benson said. ``Certainly he was a  
great governor and was a main source of getting this built. But 
they could have thought that through a little further as far as I 
was concerned.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McKeithen, who died earlier this month at the age of 81, was  
popular enough to convince reluctant voters in central and north 
Louisiana to go along with the New Orleans project. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commission asked Gov. Mike Foster to hold off signing the  
bill to allow time to study the impact of the move so they can make 
a recommendation. Under the law, the governor must act within 20 
days from the time he receives it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the thing to remember is that once you put Governor  
McKeithen's name on the Dome, you limit yourself,'' said Doug 
Thornton, dome manager. ``You take away the flexibility of ever 
being able to sell it unless McKeithen's name is taken away 
again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Superdome is currently operating in the black and does not  
need the additional revenue, said Dome spokesman Bill Curl. But the 
money generated by adding corporate names to stadiums is frequently 
used as an inducement to lure or retain professional sports 
franchises. If the Superdome is prohibited from doing so in the 
future, it would lose a bargaining chip with the NFL team. 
</P>
<P>
	``If at some point you want to enhance further inducements to  
the Saints' lease, will you have the flexibility of possibly doing 
it by selling the naming rights or does it come out of public 
money?'' asked Thornton. 
</P>
<P>
	The chance to link a corporate name to the Superdome would be  
worth $30 million to $40 million over a 10-year period, marketing 
experts believe. 
</P>
<P>
	``That may even be on the conservative side,'' said Fred Fried  
of Integrated Sports International, a marketing company that 
negotiated corporate sponsorships, including 3Com Park in San 
Francisco and Ericsson Stadium in North Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are very few venues that have the kind of visibility the  
Superdome has and are virtually guaranteed of having the Super Bowl 
and Final Four regularly,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Saints raised ticket prices this year and have hinted that  
they need more financial incentives to their lease that runs 
through 2018. 
</P>
<P>
	Team officials also scheduled a series of meetings with business  
and political leaders to demonstrate how the Saints' finances 
compare with those of other teams in the league. The Saints have 
not released their financial figures, but said they ranked 21 out 
of 31 NFL teams in total revenue in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue, who met with Gov. Mike Foster  
and Mayor Marc Morial last summer to discuss difficulties faced by 
small market teams, said that without sufficient earnings the 
Saints would suffer competitively. 
</P>
<P>
	A recent Forbes analysis showed the Saints with the 12th-highest  
revenue in the league and the fourth-highest operating profit. The 
report, based on 1997 data, showed the Saints generated operating 
profits of $18.5 million, almost three times the league average of 
$5.3 million, Forbes said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Saints dispute those figures and have repeatedly stated  
their need for more revenue. 
</P>
<P>
	The Saints would like to renegotiate four items in their lease  
that could produce another $6 million. Included in those items is a 
request that they get all money produced by selling the naming 
rights of the Superdome. Saints officials said NFL teams are 
getting an average of $2 million a year through such arrangements. 
</P>
<P>
	Dave Dixon, who worked with McKeithen to see the Dome built,  
believes the late governor deserves to be honored for it, but also 
acknowledges the problems naming it for him can create. 
</P>
<P>
	``If any of this creates a situation that makes it difficult for  
a small market city to compete with large cities to keep the 
Saints, it should be carefully thought through,'' Dixon said. 
``Perhaps it would be better to have a statue in front of the Dome 
or something inside honoring Governor McKeithen. I know he wouldn't 
want anything done that would hurt the Dome.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
