<HEADLINE> Teamsters, Anheuser-Busch Reach Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- The long and often bitter dispute between  
Anheuser-Busch and its largest union is apparently over. 
</P>
<P>
	The Teamsters and the St. Louis-based maker of Budweiser,  
Michelob and other beers Thursday announced a tentative agreement 
on a five-year contract. The deal must be approved by the union's 
8,000 members. Mail-in voting is expected to take about a month. 
The union covers workers ranging from bottlers and brewers to truck 
drivers and mechanics. 
</P>
<P>
	``This new contract, when ratified, would keep our employees the  
best-paid in the brewing industry and provide job security in the 
highest-paying production jobs in American industry,'' 
Anheuser-Busch spokesman John E. Jacob said. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement would end nearly two years of failed negotiations.  
Frustrated by the impasse, Anheuser-Busch last year imposed its 
final offer, a contract that would have paid the average Teamster, 
with overtime, about $66,000 annually by the end of the contract in 
early 2003. 
</P>
<P>
	But union members were unhappy because the contract did not  
guarantee job security. In September, union workers walked off the 
job in St. Louis for about a day. 
</P>
<P>
	``This agreement includes gains over the imposed contract that  
address the most critical concerns for our members and their 
families, including unprecedented job security measures and wage 
and benefits increases,'' said Jack Cipriani, director of Brewery 
and Soft Drink Workers Conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Anheuser-Busch spokesman Steve LeResche said the new deal would  
guarantee that none of the 12 domestic breweries would be closed 
during the life of the contract ``barring some major, unforeseen 
negative impact,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Union spokesman Chip Roth lauded the company for the job  
security provision. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not aware of any other Teamster members who enjoy that  
kind of commitment from their employer,'' Roth said. 
</P>
<P>
	The new contract would be valid through February 2004, a year  
longer than the deal the brewery had implemented over the union's 
objection. LeResche said other provisions of the contract would: 
</P>
<P>
	--Boost the average pay, with overtime, to $68,000 by the end of  
the contract; 
</P>
<P>
	--Increase pension benefits and continue no-cost healthcare  
coverage; 
</P>
<P>
	--Provide a lump-sum payment for each worker based on performance  
of the company's stock; 
</P>
<P>
	--Offer incentives for workers who meet certain safety and  
attendance guidelines. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to St. Louis, Anheuser-Busch operates breweries in  
Baldwinsville, N.Y.; Cartersville, Ga.; Columbus, Ohio; Fort 
Collins, Colo.; Houston; Jacksonville, Fla.; Los Angeles and 
Fairfield, Calif.; Merrimack, N.H.; Newark, N.J.; and Williamsburg, 
Va. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
