<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Strike Called at Greek Airline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATHENS, Greece (AP) -- Unions at Olympic Airways on Thursday  
called a 24-hour strike for July 1 after a subsidiary of British 
Airways took over management at Greece's troubled state airline. 
</P>
<P>
	Union leader Michalis Perros described the deal as a  
``gravestone'' for Olympic by placing it in the hands of a 
competitor. ``It's like asking a wolf to tend to the sheep,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Olympic staff staged a demonstration outside parliament,  
demanding that the deal be scrapped. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the agreement announced Wednesday, the BA subsidiary  
Speedwing will run Olympic for 30 months, overseeing a financial 
rescue plan for the airline long plagued by debts and labor 
disputes. British Airways will be allowed to buy a stake in the 
airline of up to 20 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The government argues Olympic cannot survive unless it forms  
partnerships with major airlines and insists the deal will not lead 
to job losses. 
</P>
<P>
	Transport Minister Tassos Mandelis described the deal as a last  
ditch attempt to turn around the money-losing carrier. ``Olympic 
Airways was the only airline left in Europe ... without a strategic 
partnership and now it has found the best partner, British 
Airways,'' Mandelis told state-run NET television. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
