<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 07:32:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Colangelo: Game Will Improve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Jerry Colangelo, one of the most influential  
owners in the NBA, promised a gathering of sports editors from 
newspapers around the country Wednesday that professional 
basketball will change for the better next season. 
</P>
<P>
	Colangelo, owner of the Phoenix Suns and managing general  
partner of baseball's Arizona Diamondbacks, made the remark in a 
question and answer session during the keynote luncheon address at 
the Associated Press Sports Editors annual meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	The game can be made more entertaining by enforcing rules that  
are already in place, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to open it up,'' Colangelo said. ``We're going to  
clean up the game. We're going to insist that it be called the way 
basketball was meant to be called, because basketball was meant to 
be played showing athleticism, showing an open-court situation, 
getting away from the mugging that's taking place, giving a little 
more emphasis to offense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Colangelo returned Tuesday night from New York, where he  
attended a meeting where the league discussed ideas about improving 
the deteriorating quality of play in the NBA. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you look at videotapes of 20 years ago, 15, 10, five  
years ago to what the game is today, there has been an evolution of 
what we've allowed to take place in terms of mugging, chucking, 
forearm shivers, etc.,'' Colangelo said. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we would enforce the rules that we have, you'd see a  
different game, but we've allowed it to go a particular way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Colangelo has been involved in the NBA since 1966, when he  
helped found the Chicago Bulls. Two years later, he moved to 
Phoenix as general manager of the expansion Suns. Later, he bought 
the team. 
</P>
<P>
	He said coaches who want to control the game have made every  
possession so important ``you end up with a half-court, post-up 
game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We've given too much liberty to defense. ... We've taken the  
offense out of the game. Shots are down. Scoring is down. 
Percentages are down. You can track it. We're going to make some 
real changes, and they'll be in effect this coming year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Colangelo said he is one of the leading voices for the changes.  
</P>
<P>
	``Like I said yesterday,'' he said. ``The media expects it, the  
fans demand it and it's the right thing to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Colangelo also spoke about his recently published book, ``How  
You Play The Game,'' which recounts his rise from an Italian 
neighborhood in Chicago to one of the leading sports figures in the 
country. 
</P>
<P>
	He repeated a theme of his book, that young athletes are too  
coddled and pampered, leading to some of the image problems that 
players have once they get to the professional level. 
</P>
<P>
	Colangelo defended his tactics in bringing major league baseball  
to Phoenix and disputed the widely held notion that he was behind 
the moves that led to the construction of Bank One Ballpark 
primarily with public money without a public vote. 
</P>
<P>
	That legislation was passed 2 1/2 years before he was asked to lead  
an effort to bring baseball to Arizona. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had absolutely zero to do with it,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Initially, he didn't think much of the baseball offer, then  
changed his mind after studying the idea and deciding it would 
work. 
</P>
<P>
	Colangelo spent $118.9 million on free agents during the  
offseason, and as a result the Diamondbacks are contenders in just 
their second season. 
</P>
<P>
	But acceptance from other baseball owners has been slow in  
coming, especially at a time when there is little contact between 
the owners and the major league hierarchy. 
</P>
<P>
	``For me, in the NBA, I'm involved in every decision, with all  
the major committees that I participate on,'' Colangelo said, ``so 
you feel very much more involved. 
</P>
<P>
	``Thus far that hasn't been the experience in baseball. That  
probably will change to some degree as we continue to pay our dues, 
I guess.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
