<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 02:20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Graf Escapes Against De Swardt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WIMBLEDON, England (AP) -- The serve came at Steffi Graf faster  
than she expected and whizzed past. She looked at the scoreboard 
and rolled her eyes: 116 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	That wasn't the only bad news for Graf early in her second-round  
match Wednesday at Wimbledon. She lost five of the first six games 
to pesky Mariaan de Swardt, but then rallied to win 4-6, 6-3, 6-2. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was wondering a little bit out there,'' Graf said. ``I felt  
like a spectator in the beginning, the way she was hitting those 
serves. There wasn't much I could do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	De Swardt slammed four aces on her way to the early lead, but  
she was unable to pull off the second big upset in as many days at 
the All England Club. 
</P>
<P>
	Graf became the tournament favorite when top-ranked Martina  
Hingis lost Tuesday to 16-year-old qualifier Jelena Dokic. But Graf 
grimaced when asked about her chances of winning Wimbledon for an 
eighth time. 
</P>
<P>
	``Wimbledon is the biggest tournament around and the one I enjoy  
the most,'' she said. ``But if I win it or not, it's nothing that I 
worry right now about.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aside from Hingis' defeat and the absence of rain, the first  
three days of play produced few surprises. 
</P>
<P>
	Monica Seles, Venus Williams, Anna Kournikova and 1998 runnerup  
Nathalie Tauziat joined Graf in the third round with straight-set 
victories. Hingis remained the only seeded woman eliminated. 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Courier advanced beyond the second round at Wimbledon for  
the first time since 1993, when he lost in the final to Pete 
Sampras. Courier outlasted 12th-seeded Carlos Moya 6-3, 3-6, 7-6 
(7-1), 3-6, 6-2. 
</P>
<P>
	Moya, who has still never reached the third round in four tries  
at Wimbledon, was the first seeded man to lose. Fellow Spaniard 
Felix Mantilla, seeded 16th, was later eliminated by American Paul 
Goldstein, 6-2, 6-4, 6-7 (5-7), 6-2. 
</P>
<P>
	Five-time champion Sampras, again looking almost invincible on  
grass, swept Sebastien Lareau 6-4, 6-2, 6-3. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been a good start,'' Sampras said. ``The fact that I've  
won here a couple of times gives me confidence. I don't feel the 
pressure, because I've proved myself here. If I don't win another 
Wimbledon, I'm sure I would be happy with five, but I'd love to win 
six.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also advancing were Yevgeny Kafelnikov, Mark Philippoussis, Greg  
Rusedski, Karol Kucera and Tommy Haas. 
</P>
<P>
	Unseeded losers included Jennifer Capriati and French Open  
runnerup Andrei Medvedev. 
</P>
<P>
	With Graf coming off her French Open victory earlier this month,  
de Swardt appeared unlikely to mount a challenge. The stocky South 
African, ranked 38th, lost 10 of her first 12 matches in 1999 and 
has just one tournament title in 13 years on the WTA Tour. 
</P>
<P>
	But Graf brings out the best in de Swardt. They met twice  
previously, with Graf surviving a tough three-setter at Wimbledon 
in 1992, and de Swardt winning in 1995 at Brighton when Graf was 
ranked No. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	De Swardt played almost flawless tennis in the first set  
Wednesday, belting aces and repeatedly winning points with 
acrobatic shots at the net. But she double-faulted twice to lose 
her serve in the first game of the final set, and Graf pulled away 
from there. 
</P>
<P>
	``Experience helps a lot, and concentrating on what you know you  
can do,'' Graf said. ``You try to hang in there. The way she 
started the match, if she had continued like that, there would have 
been very little I could do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Someone suggested that the tough test might help Graf as she  
advances deeper into the tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's always easy to say, `Yeah, I like to have  
three-setters,''' she said with a smile, ``if you come out as a 
winner.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
