</P>
<P>
 *Bishop's title eludes gay priest    	
</P>
<P>
	BATH, N.Y. (AP) -- The Episcopal Church's Diocese of Rochester  
has elected the Rev. Jack McKelvey as its next bishop, narrowly 
bypassing a candidate who had hoped to become the church's first 
openly gay bishop. 
</P>
<P>
	The polling took place at the St. Thomas Episcopal Church in  
Bath, 60 miles south of Rochester. After five ballots, McKelvey 
defeated the Rev. V. Gene Robinson and three other nominees to 
succeed retiring Bishop William G. Burrill at year's end. 
</P>
<P>
	The election still must be approved by a majority of the  
dioceses and bishops in the 2.5 million-member church, which is 
based in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	McKelvey, 57, an assisting bishop of the Newark (N.J.) Diocese  
for nine years and a priest since 1967, supports same-sex marriages 
and ordination of openly gay ministers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the church is going to have to be ready for it  
eventually,'' he said. ``When that is I don't know, but gay and 
lesbian people to be sure are human beings under God's care.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As for Robinson, he said, ``We would not differ theologically  
and perhaps in anything that I can think of.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Robinson, 52, assistant to Bishop Douglas Theuner of the Diocese  
of New Hampshire and a priest for 25 years, was married with two 
children when he acknowledged he was gay in 1986. He now lives with 
his partner, Mark Andrew. 
</P>
<P>
	``Clearly it was an issue in this election,'' Robinson said,  
``and I applaud the people of the diocese in being quite open in 
asking me about that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Robinson said he would seek to become bishop in another diocese.  
``I believe God is calling me ...,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *American Baptists expel four churches    	
</P>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Four California churches were expelled  
by the board of the American Baptist Churches USA on the eve of the 
church's nationwide biennial meeting. The offense was ``welcoming 
and affirming'' homosexuals. 
</P>
<P>
	American Baptist congregations are autonomous. The denomination  
is a voluntary association with no authority except to withhold its 
affiliation. Churches join by affiliating with a region; the five 
churches were dismissed from their regions but appealed to the 
General Board. 
</P>
<P>
	Failing to win on appeal were Lakeshore Avenue Baptist Church in  
Oakland; First Baptist Church of Berkeley; New Community of Faith 
in San Jose; and San Leandro Community Church in San Leandro. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *Reformed Church retains ties    	
</P>
<P>
	SIOUX FALLS, S.D. (AP) -- Delegates of the Reformed Church in  
America defeated proposals to sever ties with the United Church of 
Christ over UCC acceptance of homosexuality. 
</P>
<P>
	Another bill that failed would have led to efforts to determine  
whether the UCC has lost belief in the full divinity of Jesus 
Christ and has become unitarian in its theology. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year four denominations -- the Reformed Church, the UCC,  
Evangelican Lutheran Church of America and Presbyterian Church 
(USA) -- entered a close fellowship, but not full organizational 
merger, involving some 10.5 million members. 
</P>
<P>
	The more conservative Reformed Church had initiated a dialogue  
with the UCC on homosexuality. Talks ended last January with each 
denomination urging the other to change its policy. 
</P>
<P>
	``We admonish the UCC to repeal its official positions that  
sanction homosexual practice,'' the Reformed Church panelists said. 
But UCC negotiators said stands like the Reformed Church's help 
foster ``virulent voices of prejudice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *Muslims get cemetery    	
</P>
<P>
	WATERLOO, Iowa (AP) -- The more than 4,000 Muslims in the  
Waterloo area now have a cemetery that conforms to their customs 
and burial practices. 
</P>
<P>
	The Muslim community grew in large part with the arrival of more  
than 3,000 Bosnians since 1996 and had been without a cemetery 
until the city's Board of Adjustment approved zoning of 4 acres of 
farmland near two other cemeteries. 
</P>
<P>
	Muslims bury their dead in the direction of the holy city of  
Mecca and in rows in the order in which they pass away. They do not 
use a coffin or concrete vault and have relatively small 
headstones. 
  	   	
</P>
