<HEADLINE> Bengals Sign DB Tremain Mack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Tremain Mack, a kick returner and defensive  
back who landed in jail last season because of drunken-driving 
arrests, signed a new two-year contract Thursday with the 
Cincinnati Bengals. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bengals, who drafted Mack in the fourth round in 1997 from  
the University of Miami, reinstated him two weeks ago. NFL 
officials still have not said whether he will face league 
discipline, which could involve a suspension, this season because 
of his alcohol problems. 
</P>
<P>
	This would have been the final season of his original three-year  
contract with the Bengals, but the new contract secures him through 
the 2000 season. Terms weren't disclosed. 
</P>
<P>
	Mack was primarily a kick returner last season before missing  
the final four games because of his latest drunken-driving arrest. 
He served jail time for a probation violation and has been 
undergoing an NFL-mandated alcohol evaluation program. 
</P>
<P>
	He had a history of drinking problems when the Bengals drafted  
him. He had been arrested six times in less than four years, with 
at least three of the arrests related to alcohol. 
</P>
<P>
	He is listed as the backup at left cornerback to rookie Charles  
Fisher, although he has played mostly at strong safety his first 
two years. Mack set team records in kickoff return average (25.9) 
and yards (1,165) in the first 12 games last season, with one 
touchdown. 
</P>
<P>
	He was jailed in Clermont County, east of Cincinnati, beginning  
in December after violating his probation stemming from a 
drunken-driving arrest Oct. 13, 1998, in the Cincinnati area. He 
underwent a mandatory two-month treatment program and was evaluated 
by the NFL under its substance-abuse program. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
