<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 10:10:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Claudia Lonow Mines Past for Laughs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- In Showtime's ``Rude Awakening,''  
actress-turned-writer Claudia Lonow fearlessly tells all (or close 
enough) about a woman derailed by life in the Hollywood fast lane. 
</P>
<P>
	At this moment, however, she's distracted from the series'  
sophomore season and is being coy about telling why. 
</P>
<P>
	``You don't want to know what I was doing right now. You  
wouldn't believe how stupid it is,'' she says. Then, living up to 
the bold honesty of ``Rude Awakening,'' she 'fesses up. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm single and young and ... good-looking, but I never have  
time to meet anybody,'' she says. ``I signed up for this dating 
service, someone wrote me, and me and the other writers on the show 
are sitting and composing a funny e-mail back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's the straight-talking Lonow who, as personified by  
fictional Billie Frank, makes ``Rude Awakening'' such a bracing 
slap in the face of timid television and TV's shrinking-violet 
female characters. 
</P>
<P>
	``One thing I wanted to do with this character is have a woman  
who really says what's on her mind. Girls are expected to always be 
good, and I just hate that,'' Lonow says. 
</P>
<P>
	Billie is an angry young woman with a drinking problem and a  
knack for making things tough for herself and her friends. That her 
life manages to be the stuff of truth and humor is due to Lonow, 
who knows both the dark terrain and the mechanics of comedy. 
</P>
<P>
	The series, starring Sherilyn Fenn (``Twin Peaks'') as Billie,  
returns to Showtime 10 p.m. EDT Saturday with 22 new episodes. Lynn 
Redgrave, Jonathan Penner and Rain Pryor co-star, with Roger E. 
Mosley (``Magnum, P.I.'') joining as a series regular. 
</P>
<P>
	Also appearing this season will be Karen Black, Michelle  
Phillips and rocker Roger Daltry. 
</P>
<P>
	A true ``dramedy,'' mixing comedy and tragedy in the half-hour  
format and minus a laugh track, the series chronicles the struggle 
of former child star Billie to conquer her alcoholism and assorted 
demons. 
</P>
<P>
	Her mother (played by Redgrave) isn't much help. When Billie  
announces she has attended her first recovery group meeting, dear 
mom cheerily pours champagne for both to toast the milestone. 
</P>
<P>
	So how much of Lonow's life is in ``Rude Awakening''?  
</P>
<P>
	``I like to say 60 percent is true and 40 percent is fictional,  
and it's up to you to figure out which,'' she replies. 
</P>
<P>
	Here's some help:  
</P>
<P>
	-- Billie is an alumna of a primetime soap opera, ``Emerald  
Isle''; Lonow played Michele Lee and Don Murray's wayward daughter, 
Diana Fairgate, on CBS' ``Knots Landing'' from 1979-84 and in the 
series' final year, 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Billie is working, reluctantly, on her alcohol addiction  
problem; Lonow did the same, eventually embracing the sober life in 
her 20s. (Her age now? ``You can put down 34.'') 
</P>
<P>
	-- Unlike Billie, Lonow has a ``very good relationship'' with her  
parents. And, unlike Billie, she managed to channel her energy away 
from acting and into what has turned out far more rewarding: 
writing and, with ``Rude Awakening,'' producing. 
</P>
<P>
	If she had any inclination to continue as an actress, taking  
part in the ``Knots Landing'' reunion movie in 1997 cured her of 
the impulse. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't want to be there. All I could think was, 'The last  
time I did this I was 21.' I didn't want to be this person 
anymore,'' Lonow says. She also concluded, ``I was a very good 
actress as a teen-ager, but perhaps not so great as a grown-up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although the cast and producers of ``Knots Landing'' were  
supportive, the pressure of working so young on a project in which 
so much money was at stake contributed to her addiction, Lonow 
says. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would say it's an unusual person who can deal with that kind  
of stress and not have it affect them. It was hard for me,'' she 
says. 
</P>
<P>
	Would she let her daughter, now 5, act? ``No way,'' Lonow  
replies, firmly. ``When you're a teen-ager, you should work in a 
clothing store.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Searching for a new career, she struck out in a direction that  
was, partly, a return to her roots. As the stepdaughter of Mark 
Lonow, co-owner of the Improvisation comedy club chain, Lonow had 
written and performed routines beginning in her teens. 
</P>
<P>
	After studying screenplay writing, she began job-hunting -- very  
unsuccessfully. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was Mark's daughter, a drunk, who used to be on 'Knots  
Landing,' and I was never fabulous as a comic. ... It took me a 
while to figure out that if I'm gonna get into this, I've got to 
pursue people who don't know me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At one point, she was grateful for a job as a Hollywood  
assistant. Then came jobs writing comedy CD-Roms, then an Internet 
show called ``Claudia Boulevard'' and, finally, luck. 
</P>
<P>
	A pilot she was hired to polish for producer Joe Voci didn't  
sell. But when Lonow mentioned her idea for a comedy drawing on her 
life, Voci told her to write it; Showtime bought ``Rude 
Awakening.'' Most critics liked it. 
</P>
<P>
	``Last year was one of just constant surprise. I'm just  
beginning to recover from it now,'' Lonow says. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in television ....  
</P>
<P>
	IN THE SOUP: Stand-up comedian Hal Sparks is the new host of E!  
Entertainment Television's ``Talk Soup.'' Sparks, a Los Angeles 
comedy club regular and guest star on series including ``Dr. Quinn, 
Medicine Woman'' and ``Lois &AMP; Clark: The New Adventures of 
Superman,'' will take over July 5. John Henson, current host of the 
show that takes a lighthearted look at talk show highlights, is 
leaving to work at ABC. 
</P>
<P>
	Lynn Elber can be reached at lelber''at''ap.org  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 15:20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Fall, Pushing Yield Up / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Long-term bonds fell for a fifth straight  
session Thursday, pushing interest rates farther above 6 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond fell 7/32  
point, or $2.19 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, a key 
influence on borrowing costs, rose to 6.16 percent from 6.14 
percent late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Treasurys have been in a steady decline since Friday, when the  
market began reversing the rally spurred by Federal Reserve 
Chairman Alan Greenspan's congressional testimony. With the Fed 
expected to raise interest rates next week to slow the economy, 
potential bond buyers aren't stepping in even though many see 
current yields as attractive. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
were unchanged to up 1/32 point, while intermediate maturities were 
between unchanged and down 1/16 point, reported Bridge Telerate. 
</P>
<P>
	In other trading Thursday, yields on three-month Treasury bills  
were 4.72 percent as the discount rose 0.01 percentage point to 
4.60 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Six-month yields were 5.03 percent, as the discount rose 0.01  
percentage point to 4.84 percent. One-year yields were 5.16 percent 
as the discount was unchanged at 4.90 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, rose to 4.88 percent from Wednesday's 4.69 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell 1/2 to 118 3/8. The average yield to 
maturity rose to 5.56 percent, up from 5.53 percent late Wednesday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
