<DOCNO> APW19990624.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 15:21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  ESPN's X Games Kick Off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Skateboarders, cyclists, street lugers and  
other fringe athletes with a need for speed hit the uncommonly 
steep streets of this city Thursday for ESPN's annual X Games. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 400 athletes from around the world are competing for  
nearly $1 million in prize money in the 10-day extreme sports 
competition, which has become a huge draw for advertisers seeking 
to tap into the youth market. 
</P>
<P>
	Competitive events include sportclimbing, skateboarding, street  
luge, bicycle stunt riding, aggressive in-line skating, 
wakeboarding, and skysurfing, set against a background of 
alternative music concerts and merchandising events. 
</P>
<P>
	The skysurfing competition finished Monday over the Monterey Bay  
with the two-man team of Eric Fradet and Alex Iodice of France 
taking the gold medal. 
</P>
<P>
	In skysurfing, competitors leap from a plane with a snowboard  
strapped to their feet, and make a series of high-speed spins, 
flips and surfing-styled moves, all recorded by a parachuting 
cameraman. The descents are judged on technical execution and 
style. 
</P>
<P>
	ESPN expects about 200,000 spectators along the city's  
waterfront, where many of the skateboarding and bicycling events 
will take place. The street luge will take advantage of a 
particularly steep hill that runs past the city's Cliff House next 
to the Pacific ocean. 
</P>
<P>
	This is the first time the event has been held in San Francisco.  
Despite the city's reputation for skateboarding, skating down a 
sidewalk in the city is illegal and can incur fines up to $100. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 15:21:01 </DATE_TIME>
