<DOCNO> APW19990624.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 07:32:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Golfer Webb Having Dream Season  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) -- When Karrie Webb says she is having a  
dream year on the LPGA Tour, she's not kidding. 
</P>
<P>
	The 24-year-old Australian is building on her modern LPGA record  
of 16 consecutive finishes in the top 10, has already won five 
times this year and is on the verge of becoming the first woman to 
go over $1 million before July. 
</P>
<P>
	But on the eve of the LPGA Championship, Webb revealed she has  
had some ``really weird dreams'' the last couples of weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	The most recent one involved her in a playoff with fellow Aussie  
Rachel Hetherington. Tournament officials made them walk up and 
down a steep hill before they could hit their tee shots, and Webb 
was out of breath. 
</P>
<P>
	``Then I woke up,'' she said. ``I woke up before I had the  
playoff because I didn't want to know who won.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Like that would have been a big surprise.  
</P>
<P>
	Webb isn't winning every week on the LPGA Tour, it just seems  
that way. In 13 tournaments this year, she has won five times and 
been in contention on Sunday in all but three of them. 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, two of those happened to be majors. She was among  
those in the wake left by Dottie Pepper in her record-setting 
victory in the Dinah Shore, and she finished 10 strokes behind Juli 
Inkster in the U.S. Women's Open. 
</P>
<P>
	At 24, Webb has already accomplished more than she could have  
dreamed with 14 victories and already enough earnings to rank 12th 
on the career money list. All that remains is that first major, and 
she will certainly be one of the favorites at Dupont Country Club. 
</P>
<P>
	Not that she would consider herself a failure if it doesn't  
happen this week. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe if I was 40 years old and heading on the way out,'' she  
said. ``But I'm still on the way. I know I have a lot of golf ahead 
of me. Three and a half years ago, if someone told me I had won 
this many times out here, I would never have believed them. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just living the dream now.''  
</P>
<P>
	The biggest dream of all this week belongs to Inkster.  
</P>
<P>
	Winning two major championships as a rookie 15 years ago -- the  
Dinah Shore and du Maurier Classic -- only made Inkster hungry to 
win them all. Perhaps that's why the LPGA Championship means more 
to her now than ever. 
</P>
<P>
	Having won the U.S. Open at Old Waverly three weeks ago, Inkster  
could join Pat Bradley as the only women to complete the modern 
LPGA career Grand Slam. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to have to have another great week to do it,''  
Inkster said. ``It's been a little hectic in my lifestyle, and I 
just have to focus on my golf game. But I think I can do it. I 
think I have as good a chance as anybody else out there right 
now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mickey Wright, whose swing Ben Hogan said was the best he ever  
saw, is the only other woman to win all four majors, which from 
1955-66 consisted of the U.S. Open, the LPGA Championship, the 
Titleholders and the Western Open. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a pretty difficult task,'' Bradley said. ``You're dealing  
with majors, which aren't your everyday, ordinary tournaments. But 
I think if anybody has the savvy to do it, Juli is perfectly 
qualified for that task.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The problem is, Inkster isn't the only player capable of winning  
this week. 
</P>
<P>
	The defending champion is Se Ri Pak, who won last week in  
Absecon, N.J., for the first time this year. All four of Pak's 
victories in 1998, when she became the first rookie since Inkster 
to win two majors, came during a 10-week stretch. 
</P>
<P>
	``It makes a good feeling to this week,'' Pak said.  
</P>
<P>
	And Webb seems to have good feelings every time she tees it up.  
She is coming off a memorable victory two weeks ago in Rochester, 
where she birdied the last three holes to win by one stroke. 
</P>
<P>
	Webb decided to take last week off -- as hot as she is, she  
probably could have made a fortune in the casinos of Atlantic City. 
</P>
<P>
	``I set my schedule up around the majors,'' she said. ``I'm  
trying to peak at the right time. I feel my game is in pretty good 
shape. I have never had as much confidence as I have right now on 
the golf course.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The only place her confidence seems to be lacking is in her  
dreams. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
