<DOCNO> APW19990624.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 20:38:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Israel Bombs Southern Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- Israel's warplanes bombed power stations  
and bridges Thursday in retaliatory strikes that left at least six 
people dead. The escalation in hostilities came as guerrilla 
attacks in northern Israel killed two Israelis and injured 13. 
</P>
<P>
	Forty-five people in Lebanon were wounded in nine Israeli  
airstrikes, three of which targeted a power facility on a hill 
overlooking Beirut and left much of the city in darkness. 
</P>
<P>
	The attacks were among the heaviest by Israel since a 1996  
Israeli bombing blitz in Lebanon left 175 dead. 
</P>
<P>
	Warplanes also hit a power substation in the eastern city of  
Baalbek and four airstrikes targeted bridges on the main coastal 
road to southern Lebanon. 
</P>
<P>
	The Israeli army said in a statement that air force planes  
carried out the bombings in response to Hezbollah rocket attacks on 
northern Israel earlier in the day. 
</P>
<P>
	Two Israelis were killed as Katyusha rockets rained down on the  
Israeli border city of Kiryat Shmonah. At least 13 people were 
injured, one seriously. 
</P>
<P>
	The two men who were killed -- the first Israelis to die in a  
rocket barrage since 1995 -- had apparently been standing in front 
of city hall when a Katyusha scored a direct hit on the building. 
</P>
<P>
	After Israel's air raids, the guerrillas retaliated with more  
rocket attacks on northern Israel, witnesses said. There were no 
immediate reports of casualties in that shelling. 
</P>
<P>
	``What happened amounts to a catastrophe and is new proof of  
Israel's unlimited barbarianism,'' Prime Minister Salim Hoss said 
in a statement, adding that he was in contact with ambassadors of 
the United States and other nations to intercede with Israel to 
halt the escalation. 
</P>
<P>
	Israeli television reported that the decision to bomb Beirut was  
made by Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's government. The newly 
elected Ehud Barak has been updated but was not involved in the 
decision, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hezbollah is wrong if it thinks it can take advantage of the  
period of government transition to hit residents of the north,'' 
Netanyahu said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Netanyahu met with his security Cabinet until early Friday  
morning. Afterward, Israeli radio stations broadcast his concluding 
statement: ``If there's no quiet on the border, there's no quiet in 
Lebanon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A U.S. State Department urged all sides to act with restraint.  
</P>
<P>
	Hezbollah is leading a guerrilla war to oust some 1,500 Israeli  
soldiers and the 2,500 militiamen from the Israeli-allied South 
Lebanon Army from the occupied zone. 
</P>
<P>
	South Lebanon, where Israel maintains a ``security zone'' to  
protect its border from guerilla attacks, always simmers with 
tension, but civilian deaths on either side have been known to 
spark mini-wars. 
</P>
<P>
	The violence mushroomed during a daylong series of  
back-and-forth attacks. Hezbollah struck first on Thursday, 
shelling northern Israel in response to the wounding of a Lebanese 
civilian in Israeli attacks in previous days. 
</P>
<P>
	Israel quickly responded by sending planes to bombard the area  
where the rockets were believed to have been fired. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Beirut attacks, state-run TV reported that four firemen  
were killed and 10 people were wounded in a raid as they struggled 
to put out the flames at the power station from an earlier attack. 
</P>
<P>
	Early Friday, six hours after the strike on the Jamhour  
substation overlooking Beirut, Israeli aircraft struck at another 
substation that also feeds the Lebanese capital with electricity. 
</P>
<P>
	Flames could be seen for a distance from the Bsalim station,  
also above Beirut, plunging more neighborhoods in darkness. It was 
not immediately clear whether there were casualties. 
</P>
<P>
	Israeli warplanes could be heard rumbling over Beirut, drawing  
heavy anti-aircraft fire from the ground that lit up the night sky. 
</P>
<P>
	Israeli warplanes also blasted targets in the city of Baalbek, a  
Hezbollah guerrilla stronghold in eastern Lebanon's Bekaa Valley, 
wounding 20, security officials reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Jets also struck three bridges on the coastal highway between  
Beirut and Sidon, 25 miles to the south. Two people were killed and 
eight others wounded at Damour, halfway between Beirut and Sidon. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Awali River Bridge on the outskirts of Sidon, two strikes  
wounded two Lebanese soldiers and five others. 
</P>
<P>
	Many neighborhoods of the Lebanese capital and its suburbs,  
including the guerrilla strongholds in south Beirut, lost 
electricity while firemen struggled at the site to hose down the 
flames. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 20:38:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Israel Bombs Southern Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- Israel's warplanes bombed power stations  
and bridges Thursday in retaliatory strikes that left at least six 
people dead. The escalation in hostilities came as guerrilla 
attacks in northern Israel killed two Israelis and injured 13. 
</P>
<P>
	Forty-five people in Lebanon were wounded in nine Israeli  
