<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 12:40:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rains Threaten Midwest Wheat Crop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WELLINGTON, Kan. (AP) -- Spreading like a golden wave across the  
nation's heartland, millions of acres of winter wheat began 
ripening a few weeks ago, drawing crews from across the country and 
the world to harvest it. 
</P>
<P>
	Then the rains began.  
</P>
<P>
	Now, the fields are too soggy for the 27,000-pound combines to  
move in, and the wheat is too wet to harvest. 
</P>
<P>
	Soon the stalks will fall over, making the crop even harder to  
bring in. And soon, too, the wheat heads will shatter, destroying 
the crop's commercial value for anything but animal feed. Winter 
wheat is used primarily to make bread. 
</P>
<P>
	The ``custom cutters'' who follow the ripening crops and  
streamed into Kansas, Oklahoma and Texas from as far away as 
Australia and South Africa are waiting out the weather in hotel 
rooms in sleepy rural towns, doing little but sleeping, eating and 
hoping for the rain to stop. 
</P>
<P>
	Forecasters said that's not likely anytime soon. Rain and  
thunderstorms are expected to continue into next week in Kansas. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody is in the same boat -- sitting and waiting,'' said  
Robert Wawrzyniak, who hauled his combine from Missouri into Kansas 
two weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The rain could mean big losses for farmers, too.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think it is too soon to say it is a national disaster, but  
obviously the acres harvested are going to be down quite a bit,'' 
said Mark Simmons of the Kansas Association of Wheat Growers. 
</P>
<P>
	Only 2 percent of the winter wheat crop has been harvested in  
Kansas, compared with 31 percent by this time last year, Kansas 
Agricultural Statistics reported this week. Oklahoma farmers have 
harvested 51 percent of their crop, compared with 79 percent at 
this time a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	In Oklahoma, where the wheat has been ripe much longer, many  
farmers have already abandoned their crops. In southern Kansas, 
especially around Medicine Lodge, reports of shattered wheat heads 
are also coming in. 
</P>
<P>
	The unseasonable rains hurt wheat in a number of ways. Wet wheat  
can rot during storage, and even once it dries out, the heads tend 
to shrivel up, lowering the weight per bushel and affecting the 
price farmers get. 
</P>
<P>
	Kansas and Oklahoma account for about one-third of all winter  
wheat grown in the United States. So far, commodity prices that 
could ultimately lead to higher bread prices in the supermarket 
have not been affected. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think we are reaching a strong concern about the  
national production,'' said Kansas state statistician Eddie Wells. 
</P>
<P>
	Just how much damage the rains have done to the wheat crop won't  
be known until the combines can get back into the fields. 
</P>
<P>
	In northwestern Kansas -- where wheat is just beginning to ripen  
-- the crop is still in mostly good condition. But farmers fear that 
with all of Kansas ready to harvest at the same time -- and with 
nearly half of the Oklahoma fields still uncut because of rain 
there-- there won't be enough crews and combines to get the crops in 
fast enough once it dries up. 
</P>
<P>
	Wawrzyniak, who came here from Maitland, Mo., with his wife and  
son, said he has worked just 6 1/2 hours in the past two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is costing me money,'' he said. Many cutters are moving on  
in search of drier fields. That could pose a problem for some 
farmers, who rely on the crews to harvest about 60 percent of the 
fields. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's really going to put us in a bind, but it's happened  
before,'' said Marsha Carothers, whose family will use its own 
three combines to finish harvesting its 3,300 acres near Anthony, 
Kan. ``We're used to it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 23:10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cities Fear Gunmaker's Ch. 11 Move </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A California gunmaker targeted in lawsuits by  
cities seeking to recoup the costs of gun-related violence has 
filed for bankruptcy protection, raising concerns that other 
weapons manufacturers named in the lawsuits will follow the same 
path to escape big payouts. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis Industries, a Chino, Calif.-based company that produces  
small, cheap handguns known as Saturday night specials, filed for 
Chapter 11 protection in May. 
</P>
<P>
	The move has alarmed attorneys representing cities that have  
sued Davis and more than a dozen other gunmakers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a no-win situation for everybody. The industry would  
basically be run by a bankruptcy judge and our suits would be put 
on hold until the industry is reorganized by the court,'' said 
lawyer John Coale, who sued gunmakers on behalf of New Orleans, 
Cincinnati, Cleveland and Newark, N.J. 
</P>
<P>
	A call seeking comment from Davis Industries was not returned  
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Cities including Los Angeles, Chicago and New Orleans filed the  
suits, accusing gunmakers of failing to equip weapons with adequate 
safety devices, and marketing them in ways that allow firearms to 
fall into the hands of criminals. 
</P>
<P>
	The cases are patterned after lawsuits that forced cigarette  
makers to pay some $246 billion over the next 25 years to reimburse 
states for the costs of treating tobacco-related illnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Doug Painter, executive director of the Washington-based  
National Shooting Sports Foundation, said there has been no 
indication that gun companies are collectively considering 
bankruptcy as a legal strategy. 
</P>
<P>
	``Never has it been brought up by any of our member companies,''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The owner of a California gunmaker, however, said bankruptcy  
would provide the firearms industry with some clear advantages. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think what Davis is doing is probably a good idea,'' said  
Jim Waldorf of Lorcin Engineering, a Mira Loma-based company. 
``When you have a multitude of things that have no merit on the 
evidence, it's best for it to be decided in a federal arena rather 
than in several jurisdictions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Once a defendant files for protection, the lawsuits move into  
federal bankruptcy court where the judge ultimately approves a 
reorganization plan for the company and decides where to allocate 
its money. 
</P>
<P>
	Plaintiffs who win their lawsuits join other creditors in trying  
to collect. Even if the company wants to offer a settlement, the 
other creditors and the bankruptcy judge typically have a say in 
whether it will be approved. 
</P>
<P>
	Waldorf said Lorcin won't file for bankruptcy. The company  
emerged from Chapter 11 protection only six months ago after being 
hit with two dozen product liability suits, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Pressure from the lawsuits has prompted the National Shooting  
Sports Foundation to hold talks with the municipalities and their 
attorneys about technical issues, such as the viability of safety 
technologies that the lawsuits advocate. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not settlement talks; it's opening discussions to clarify  
what we believe is a tremendous amount of misinformation and 
misunderstanding in the lawsuits themselves,'' Painter said. 
</P>
<P>
	As an example, Painter referred to ``smart'' gun technologies  
that the lawsuits accuse gunmakers of refusing to adopt. Such guns 
would fire only after recognizing the owner's voice or palm prints. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, no one has been able to make such a device small or  
rugged enough to fit inside a handgun, Painter said. 
</P>
<P>
	Coale did not believe the talks would lead to a settlement.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm pessimistic now that the moderates in either camp are  
going to prevail,'' he said. ``We're probably going to go to war.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tobacco companies entered their legal battle with the states as  
a unified, prosperous industry. Gun companies, by contrast, don't 
have as much money and have failed to reach a united legal 
strategy. Aside from the foundation-sponsored discussions, they 
have chosen to deal with the cities' lawsuits individually. 
</P>
<P>
	The gun industry comprises mostly small companies with annual  
revenues in the $2 billion to $3 billion range. The only publicly 
traded company, Sturm Ruger &AMP; Co. Inc., reported earnings of $8.4 
million on revenues of $62.9 million for the first quarter of 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	Gun sales fell sharply after peaking in 1993, when Americans  
responded to the 1992 Los Angeles riots and proposed gun-control 
laws by buying thousands of new weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	But industrywide sales in 1999 are on the rise, Waldorf said,  
because of new restrictions being considered in the wake of the 
Columbine High School massacre. 
</P>
<P>
	``Gun control always spurs sales,'' he said.  


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 04:20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cops: Man Smothered Infant Son </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FRANKLIN, Ind. (AP) -- Haunted by the image of his dead baby's  
distorted face, a man walked into the Johnson County Jail and 
allegedly confessed to killing his infant son. 
</P>
<P>
	``Then he begged me to shoot him,'' Sheriff's Maj. Terry  
Nichalson said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Ronald Shanabarger, 29, was held without bond and was expected  
to be charged today with killing Tyler Shanabarger, who was less 
than 8 months old. 
</P>
<P>
	Shanabarger told authorities he wrapped plastic wrap around  
Tyler's head Saturday night and walked away. He said he returned 20 
minutes later, removed the wrap and placed his dead son face-down 
in a baby bed for his wife, Amy, to discover. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Shanabarger thought the baby was asleep and didn't realize  
anything was wrong until the child failed to wake up Sunday 
morning, Nichalson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials thought the baby died of Sudden Infant Death Syndrome.  
Franklin Police Chief Harry Furrer said an autopsy did not reveal 
evidence of foul play. 
</P>
<P>
	Nichalson said Shanabarger, with his wife, came to the sheriff's  
office Wednesday morning, saying he decided to confess because his 
conscience got the best of him. 
</P>
<P>
	``My son died of SIDS on Sunday. But that's not what happened,''  
Shanabarger told a jail officer, according to police. ``I killed 
him. I killed my son.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``He said he kept seeing the baby's face,'' Nichalson said. ``It  
was not a pretty sight, because the baby laid dead all night and 
the blood had collected under the skin and it looked pretty bad.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nichalson said the killing was an act of revenge ``against  
someone other than the victim,'' but did not explain further. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
