<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 4 Die in N.C. From Carbon Monoxide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Four people were found dead today at a  
townhouse complex, apparently overcome by carbon monoxide fumes 
from a car left running in an attached garage. 
</P>
<P>
	The unidentified victims were found in two units at the Cedar  
Mill Apartments in downtown Charlotte, city Deputy Fire Chief David 
Duffy said. 
</P>
<P>
	The dead included a man and a woman in a three-story townhouse  
where the car was running and another couple in an adjacent 
townhouse. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators were treating the deaths as accidental.  
</P>
<P>
	``Two were asleep. Two of them may have been trying to get out  
because they were found near stairs,'' said Charlotte-Mecklenburg 
Police Department spokesman Keith Bridges. 
</P>
<P>
	Three other residents in a third adjacent townhouse were  
sickened by the carbon monoxide and treated at a hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said that someone drove the car into a garage attached to  
the complex Wednesday night and left it running. The garage 
apparently filled with carbon-monoxide fumes, which then filtered 
into the townhouses. 
</P>
<P>
	Firefighters found the bodies shortly after 7:50 a.m. when heat  
from the car set off sprinklers. The car did not catch fire. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
