<DOCNO> APW19990624.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 17:31:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Astros Manager Pays Surprise Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- The Houston Astros got a pleasant surprise  
Thursday when manager Larry Dierker showed up at practice, just one 
day after he checked out of the hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	Well ahead of schedule, Dierker paid a brief visit to the  
Astrodome, delighting his players just 10 days after brain surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was told to come here and be like a fan and not like a  
manager,'' Dierker said. ``So I guess I'll leave about the third 
inning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The upbeat Dierker wasn't expected until later in the week or  
next week. He showed up a day after leaving Methodist Hospital, 
where doctors removed tangled blood vessels that caused him to have 
a seizure. 
</P>
<P>
	He still doesn't plan to return to the dugout until after the  
All-Star break. 
</P>
<P>
	``Considering what he went through, he looks great,'' second  
baseman Craig Biggio said. ``He does have a nasty zipper (scar) on 
his head but he looks great.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wearing a small brimmed straw hat that covered his scar and a  
flowery yellow Hawaiian shirt that has become his trademark, 
Dierker met with his coaching staff and talked with players at 
batting practice. 
</P>
<P>
	He stood for interviews and chatted near the batting cage for  
about 40 minutes before Thursday night's game against the 
Cincinnati Reds. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone has said he's OK, but to see him come through that  
door and shake our hands wearing that shirt makes us feel better,'' 
first baseman Jeff Bagwell said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dierker said his doctor approved the visit. He promised to  
follow medical instructions and won't try to return to the dugout 
too soon. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think all of us who are Type-A personalities, once they know  
they are OK, try to get things going again and get things done,'' 
Dierker said. ``But I'm not going to give myself stress. I'm going 
to do what the doctors tell me to do. 
</P>
<P>
	``It really changes your perspective,'' Dierker said. ``The  
first day I was able to get out of bed and sit at a table, have a 
cup of coffee and read the newspaper, it's the first thing people 
do and don't give it a second thought. 
</P>
<P>
	``For me it was like a miracle.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 17:31:01 </DATE_TIME>
