<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tycoon Brennan Settles Fraud Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- Penny-stock tycoon Robert E. Brennan, facing  
trial on racketeering and fraud charges, has reached settlements 
with New Jersey regulators, state lawyers told a judge on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	No details of the deals will be made public until Monday, when  
they are to be filed with Superior Court Judge Philip M. Freedman. 
</P>
<P>
	If they stick, the settlements avert a non-jury trial that was  
expected to last two to six months. 
</P>
<P>
	Brennan, a longtime Monmouth County resident who now lives in  
Juno Beach, Fla., made no comment to reporters after the deal was 
announced. His bankruptcy lawyer, Gerald Gline, who had come aboard 
in recent days to assist in settlement talks, also declined to 
speak. 
</P>
<P>
	Brennan, 55, became nationally known in the 1980s through  
television commercials for his First Jersey Securities Inc., in 
which he would step from a helicopter and tell investors to ``come 
grow with us.'' The company has been inactive since 1987. 
</P>
<P>
	With an eye on his legal entanglements, he chose the name ``Due  
Process'' for his stable of thoroughbred racing horses in Colts 
Neck. He also had a riverfront home in Brielle. 
</P>
<P>
	State authorities charge that after closing First Jersey,  
Brennan secretly controlled two now-shuttered brokerages, Hibbard 
Brown and L.C. Wegard &AMP; Co. Inc., which pushed stocks he controlled 
onto unwitting investors. 
</P>
<P>
	The state accused Brennan, six others and the brokerages of  
making $300 million in illegal profits at the expense of individual 
investors from 1988 to 1995 by using illegal ``boiler room'' sales 
tactics and manipulating the prices of the low-cost securities. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit sought full restitution for investors, and $900  
million in penalties. Since it is a civil case, the defendants face 
no prison time. 
</P>
<P>
	The trial had been scheduled to start early in the month, but  
Freedman adjourned it until June 16 so defense lawyers could take 
depositions from three other former associates of Brennan. 
</P>
<P>
	That trio -- Richard Brown, former president of Hibbard Brown;  
Leonard B. Greer, owner of Wegard; and Michael McDermott, Wegard 
sales director -- recently settled charges against them and agreed 
to testify against their former patron. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 21:40:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> North Korea 3, Denmark 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Song Ok Jo scored her second goal in two  
games as surprising North Korea dominated Denmark 3-1 Thursday 
night and put itself in position to advance from Group A into the 
quarterfinals of the Women's World Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	North Korea's quick, physical play frustrated Denmark from the  
first minute of play. The North Koreans scored twice in the first 
half and then held on for their first World Cup victory after 
building their lead to 3-0 late in the game. North Korea lost 2-1 
to Nigeria in its opening match and plays the United States Sunday 
in Foxboro Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	North Korea scored first when Jin Pyol Hui left-footed the ball  
into an untended goal in the 15th minute of the match. Danish 
keeper Dorthe Larson left the box in an attempt to intercept a pass 
by Sol Yong Suk, who set up Jin perfectly on the left side a few 
yards inside the penalty box. 
</P>
<P>
	Song's second goal of the tournament was a beauty, putting North  
Korea ahead 2-0 in the 38th minute. Just outside the penalty box 
she spurted past one defender, slipped the ball between the legs of 
a second and drilled a left-footed shot past Larson into the left 
top corner of the net. 
</P>
<P>
	North Korea led 3-0 in the 72nd minute when Kim Kum Sil  
left-footed a loose ball in front of the goal into an empty net 
after Larson fell down in traffic. The ball came Kim's way after a 
corner kick had bounce off one of her teammates. 
</P>
<P>
	Denmark, which opened with a 3-0 loss to the United States,  
scored its first goal of the tournament in the 74th minute off a 
mistake by keeper Kye Tong Sun, who punched a shot on goal instead 
of catching it. The ball bounced at the feet of Janni Johansen, who 
slipped the ball past a defender and into the left corner. 
</P>
<P>
	Denmark had two near-goals in the first half. Jane Rasmussen's  
header off a cross hit the near-post just below the upper angle in 
the 31st minute. Just before the half, Louise Hansen hit the top of 
the bar just over the hand of keeper Kye. 
</P>
<P>
	The Danes appeared upset by the wet field, which was inundated  
after a downpour occurred for about an hour before the game began. 
Two Danes slipped while kicking the ball during the first minute of 
play, including forward Marlene Kristensen, who appear to injure 
her right knee and was taken from the field by ambulance. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
