<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sex Curriculum in Church To Change </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- The Presbyterian Church's sex education  
curriculum will likely be revised to include a more 
abstinence-based stance, church leaders said. 
</P>
<P>
	The 560 commissioners of the Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.)  
general assembly voted Wednesday in support of revising the 
curriculum, which teaches abstinence but also offers 
contraceptives. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure means some of the teachings phased in gradually  
since 1989 could be stricken altogether, particularly the option of 
contraceptive use, which some literature mentions prominently. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal that passed was somewhat less radical than an  
original measure, which would have eliminated all references to 
contraceptives and stopped the distribution of all sexual material 
until the wording was modified. 
</P>
<P>
	Members who proposed the changes said preaching anything but  
abstinence sends the wrong message. 
</P>
<P>
	``This lacks biblical integrity,'' said Katherine Goyette of San  
Joaquin, Calif., a youth advisor to the assembly. ``We can teach 
the joy of sexual relationships, but we are called to live a life 
that proclaims Jesus. We cannot conform any longer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But some said teaching only abstinence is no longer practical.  
With teenagers exposed to so many sexual images, they said, failing 
to provide education will cause bigger problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think an abstinence-only curriculum doesn't respond to  
reality,'' said Donna Riley of Princeton, N.J. ``The church has a 
responsibility to protect teenagers from things like unwanted 
pregnancies, not to mention (sexually-transmitted) diseases.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Congregations, parents and some church schools within the  
denomination widely use the church's sex curriculum, but it's not 
mandatory. 
</P>
<P>
	The curriculum must now be modified and submitted to a committee  
for approval within two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Also this week at the assembly, the issue of gay and lesbian  
ordination is expected to resurface. By Friday, the general 
assembly was expected to tackle a measure that strikes language 
from the church constitution, which could open the door to 
homosexual ordination. 
</P>
<P>
	The Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.) has about 3 million members.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
