<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Plan for Penguins Criticized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Lawyers for the Pittsburgh Penguins' landlord  
told a bankruptcy judge today that Mario Lemieux's plan to save the 
bankrupt team is unsatisfactory, even though the retired player has 
offered to pay the landlord in full. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Bernard Markovitz, however, was  
unconvinced by Philadelphia-based SMG Inc.'s arguments. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's obvious that you have an agenda other than being paid,''  
the judge said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for Lemieux and SMG, which subleases the Civic Arena to  
the Penguins for more than $6 million a year, ended talks Wednesday 
night without an agreement that could have given Lemieux a better 
chance of buying the team. 
</P>
<P>
	His plan calls for removing SMG as the landlord. SMG leases the  
Civic Arena from the Public Auditorium Authority for $350,000 a 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Markovitz today is expected to choose Lemieux's plan or one from  
the NHL. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux's agent, Tom Reich, said he still hoped Markovitz would  
confirm Lemieux's plan. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, the negotiators failed to decide on either a new  
lease for the team or a buyout of the SMG lease, said SMG attorney 
Daniel Shapira. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux lawyer Doug Campbell told Markovitz on Wednesday that  
Lemieux could not buy the franchise if the Penguins owe more than 
$10 million to SMG. 
</P>
<P>
	In a ruling last week, Markovitz said SMG's lease with the  
Penguins was actually ``a financing device masquerading as a 
lease.'' The judge said the deal had been set up as a cover for a 
cash infusion for the team. 
</P>
<P>
	Markovitz found that SMG paid $24 million to Penguins owner  
Howard Baldwin for the rights to manage the arena and sublease it 
to the team. Baldwin used that money to buy the team from Edward 
DeBartolo. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux, a retired Penguins center who is owed money by the  
team, is leading a group that is trying to buy the team and has the 
endorsement of Pittsburgh and Allegheny County officials and the 
NHL. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the NHL also has a fallback plan that could fold the  
franchise and sell it out of town if Markovitz does not approve a 
reorganization plan. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Lemieux proposal is not approved, the NHL deal will be  
the only plan on the table. 
</P>
<P>
	The NHL has set a deadline for Sunday to resolve the bankruptcy  
so that the league can schedule games for the upcoming hockey 
season. The player draft is to start on Saturday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
