<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Va. Tech Gets Big East Offer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BLACKSBURG, Va. (AP) -- Virginia Tech, which rose into college  
football's upper echelon as a two-time Bowl Alliance representative 
of the Big East Conference in the mid-1990s, has been offered full 
membership in the league. 
</P>
<P>
	Virginia Tech and Big East officials both confirmed the offer  
Thursday, though neither the school nor the conference would say 
when the Hokies might join. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a positive step forward for the university and  
Virginia Tech athletics,'' Tech President Paul Torgersen said in a 
release. ``There are some conditions contained in the proposal that 
will require evaluation and thoughtful ... consideration.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Hokies, who haven't been an all-sports member of one  
conference for more than 30 years, are a member of the Big East for 
football only, and they have used that affiliation to push their 
football team into the national spotlight. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, they advanced to the Sugar Bowl and earned arguably  
their biggest victory ever, 28-10 against Texas. The following 
year, they again represented the Big East in the alliance and lost 
41-21 to Nebraska in the Orange Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	Apart from football, the Hokies are members of the Atlantic 10  
Conference in 19 sports and they wrestle in the Eastern Wrestling 
League. 
</P>
<P>
	School officials declined to say what conditions were under  
discussion. Big East spokesman Rob Carolla, however, said that any 
time a school joins a conference, there are issues like revenue 
sharing, membership fees and a phase-in schedule that have to be 
worked out. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hokies last single-conference affiliation was with the  
Southern Conference, from 1921-1965. 
</P>
<P>
	Tech, West Virginia, Rutgers and Temple were offered  
football-only membership in the Big East in 1990, joining 
all-sports members Syracuse, Boston College, Miami and Pittsburgh 
to form the conference's football league. Those four all-sports 
members had threatened to leave the conference if football was not 
added. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1994, the conference invited West Virginia and Rutgers to  
become all-sports members, leaving Virginia Tech and Temple as the 
only football-only schools. Last year, Notre Dame joined the 
conference in all sports except football and wrestling. 
</P>
<P>
	Other members of the Big East included Connecticut, Georgetown,  
Providence, St. John's, Seton Hall and Villanova. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
