<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Mexican officials have found lead poisoning  
in more than 4,000 children living near a northern silver refinery, 
double the number reported in a study in 1998, newspapers reported 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Health Undersecretary Jose Narro told a Senate subcommittee that  
56 children were so severely poisoned they required hospital 
treatment, the newspaper Reforma reported. Television reports said 
that only 26 are still hospitalized. 
</P>
<P>
	Children living near the Met-Mex Penoles plant in Torreon, 500  
miles north of Mexico City, have been shown to have abnormally high 
levels of lead in their blood. 
</P>
<P>
	In May, the government announced a plan to evacuate a 20-block  
area surrounding the plant, demolish 393 homes, bury lead-tainted 
soil under asphalt and establish a $6 million fund to help sick 
children. 
</P>
<P>
	Lead can cause digestive problems, mental disturbances and  
paralysis. In extreme cases, it can cause muscular collapse, 
convulsions and brain disease. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- More than 5,000 students and faculty of  
Mexico's largest public university demonstrated Thursday against a 
student-led strike that has kept the school closed for more than 
two months. 
</P>
<P>
	Francisco Barnes de Castro, rector of the National Autonomous  
University of Mexico, said the protest was to ``demand the return 
of our university.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barnes sparked the strike with a March 15 decision to raise  
annual tuition from 2 cents to $145 per year. 
</P>
<P>
	He has since agreed to make those fees voluntary, but that  
concession failed to persuade radical students to end the strike, 
begun in April. They say the constitution guarantees a free 
university education. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	LIMA, Peru (AP) -- Traces of the cancer-causing chemical dioxin  
were found in 128 tons of powdered milk imported from Belgium and 
destined for a food program feeding poor schoolchildren, Peruvian 
health officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	President Alberto Fujimori assured Peruvians late Wednesday that  
none of the contaminated powdered milk had been distributed and 
would be returned to Belgium. 
</P>
<P>
	Peru banned Belgian meat and milk imports on June 16 for 90 days  
after reports emerged that a Belgian firm had supplied 
dioxin-contaminated animal feed to farmers raising pigs and cows. 
</P>
<P>
	Peruvian health authorities have not determined the level of  
dioxin in the powdered milk, imported by the Peruvian company IGASA 
in March before the ban was implemented. IGASA officials said the 
milk is not a health threat. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
