<HEADLINE> American Studying Safety Procedures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- American Airlines CEO Donald Carty said Thursday  
that the airline is looking at safety issues involving its pilot 
training and other procedures in the wake of a crash in Arkansas 
this month which killed 11 people. 
</P>
<P>
	Carty also welcomed an ongoing probe of the accident by the  
National Transportation Safety Board. ``It would be really 
irresponsible of us and the NTSB not to ask the questions,'' he 
said following a speech to the British American Commerce 
Association. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1993, American has had two fatal crashes killing 171  
people and four accidents causing minor injuries, more accidents 
than any other U.S. carrier in the last six years. 
</P>
<P>
	NTSB investigators are focusing on procedures and training and  
the corporate culture at the Fort Worth-based American. The agency 
expects to examine the frequency of pilot training at American, 
whether standard operating procedures are emphasized enough in 
training and if pilots are granted too much discretion in the air. 
</P>
<P>
	In late 1994, American Airlines changed its training practices  
with captains receiving 20 percent fewer hours of training each 
year. Before the changes, American Airlines' captains would get 10 
hours of simulator training annually during two visits to the 
flight school in Fort Worth. That was changed to eight hours during 
one visit to the school. 
</P>
<P>
	``Up to this point there have been no problems that we're aware  
of,'' American spokesman John Hotard said of the training 
reduction. ``Obviously as we go through the review that will be 
something we look at because we'll be looking at everything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the Federal Aviation Administration and the airline,  
along with outside consultants, will review safety and training 
programs. The evaluation is the first part of a nationwide effort 
to look at all airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	The airline has already begun its own investigations into  
training and attitude at the company, said Carty. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'd be irresponsible not to ask the questions,'' said Carty,  
who is chairman at American's parent company, AMR Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	The NTSB investigation into American's safety record is similar  
to all that are done following any accident, according to agency 
spokesman Ted Lopatkiewicz. 
</P>
<P>
	``In every investigation we look into the operations of an  
airline and what role they may have played in an accident,'' 
Lopatkiewicz said, adding that the probe is in the early stages. 
</P>
<P>
	Aside from the MD-80 crash during a thunderstorm in Little Rock  
on June 1, other accidents contributing to the analysis of 
procedures at Fort Worth, Texas-based American include the crash of 
an American jet en route to Cali, Colombia, in December 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators said four other American planes had mishaps while  
landing, causing minor injuries. The planes were damaged, but the 
accidents attracted little attention. 
</P>
<P>
	In the most recent of these, on June 14 a Boeing 757 hit the  
airport fence in Tegucigalpa, Honduras, during an approach that was 
too low. None of the 190 people aboard was injured. 
</P>
<P>
	A former NTSB official said the string of accidents since 1993  
is something the airline should worry about. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be irresponsible not to step back and see whether  
your accident prevention program was working,'' said C.O. Miller, 
who headed the NTSB's Bureau of Safety during much of the 1980s. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
