<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Union Cavalrymen Finally ID'd </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Something compelled James Harris to  
answer the bugle's call a second time. 
</P>
<P>
	The 24-year-old Missourian had seen more than his share of  
action in the Civil War during his 10 months as a Union cavalryman. 
But perhaps Harris felt he'd left the job unfinished. Maybe he 
missed the camaraderie of his old outfit. 
</P>
<P>
	``According to the family story, he just got on his horse and  
ran away without telling anybody,'' said Katie Findlay of Poplar 
Bluff, Mo., the wife of Harris' great-grandson. 
</P>
<P>
	Months after re-enlisting in 1864, Harris died in battle in  
Alabama and was buried for more than a century as an ``unknown.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, his and two other ``unknown'' markers are scheduled  
to be replaced with headstones identifying their graves -- the 
culmination of sleuthing by an author who documented their 
sacrifices. 
</P>
<P>
	David Evans, a writer from Athens, Ga., followed the trail of  
military documents to find Harris; William Britt, a 38-year-old 
volunteer from Paris, Tenn.; and Pvt. David Sage, 20, of Bellevue, 
Neb., at the Marietta National Cemetery in Georgia. 
</P>
<P>
	Evans gathered the evidence while researching his 1996 book  
``Sherman's Horsemen,'' which recounts Union cavalry raids around 
Atlanta in 1864. 
</P>
<P>
	``Officers who set up the national cemeteries knew they were  
going to have an awful lot of unknown soldiers on their hands,'' 
Evans said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They kept very precise notes. They knew at some point someone  
might come along with enough information to identify some of these 
unknown soldiers. I don't think they thought it would take 134 
years, but that's how this worked out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In December 1861, the 5th Iowa Cavalry began as the Curtis Horse  
Regiment near St. Louis, Mo. Two of its leaders were from Iowa and 
it included soldiers from throughout the Midwest. 
</P>
<P>
	Harris had joined the Osage County Independent Mounted Rifles,  
which became the Cavalry's Company M. 
</P>
<P>
	Less than a month after the regiment was formed, a 16-year-old  
from Nebraska joined. David Sage was the eldest son born to Selah 
and Mary Ann Sage, who were among the first settlers of Sarpy 
County in southeast Nebraska. 
</P>
<P>
	In the summer of 1863, the 5th Iowa Cavalry became part of the  
Army of the Cumberland and eventually moved to Tennessee. Around 
that time, William Britt joined the regiment. Britt, an illiterate 
Irish immigrant, was married and working as a day laborer when he 
decided to enlist. 
</P>
<P>
	A year later, the regiment was selected for its most prestigious  
duty to date. Union Gen. William T. Sherman was ready to advance on 
Atlanta. But before he did, Sherman wanted to cut lines of 
communication and transportation to the city. 
</P>
<P>
	On July 18, 1864, the 5th Iowa Cavalry was ordered to destroy a  
line of railroad trestlework west of Loachapoka, Ala., outside 
Auburn. But as the cavalrymen worked, they were surprised by a 
train carrying Confederate soldiers. 
</P>
<P>
	In the skirmish that followed, the Union forces were driven  
back. Harris and Sage died and later were buried where they fell. 
Seven other men, including Britt, were wounded and left behind. The 
wounded were taken to the Confederate hospital in nearby Notasulga. 
Britt died on Aug. 8 and was buried on the hospital's grounds. 
</P>
<P>
	After the war ended, Army officials began the grim business of  
collecting and cataloging the dead. Finding the bodies of Britt, 
Harris and Sage was easy enough, but there was no way to identify 
them when they were exhumed and moved to the Marietta cemetery. 
</P>
<P>
	``That wasn't uncommon,'' said Steve Meyer, a Civil War  
historian. ``There were no Social Security cards, no driver's 
licenses. And in a situation like this, where the Union forces were 
overwhelmed, they had to leave their dead and wounded behind.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Evans found casualty lists that named Harris and Sage as the  
only Union soldiers killed at one of the battle scenes, while Britt 
was identified as the only Union fatality from the battle who died 
at the Confederate hospital at Notasulga. 
</P>
<P>
	Evans also found Britt's death certificate at the University of  
Texas at Austin. He cross referenced information in the cemetery's 
original burial register with 1869 notes from the U.S. Army about 
where the bodies were found. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the new tombstones being unveiled Friday, only Britt's will  
bear his name. Harris and Sage will receive headstones bearing 
their unit numbers. James Wallace, the cemetery's administrator, 
said with both dying on the same day in the same place, officials 
cannot determine which grave belongs to which man. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Harris' descendants are thrilled he has been found.  
</P>
<P>
	``This is quite a surprise. We had no idea where he was  
buried,'' said his great-grandson, Floyd Findlay, who once traveled 
with his wife to Alabama to try to find Harris' grave. 
</P>
<P>
	Evans was able to get word of Friday's scheduled ceremonies to  
Britt's descendants in Ireland. At Killadriffe Cemetery in 
Kilmolyer, Ireland, they dug up soil from the grave of his parents 
and shipped it to America. Britt will rest under that native soil 
in Georgia. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
