<HEADLINE> Most Asian Markets Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian stock markets ended mostly higher  
Thursday, with Singapore's key index setting its second record in 
as many days and Tokyo shares rising moderately despite the lack of 
fresh incentives. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo's benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 41.57  
points, or 0.24 percent, closing at 17,628.32 as foreign investors 
poured money into the market. On Wednesday, the average fell 190.87 
points, or 1.07 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the U.S. dollar slipped slightly against  
the Japanese yen when expected intervention by Japan's central bank 
to support the dollar failed to materialize. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 121.90 yen in late trading, down from 121.98  
yen late Wednesday in Tokyo and also marginally lower than its 
overnight New York level of 121.92 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	In Singapore, the Straits Times Index climbed 24.26 points, or  
1.1 percent, to 2,191.73, surpassing Wednesday's record close of 
2,167.47. Before that, the Singapore index had not set any records 
since February 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts noted that some foreign fund managers had begun selling  
their holdings, indicating the recent rally may soon run out of 
steam. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors also were bracing for a widely expected U.S. interest  
rate hike, when U.S. monetary officials meet next week. Any such 
rate move could hurt prices on Wall Street and in Asia. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, concerns over U.S. rates also sent Hong Kong stocks  
lower for the second straight day. 
</P>
<P>
	The blue chip Hang Seng Index fell 1.4 percent, or 195.92  
points, to 13,780.12. The Hang Seng had fallen 0.2 percent 
Wednesday from a nearly two-year high above 14,000 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Banking and property stocks, which are sensitive to interest  
rate changes, fell across the board. Investors worry that a U.S. 
rate hike would be matched locally because the Hong Kong dollar is 
pegged to the U.S. currency. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Indonesian shares plunged, triggered by an 11-percent  
tumble in PT Indofood Sukses Makmur. The JSX Composite Index closed 
down 18.550 points, or 2.6 percent, to 682.119 points. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian shares rose after a finance official  
said the government is considering upgrading this year's economic 
forecast. The Composite Index rose 6.89 points, or 0.9 percent, to 
801.72 points. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine stocks rose, propped up by heavy buying of  
property concern BW Resources and airline services group Macroasia 
Corp. The PSE index rose 27.61 points, or 1.1 percent, to 2,498.53. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: South Korean shares ended a six-day rally, which had  
added 11 percent to the key Kospi index. The Kospi slipped back 1.3 
percent, or 11.33 points, to 877.30. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Australian shares fell, led by industrial and resources  
stocks. The All Ordinaries Index fell 1 percent, or 30.3 points, to 
2,960.3. 
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Taiwan shares surged as investors gobbled up technology  
and blue-chip plastics and textile shares amid good earnings 
prospects. The Weighted Price Index rose 96.99 points, or 1.1 
percent, to 8,589.31. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand shares rallied, buoyed by a sharp gain  
in market heavyweight Telecom Corp. of New Zealand. The NZSE-40 
Capital Index rose 25.23 points, or 1.2 percent, to 2,129.68. 
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai shares rose, with the SET Index climbing 2.98  
points, or 0.6 percent, to 543.97. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
