<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> San Diego Mayor's Conduct Targeted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- A San Diego County grand jury has accused Mayor  
Susan Golding of civil misconduct in her dealings with the county 
hotel-motel association and its support of a new downtown ballpark 
for the Padres. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel made its accusation in a report to San Diego County  
District Attorney Paul Pfingst, sources who spoke on condition of 
anonymity told The Associated Press and other media outlets 
Wednesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Ric Grenell, Golding's spokesman, said neither he nor the mayor  
had seen the grand jury report and they were withholding comment. 
</P>
<P>
	The San Diego Union-Tribune reported in today's editions that  
the grand jury alleges that Golding offered to support a $4 million 
allocation for a hotel-motel association advertising program in 
exchange for the organization's support of Proposition C, the 
ballpark ballot measure approved by voters last November. 
</P>
<P>
	The $411 million ballpark and downtown development is to be  
financed in part with $225 million in municipal bonds secured by 
hotel-room tax revenues. The ballpark is set for completion by 
2002. 
</P>
<P>
	The grand jury also accused Golding of misconduct for failing to  
appoint new members to the city's watchdog Public Utility Advisory 
Commission when openings occurred. That harmed the city's economic 
interests, the panel contended. 
</P>
<P>
	The mayor's attorney, John Wertz, told the newspaper that  
Golding has done nothing inappropriate and said he and the mayor 
were confident the district attorney would conclude the panel's 
report was without merit. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike a criminal indictment, the only punishment for a public  
official found guilty of civil misconduct is removal from office. 
That could only occur after a jury trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Pfingst planned to hold a news conference later today. His  
spokeswoman, Gayle Falkenthal, said only that Pfingst plans to 
address the panel's report. 
</P>
<P>
	The county grand jury ends its term June 30. Since it was seated  
last year, the panel has criticized many public officials in 
reports, and the group itself has been criticized for the quality 
of its reports. 
</P>
<P>
	Grand jurors said the hotel-motel association backed Proposition  
C only after Golding promised to increase the hotel-room tax 
financing of efforts to market San Diego as a tourist destination. 
</P>
<P>
	Rick Mansur, president of the hotel-motel association, said the  
grand jury was off the mark because his group does not market San 
Diego -- the San Diego Convention and Visitors Bureau does. 
</P>
<P>
	Mansur did say his organization asked Golding for an increase in  
marketing dollars for the bureau, but before the City Council voted 
to put Proposition C on the ballot. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
