<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 17:00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Congressional Pay Increase in Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Senate committee approved a trio of spending  
bills today that would do everything from blocking Clinton 
administration efforts to limit mining on federal lands to leaving 
the door open for a congressional cost-of-living pay raise. 
</P>
<P>
	By 16-9, the Senate Appropriations Committee voted to allow  
hundreds of mines to ignore a 1997 Interior Department ruling that 
attempted to limit the size of waste dumps permitted for mining 
operations using federal lands. 
</P>
<P>
	White House budget office spokeswoman Linda Ricci criticized  
what she called an ``extreme anti-environmental'' provision and all 
but threatened a veto by President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	``In adopting this rider, they're threatening to do serious  
damage to the environment, and they are playing with fire,'' she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	A subcommittee of the panel had voted Tuesday to exempt only  
existing waste sites. On Thursday, the full committee approved an 
amendment by Sen. Larry Craig, R-Idaho, reversing the ruling and 
allowing exemptions for waste sites that have not yet been 
approved. 
</P>
<P>
	Craig said his amendment would affect at least 300 mining  
operations. The proposal would overturn an Interior Department 
ruling that under an 1872 law, mines can use no more than 5 acres 
for their waste. 
</P>
<P>
	``Modern mining cannot operate under those standards,'' Craig  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some Democrats objected. Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash., said the  
Craig amendment ``is asking that our public lands be used for 
larger and larger dump sites.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Committee Republicans were joined by three Democrats -- Sens.  
Robert Byrd of West Virginia, Harry Reid of Nevada, and Daniel 
Inouye of Hawaii -- in supporting Craig's amendment. 
</P>
<P>
	By voice vote, the committee also included language by Sen. Thad  
Cochran, R-Miss., that would block a June 3 executive order by 
Clinton that federal agencies cut their energy consumption by 35 
percent, compared with 1985 levels, between now and 2010. 
</P>
<P>
	Cochran called Clinton's order a ``not well-disguised effort''  
to implement portions of the Kyoto protocol, the international 
agreement by which countries have pledged to cut atmospheric 
pollution by reducing energy use. That agreement has been opposed 
by many Republicans, who worry that it would inhibit economic 
growth. 
</P>
<P>
	Both provisions were included in a $13.9 billion measure  
financing federal land and cultural programs for the coming fiscal 
year. The bill increases funds for operating national parks, but 
cuts Clinton's $797 million request for purchasing parklands to 
$265 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee also approved a $28 billion measure financing the  
Treasury Department and several smaller agencies. 
</P>
<P>
	That bill, like a version approved last month by a House  
Appropriations Committee subcommittee, so far contains no language 
blocking a pay raise for members of Congress. Under a 1989 law, 
lawmakers automatically get an annual cost-of-living pay raise 
unless they vote to deny it, and the Treasury bill is the 
traditional vehicle for doing that. 
</P>
<P>
	An effort to bar the increase could still be made in the House  
or Senate, as it does most years. But earlier this year, House 
Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., discussed the issue with Minority 
Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo. Lawmakers got their last pay raise, to 
$136,700, two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The law pegs the raise to an increase the president proposes  
each year for federal workers. Clinton recommended a 4.4 percent 
increase for the fiscal year that begins Oct. 1, and the 
congressional raise would be expected to be about 3.4 percent, or 
about $4,600. 
</P>
<P>
	The House's Treasury bill would double the president's salary to  
$400,000, but the Senate version would not. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate committee also approved a measure that would provide  
$410 million to the District of Columbia's city budget. 
</P>
<P>
	All three spending bills passed the Senate panel by 28-0 votes.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
