<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House-Senate GOP Raise $9M at Dinner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Between scenes of braying donkeys, the giant  
screen showed the guests of this year's Republican congressional 
dinner their worst nightmare: a Democratic-controlled Congress and 
White House in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	The film, meant as a cautionary tale, ended on a more comforting  
note for the GOP faithful by listing Republican achievements and 
predicting victory. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans also were consoled by the night's $9 million take, a  
record for a non-election year. The 1997 dinner raised $7 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott thanked the 3,308 guests who  
had paid $1,500 a plate for a seat at the black-tie affair. 
</P>
<P>
	``Thanks to your support, after all these years we're going to  
elect a Republican president. We're going to keep our majority in 
the Senate and the House of Representatives,'' said Lott, R-Miss. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the biggest donors were corporations interested in bills  
before Congress, and the biggest fund-raisers were lobbyists and 
lawmakers, who personally pushed tickets for the dinner. 
</P>
<P>
	BellSouth, Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Corp. and American  
Airlines were among those bringing $100,000 each, earning 
invitations to mingle with congressional leaders at a private 
breakfast in addition to Wednesday night's dinner. 
</P>
<P>
	``What they're doing is giving tonight to us so that we can help  
build Republican majority, build it stronger for 2000. What they 
get from us is a good meal and good government,'' said Stuart Roy, 
a spokesman for the National Republican Senatorial Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	With a net change of six seats each in the House and the Senate  
in next year's election, Democrats could regain control of both for 
the first time since 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	But many big contributors also are giving at a time when  
Congress is considering legislation affecting them. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Chamber of Commerce, which raised $50,000 for the  
dinner, helped lead the recent effort to pass legislation limiting 
lawsuits resulting from Year 2000 computer problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's important for the chamber to be visible with these kinds  
of events,'' said spokesman Frank Coleman. ``It reinforces the 
perception that the chamber is a political player in this town.'' 
</P>
<P>
	BellSouth contributed $100,000, earning corporate co-chairman  
status, at the request of the dinner chairman, Sen. Paul Coverdell, 
R-Ga., said company spokesman Bill McCloskey. ``We have lots of 
friends in Congress and we support our friends,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The telephone company supports legislation that would let local  
phone companies send data worldwide, instead of restricting that 
business to long-distance telephone companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Other big donors include two tobacco companies, Brown &AMP;  
Williamson and U.S. Tobacco. In its report accompanying the Justice 
Department spending bill, the Senate Appropriations Committee last 
week said the bill included no money for the department to file a 
lawsuit against tobacco companies. The White House plans to sue the 
companies to recover smoking-related costs. 
</P>
<P>
	Also helping to raise funds were Kenneth Kies, former chief of  
staff of the congressional Joint Committee on Taxation; and Deborah 
Steelman, former deputy assistant to President Reagan. There were 
more than two dozen corporate supporters, including Microsoft, 
American Airlines and Bristol-Myers Squibb. 
</P>
<P>
	To encourage lawmakers to raise money for the congressional  
dinner, Rep. Rob Portman, R-Ohio, who headed fund-raising on the 
House side, pitted region against region. 
</P>
<P>
	The Northeastern lawmakers won by raising $584,000. Rep. John  
Sweeney, R-N.Y., led the effort, bringing in $338,000 himself. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
