<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Johnson, Greene Top Track Event </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EUGENE, Ore. (AP) -- In a meeting of speed versus strength, it's  
Maurice Greene against Michael Johnson at 200 meters, the world 
record-holder in the 100 meters facing the world record-holder in 
the 200. 
</P>
<P>
	It's the main event of the 38 titles decided this weekend at the  
USA Track and Field Championships at the University of Oregon's 
Hayward Field. The showdown is Sunday at 3:52 p.m. EDT on CBS. 
</P>
<P>
	The plot lines are many.  
</P>
<P>
	Greene is coming off his world-record performance of 9.79  
seconds in the 100 last week at Athens, Greece, and now has the 
unofficial title of world's fastest human. He doesn't think that 
makes him the world's greatest sprinter. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to do more than one event,'' he said Wednesday. ``You  
have to run the relays and the 200.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His coach, John Smith, agreed.  
</P>
<P>
	``To be the world's fastest sprinter, you have to run the  
furlong (200),'' Smith said. ``It may take him a year or two to get 
there, but he's only 24.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, 31, already has established himself as the best  
200-meter runner in history. He has run the two fastest times ever, 
19.66 at the 1996 Olympic trials, then an astonishing 19.32 at the 
Summer Games in Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	Greene's best is 19.86 at Stockholm, Sweden, in July 1997. The  
last time he faced Johnson at 200 meters was May 1998 in the 
Prefontaine Classic at Hayward Field, and Greene won decisively 
over his ailing opponent in a wind-aided 19.88. 
</P>
<P>
	The circumstances are different now. Greene is still celebrating  
his record run in the 100, and Johnson is healthy but competing for 
the first time since winning the 400 at the Prefontaine Classic 
nearly four weeks ago. He skipped one meet after that because of 
the death of his grandmother. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith knows Johnson will be prepared and Greene will have to be  
at his absolute best to beat him. 
</P>
<P>
	``Michael doesn't compete unless he's ready,'' Smith said.  
</P>
<P>
	At 6-foot-1, 175 pounds, Johnson is bigger and stronger than the  
5-9, 165-pound Greene. Johnson has an unusual but efficient style 
of running, staying erect and moving his hands up and down like a 
wooden soldier. Greene's manner more resembles the typical 
sprinter, head slightly bowed, a rolling motion and arms thrashing. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson is much more experienced than Greene at the longer  
sprints. He also was the 1996 Olympic champion at 400 meters and 
has run the second-fastest time ever at that distance, 43.39, just 
off Butch Reynolds' world record of 43.29. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm still learning the 200,'' Greene said. ``I want to run a  
phenomenal race Sunday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 200 heats and semifinals are Saturday, and Greene thinks  
that will be to his advantage for the final. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll have run two 200 races in one day, which means I'll have  
run a total of 400 meters,'' he said. ``He's a 400-meter runner and 
used to running that distance. I'm not. But on Sunday, I'll have to 
run only 200 meters. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the 100, I'm a very strong finisher. I want to show that  
I'm a very strong finisher in the 200, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since Greene is planning to double in the 100 and 200 at the  
World Championships in August at Seville, Spain, this is a very 
important race for him. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's now stepping into an area in which Michael is very  
comfortable, and it's very challenging,'' Smith said. ``Michael can 
run 20 seconds falling out of bed. If he doesn't run under 20 
seconds, people are disappointed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Greene has not run the 200 often, but he trained for it last  
year, and that helped his speed in the 100, Smith said. 
Surprisingly, Greene ran the 200 last week at Athens -- after his 
record in the 100 -- and finished second in 20.03 to teammate Ato 
Boldon's 1999 world-best 19.86. 
</P>
<P>
	``He needed that race for psychological reasons, because he's  
doing it here,'' Smith said. ``He said, `You can't keep me out.' 
</P>
<P>
	``He likes challenges. He doesn't rest on his laurels.''  
</P>
<P>
	In addition to Johnson and Greene, the 200 field is loaded.  
There's also 1992 Olympic champion Mike Marsh; 1999 U.S leader John 
Capel, a Florida freshman who ran 19.87 in winning the NCAA title; 
1997 world indoor champion Kevin Little; defending champion Gentry 
Bradley; 1997 U.S. outdoor champion Jon Drummond; 1998 U.S. indoor 
champion Ramon Clay; Tyree Washington, ranked No. 2 in the U.S. 
last year, and Curtis Perry, the 1998 NCAA champion. 
</P>
<P>
	The meet began today with finals in the men's 10,000 and triple  
jump, and the women's discus throw, hammer throw and steeplechase. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
