<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Rejects Ga. Unwed Fathers Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court refused on Thursday to  
revive a Georgia law that said an unwed father could not inherit 
from his deceased children if he had not supported or treated the 
children as his own. 
</P>
<P>
	The court, by a 6-3 vote, rejected an appeal by a Georgia woman  
who said her son's father took no responsibility for him but sued 
in an attempt to collect monetary damages after the young man was 
killed in a traffic accident. 
</P>
<P>
	Georgia courts struck down the state's law, which had applied to  
unwed fathers but not to unwed mothers. The state courts said the 
law contained an unconstitutional gender-based classification. 
</P>
<P>
	Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices Antonin Scalia  
and Clarence Thomas voted to study the case but four votes are 
needed to grant such review. 
</P>
<P>
	Writing for the three, Thomas said the Georgia law ``does not  
necessarily draw a gender-based classification but arguably 
distinguishes between two different categories of men: fathers who 
support their children born out of wedlock and fathers who do 
not.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The case was filed by Zenobia Hamilton Rainey, who said her  
20-year-old son, DeAndre Bernard Hamilton, was one of three college 
cheerleaders killed in August 1997 when the van they were riding in 
crashed because of a tire defect. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamilton's father, Robert Lee Chever, sued over the accident,  
seeking half of all damages awarded as a result of his son's death. 
</P>
<P>
	Rainey asked a Gwinnett County court to bar Chever from  
inheriting anything from his son. Although his paternity was 
legally established in 1979, she said Chever never supported his 
son or treated him as his child. 
</P>
<P>
	She said Chever lived less than a mile away but had no contact  
with Hamilton until the youth confronted him when he was about 15 
years old. 
</P>
<P>
	Chever argued that the inheritance law violated the  
Constitution's guarantee of equal protection, and the Georgia 
Supreme Court agreed. 
</P>
<P>
	In the appeal denied review Thursday, Rainey said the  
invalidated law should be salvaged because it ``merely recognizes 
inherent differences in the roles of men and women'' in 
childbearing. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Rainey vs. Chever, 98-1478.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
