<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Agassi Continues Winning Ways </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WIMBLEDON, England (AP) -- Andre Agassi took another step  
Thursday toward a feat last achieved by Bjorn Borg in 1980 -- 
winning the men's singles title at the French Open and Wimbledon in 
the same year. 
</P>
<P>
	But Agassi is not planning to study how the great Swedish star  
did it. 
</P>
<P>
	After brushing aside Argentina's Guillermo Canas 6-3, 6-4, 6-3  
to reach the third round of Wimbledon, Agassi was asked whether he 
might take a look at how Borg completed the difficult double 19 
years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Borg is the last player to win Wimbledon on grass just two weeks  
after capturing the French Open on clay. The Swede won six French 
Opens and five Wimbledons, all from 1974 to 1981. 
</P>
<P>
	Agassi says the caliber of competition can't be compared.  
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of things are different now than then,'' said Agassi,  
who won Wimbledon in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you look at a guy who was as fast as Borg and could hit  
the ball with such pinpoint accuracy, and guys were forced to try 
and generate pace with smaller and less capable equipment (than 
they have now), it's easy to see why he could dominate. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he played today, he would present the same problems on a  
different level in a different way, and I learn from his 
competitive instincts and certainly his tenacity. But the game 
changes all the time,'' Agassi said. 
</P>
<P>
	Agassi's main challenge Thursday was his own service games  
against Canas. Although he was a set up, the No. 4 seed went 3-0 
down in the second before winning six of the next seven games to 
capture the second set. 
</P>
<P>
	``Until I was down 3-0 in the second set, I hadn't had one  
service game where I wasn't down 15-30, 0-15, 0-30 or 15-40,'' he 
said. ``There wasn't one service game that I was holding easily. I 
snuck through the first set without giving up my serve. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was returning well and hitting the ball big and he was  
fighting hard. It turned out in hindsight that he couldn't keep 
that level up, but at that particular stage of the match he was 
speaking for himself out there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Agassi has a comparatively easy route to the quarterfinal. His  
next match is against Spaniard Alberto Martin, who, until this 
Wimbledon, had never been past the first round of a Grand Slam 
tournament and is unlikely to give the experienced American any 
major problems. 
</P>
<P>
	At 20, Martin is still to win a tournament above Challenger  
level and says he prefers to play on clay. 
</P>
<P>
	The first seeded player facing Agassi likely will be Germany's  
Tommy Haas in the round of 16. Haas, seeded 14th, has so far 
struggled through two five-setters and has to get past improving 
Australian Wayne Arthurs in the third round. 
</P>
<P>
	Agassi also admits that the surface here is a little in his  
favor. 
</P>
<P>
	Wimbledon has seen no rain at all in the first four days and the  
surfaces are dry and firm. 
</P>
<P>
	``I do think it benefits me a little more. It's better for my  
game, but Court 1 today was playing harder and quicker than the 
Centre Court and the ball was getting away from me a little me and 
I had to kind of make an adjustment out there. 
</P>
<P>
	``It does help me if a court is playing harder and bouncing  
higher, but I certainly can't count on that.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
