<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kubrick Movie Review Angers Studio </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Before this week, hardly anyone knew much more  
about Stanley Kubrick's mysterious last film, ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' 
than the fact that Tom Cruise and Nicole Kidman get really naked in 
it. 
</P>
<P>
	Sure, rumors abounded about the film, completed just before the  
legendary filmmaker's death. But Warner Bros. has not yet screened 
it for critics and Kubrick's rigorous insistence on secrecy meant 
few people knew what they were talking about. 
</P>
<P>
	Enter London film critic Alexander Walker, a Kubrick biographer  
who, as a family friend, was allowed to view the movie early. 
</P>
<P>
	Walker then published a review, including an in-depth plot  
summary, in Tuesday's Evening Standard newspaper. And now, thanks 
to the Internet, ``Eyes Wide Shut'' has segued from the best-kept 
to the worst-kept secret in Hollywood. 
</P>
<P>
	The Evening Standard's Web site saw such a huge surge in traffic  
Wednesday that the paper said some high-tech rejiggering had to be 
done to make sure the glut of people trying to read the review 
didn't lock up the site. 
</P>
<P>
	Predictably, the people at Warner Bros. are upset by Walker's  
actions -- as is Kubrick's family, according to a studio 
spokeswoman. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was a family friend, they showed it to him and he betrayed  
their trust,'' spokeswoman Nancy Kirkpatrick said. ``The family is 
very hurt and angry. It certainly wasn't the plan, and we are not 
happy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kirkpatrick said the film was not to be screened for critics  
until July 10, six days before its opening in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Walker was out of the country and could not be reached for  
comment, but he defended the timing of his review in Thursday's 
Evening Standard. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was not under any embargo,'' the paper quoted him as saying.  
</P>
<P>
	``Eyes Wide Shut,'' Kubrick's 13th film, was completed a week  
before the legendary director died in March at age 70. 
</P>
<P>
	If you don't want to know what it's about, then don't read any  
further. 
</P>
<P>
	The film, according to Walker's review, stars Cruise and Kidman  
as William and Alice Harper, ``protagonists in a story of how an 
apparently happily married couple, rich, successful New Yorkers ... 
are set at odds with each other by their dreams and fantasies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After a party at a grand mansion where each is tempted by the  
fruits of another, they quiz each other about their erotic 
fantasies and find out more than perhaps they wanted to know, 
including the fact that Kidman's character once had an affair, 
Walker says. 
</P>
<P>
	``Eyes Wide Shut'' then follows Cruise on the rebound from his  
wife's sexual revelation, as he ponders necrophilia, patronizes a 
prostitute and explores sex games among New York's rich and famous, 
curiously clad in cloaks and Venetian masks. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even at its most baffling,'' Walker says, ``it is an  
astonishing work made with masterly control and at the same time a 
humanity that this director's detractors insisted he did not 
possess.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 16:40:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Defends Affirmative Action </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore attacked critics of  
affirmative action Thursday, saying it's not time to abandon 
``special efforts'' that have achieved progress. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore defended the goals of affirmative action and toured a gay  
and lesbian center during campaign stops meant to show him as an 
inclusive leader. He was finishing a two-day California 
fund-raising blitz expected to bring in over $1 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking to a largely black audience at a campaign fund-raiser  
in the affluent suburb of Bel Air, Gore listed some of the advances 
for minorities -- a shrinking wage gap between blacks and whites and 
high school graduation rates that are close to even. 
</P>
<P>
	But he said the overall wealth of black and Hispanic families --  
wealth built up over years and handed down through generations -- is 
less than one-tenth that of white families. 
</P>
<P>
	This ``captures the accumulated impact of history cascading down  
throughout the generations,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore did not lay out an affirmative action plan of his own. But  
he quarreled with those who argue that in racial relations, ``we've 
had a generation of success and so we can abandon the special 
efforts that have brought us this far.'' 
</P>
<P>
	An Urban League report last year found black families lag far  
behind whites in the accumulation of wealth and personal assets. 
Even among households earning $50,000 or more, where the wealth gap 
is narrowest, blacks have barely half the median net worth of white 
families, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	About 125 people paid $1,000 each to attend the fund-raiser.  
</P>
<P>
	Later he visited the Gay and Lesbian Center, touring the  
community center's residential wing and talking with three members 
in front of the press. 
</P>
<P>
	Two of them were openly skeptical about Gore's visit, which came  
a week after his opponent for the Democratic presidential 
nomination, former Sen. Bill Bradley, stopped by. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to know exactly why you're here,'' said 20-year-old  
Javier Garcia. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm here to learn and pay honor to this place,'' Gore replied.  
</P>
<P>
	Gore voiced support for legislation introduced in Congress on  
Thursday that would prohibit job discrimination against homosexuals 
while also banning preferential treatment for them. He said he also 
favored outlawing hate crimes, although he did not define what 
might fall under that description. 
</P>
<P>
	Michelle Byler, 22, said after the meeting that she was left  
with ``no impression for Al Gore.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``He didn't really speak to me or say anything too impressive,''  
she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore spokesman Chris Lehane said the two events underscored  
Gore's conviction that ``we are much stronger as a country when all 
aspects of our community work together and come together.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
