<DOCNO> APW19990624.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 21:40:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Proposed Merger of 3 Unions Delayed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- The big merger of the International Association  
of Machinists and Aerospace Workers with the United Auto Workers 
and United Steelworkers of America won't happen anytime soon. 
</P>
<P>
	The unions have put the merger on hold indefinitely, but say  
talks will continue to combine the UAW and Steelworkers unions. 
</P>
<P>
	In a brief statement, the presidents of the three unions said  
the UAW and Steelworkers unions have more comparable organizational 
structures and would ``take the next step in the unification 
process by conducting immediate discussions to join their two 
unions together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``During this process, the three unions will continue to meet  
and continue their ultimate goal of reaching unification of all 
three unions,'' concluded the statement, which was posted on the 
Machinists union Web site Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Machinists spokesman Robert Kalaski said Thursday that  
differences in how the three unions elect their leaders was a major 
factor in the decision to delay the merger of all three. The 
Machinists have direct elections of their officials; the UAW and 
Steelworkers unions do not. 
</P>
<P>
	Kalaski said leaders of all three unions realized at least a  
year ago that their initial goal to merge by 2000 was unrealistic. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not dead,'' he said. ``There's still some things in the  
pot and more going in. If they don't do it by 2000, there's nothing 
wrong with 2003 or 2004. But we're going to do it right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Talks to merge the three unions began in July 1995. With more  
than 2 million members, the merged union would be the nation's 
largest. The merger was seen as a way to increase the unions' clout 
and eliminate duplicate efforts in organizing and lobbying. But it 
faced many difficulties from the start. 
</P>
<P>
	``It isn't a simple process to merge three organizations this  
different,'' said Harley Shaiken, a labor professor at the 
University of California-Berkeley. ``There are differences that 
span from the presidents down to the local unions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shaiken said the unions are cooperating more than before the  
talks began, especially in their political activities. ``So even 
though the former merger may be on hold, they're working together 
on key issues. And each of the three is doing well on its own, so 
you don't have desperation fueling the merger.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kalaski denied that the larger size of the UAW strike fund was a  
factor in the decision to delay the merger. ``All three unions have 
very healthy strike funds in proportion to their membership,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Calls to UAW spokesmen in Detroit were not returned.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 22:50:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore's Thesis Could Help Him </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Al Gore, the Harvard undergraduate, wrote a  
piece of campaign advice that Al Gore, the presidential candidate, 
could well heed: Personality is crucial for presidents in the 
television age. 
</P>
<P>
	It's the very trait some people think Gore lacks in his bid for  
the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked what word best describes him, two-thirds of Americans  
polled this spring said: ``Boring.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore, 51, was well versed about the interplay of personality and  
politics when he was in his early 20s. 
</P>
<P>
	His college thesis concluded that as soon as TV cameras began  
panning the political landscape, as soon as bright TV lights 
spotlighted presidential news conferences, as soon as presidents 
could bypass reporters and talk directly to millions of American TV 
viewers, personality became more than just a plus for presidential 
timber. 
</P>
<P>
	``A key factor in this trend is the increasing importance of the  
president's personality,'' Gore wrote in his 1969 paper, which was 
titled ``The Impact of Television on the Conduct of the Presidency 
1947-1969.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Because of this,'' he continued in staid, academic prose, ``it  
is possible to speculate that a 'role requirement' of the president 
in the future might become 'visual communication.' Just as an 
effective speechmaking technique has been a role requirement in the 
past.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore presented his 103-page thesis, which traces the history of  
presidents on TV, to earn a bachelor's degree in government at 
Harvard. Back in 1969, Gore's father, Al Gore Sr., the late senator 
from Tennessee, gave it to Herbert Klein, communications director 
for President Nixon. Klein filed it and it ended up in President 
Nixon's papers stored at the National Archives. 
</P>
<P>
	The advent of television in politics prompted the public to  
substitute personality for issues when evaluating presidential 
appearances, Gore surmised in his paper. ``This is, of course, 
human nature and politicians have always known it,'' he wrote. 
``However, the old medium, newspapers, filtered out references to 
the president's personality, and reported primarily the issues 
involved.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thirty years later, personality is an issue for Gore's campaign  
for president, says Aubrey Immelman, an associate professor of 
psychology at St. John's University in Minnesota who presented a 
study on Gore's political personality last year to the 
International Society of Political Psychology. 
</P>
<P>
	Who is Al Gore? Immelman's study reveals ``a dutiful,  
conscientious character infused with a distinctly aloof, 
introverted aspect.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The American public has the wrong perception of Gore, insists  
his wife, Tipper. If boring means being a great husband and father 
while still managing to be ``funny, sexy and there for you when you 
need him,'' she'll take ``boring'' any day, Mrs. Gore gushed 
recently on ``The Oprah Winfrey Show.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked about Gore's reserved nature, Marla Romash, deputy  
chairman of the Gore campaign, sighs. 
</P>
<P>
	``The vice president has answered this,'' she says. ``He's said  
'I am who I am.' Anybody who knows Al Gore knows he's a funny, 
engaging, warm guy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Late-night talk show hosts think he's funny too. In the past six  
months, Gore has been the butt of 52 of their jokes, according to 
the Center for Media and Public Affairs in Washington, which keeps 
a running joke tally. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore even pokes fun at himself, repeating the tired joke about  
how he's so dull that the Secret Service code name for him is ``Al 
Gore.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To be a contender for 2000, Immelman says, Gore needs to drop  
the self-effacing jokes and send the message that his stiffness 
reflects integrity; his woodenness, a portent of what would be a 
focused approach to the business of leading the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	Personality -- or the lack of one -- is an issue that Gore can  
only overcome with fresh ideas, said Erwin Hargrove, a political 
science professor at Vanderbilt University who wrote a book on 
presidential leadership, style and personality. 
</P>
<P>
	Hargrove was in Carthage, Tenn., earlier this month when Gore  
launched his presidential campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was his sober self,'' Hargrove said ``Then he started  
shouting. I guess he was trying to show he has some blood in his 
veins. It doesn't work. I think Albert has enough force of 
personality. He needs a message.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 18:30:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gwynn Back on Disabled List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Tony Gwynn's pursuit of 3,000 hits is on hold  
again. 
</P>
<P>
	The San Diego Padres star was placed on the 15-day disabled list  
for the second time this season Thursday with a pulled left calf. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be easy to sit here and be frustrated and say, `Hey,  
I'm this close to 3,000. What the hell's going on?' But I take the 
approach that it could be worse,'' Gwynn said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gwynn, an eight-time NL batting champion, needs 18 hits to  
become the 22nd player to get 3,000 hits. He spent three weeks on 
the DL earlier this season because of the same injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the setback, Gwynn is confident he'll reach 3,000 hits  
this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``It doesn't concern me, because I'm gonna get 'em,'' he said.  
``I mean, I've played too long to just be totally ticked off 
because I'm 18 hits short and I can't play. When I get back out 
there, I'm going to get 18 hits.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gwynn, 39, hasn't played since leaving Saturday's game against  
Pittsburgh. The outfielder was scheduled to play Tuesday against 
Los Angeles, but aggravated the injury while shagging fly balls 
before the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``I took my glove and tried to throw that thing through that  
wall out there in right field, because I knew this was a setback,'' 
Gwynn said. ``I knew it was worse than just being tight. I've never 
had anything linger this long, especially after doing all the rehab 
that they've asked me to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gwynn originally hurt the calf on May 21 against Cincinnati  
while running to first base. 
</P>
<P>
	``People thought it was my Achilles again, but I knew it was my  
calf,'' said Gwynn, who has been plagued by Achilles' problems in 
recent years. ``There were days that it felt really good and other 
days where it was tight as a drum.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This is the seventh time Gwynn has been on the DL in his 18-year  
career. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know when I'll come off, but when I do, I hope to be  
100 percent and not have to worry about this anymore,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Pitcher Andy Ashby, who has been on the DL with a strained lower  
back, was activated to take Gwynn's spot on the roster. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 08:40:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  France Lifts Coke Production Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- As France today lifted its ban on  
production of Coca-Cola, the world's largest soft-drink company was 
taking longer than expected to resume operations at two Belgian 
plants that were shut following reports of illnesses among children 
who drank its products. 
</P>
<P>
	The French finance minister, Dominique Strauss-Kahn, said today  
that a ban on canned Coca-Cola drinks produced at the northern town 
of Dunkirk was lifted on a recommendation by the government agency 
charged with food security. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of people who drank from cans produced in Dunkirk had  
reported illnesses in the past two weeks. Rat poison was detected 
on the outside of one can, but the exact cause of the illnesses was 
not detected, said Francois Muguet, a state prosecutor. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today, it seems that the product and its packaging are safe,  
so the sales can start up again,'' Strauss-Kahn said at a news 
conference. 
</P>
<P>
	The Belgian government, which had banned imports on beverages  
produced at the Coca-Cola plant at nearby Dunkirk, has said it 
would allow sales in Belgium once France cleared the products. 
</P>
<P>
	Belgium also announced on Wednesday it is allowing Coca-Cola to  
resume production at factories in the Belgian communities of 
Antwerp and Ghent, but imposed strict sanitary conditions. Without 
determining the cause of hundreds of illnesses reported in Belgium, 
the country's top health official termed them an accident. 
</P>
<P>
	Coca-Cola had planned to resume production today. But it was  
still gearing up for a return to bottling today and the company 
said it would be a day or two more before it completed cleaning up 
the plant and conducting inspections. 
</P>
<P>
	M. Douglas Ivester, Coca-Cola Co.'s chairman, has said it would  
take about two weeks to build up full distribution. 
</P>
<P>
	``Quite honestly, we let the people of Belgium down,'' Ivester  
said Wednesday, a day after Coke purchased ads in papers throughout 
Belgium to apologize for the health scare. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our products are completely safe, both in Belgium and  
worldwide,'' Iverster said Wednesday, sipping a bottle of Coke as 
he addressed reporters in his first news conference since the 
health scare began June 9. 
</P>
<P>
	Belgium's health minister, Luc Van den Bossche, said since June  
9, there had been 249 cases of illnesses reported in Belgium by 
people who drank Coca-Cola products. 
</P>
<P>
	Ivester said Atlanta-based Coca-Cola would pay the medical bills  
of anyone who had fallen ill after drinking Coke products, although 
he denied the drinks posed any health risk. 
</P>
<P>
	But lawsuits already are in the works.  
</P>
<P>
	``We have started an initial legal complaint against Coca-Cola  
because we want to know what happened,'' said Odilon Hermans, 
director of the St. Mary School in Bornem near Antwerp. 
</P>
<P>
	Hermans said four students who drank Coke two weeks ago are  
still too sick to return to classes, suffering exhaustion and lack 
of concentration. Of the 280 students at his school, 39 became sick 
after drinking Coke products and 15 spent a night in the hospital, 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	With Coca-Cola removed from many European shelves, rival Pepsi  
said it was meeting an increased demand for its soft drinks. 
</P>
<P>
	But spokesman Jeff Brown at Pepsi's headquarters in Purchase,  
N.Y., said the company is not trying to play up Coke's problems. He 
said Pepsi issued ``a worldwide memo directing international 
managers that they're not to exploit the situation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brown said warm weather and summer sales were boosting Pepsi  
sales in addition to the temporary withdrawal of competing products 
from the world's largest soft-drink company. 
</P>
<P>
	Ivester acknowledged that Coca-Cola had been slow to respond to  
consumer concerns about the health fears that led to bans in 
Belgium and beyond on Coke and other company brands, including Diet 
Coke, Fanta and Sprite. 
</P>
<P>
	At a separate media briefing, Coke bottles lined a table as  
government officials outlined the new sanitary conditions imposed 
at the Coca-Cola plants. But the Coke bottles remained capped and 
the ministry aides drank Belgian bottled water. 
</P>
<P>
	Van den Bossche said government scientists were unable to  
establish a clear cause for the problem, but said it appeared to 
have been caused by ``an accident during production or transport'' 
that was unlikely to happen again if proper precautions for hygiene 
were maintained. 
</P>
<P>
	Coca-Cola maintains that there were two problems -- a production  
problem in Antwerp that allowed sulfur compounds to mix with the 
carbon dioxide used to make Coke products bubbly, which gave it a 
``rotten egg'' smell and taste. Creosote on wooden shipping pallets 
also gave some Antwerp-produced cans of Coke a bad smell and taste, 
Coca-Cola said. 
</P>
<P>
	``In this case, a couple of our quality control procedures broke  
down,'' Ivester said. 
</P>
<P>
	Van den Bossche, who is also Belgium's Interior minister, said  
the lifting of the production ban would have been announced Tuesday 
were it not for late word of an extortion attempt against Coke last 
month in Germany. The minister said Wednesday he now is satisfied 
there is no link between the production problems and the extortion 
report. 
</P>
<P>
	Details of the threat were not disclosed, but a European  
Coca-Cola executive, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the 
German extortion attempt was unrelated to the problems in France or 
Belgium. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0275 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 10:00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nabisco To Close Houston Bakery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Nabisco Inc. plans to close its 50-year-old  
Houston bakery late this year, idling 425 workers. 
</P>
<P>
	The bakery, near the Texas Medical Center, manufactures Nabisco  
products like Ritz and Graham crackers, Air Crisps, Cheese Nips and 
chocolate chip cookies. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at Parsipanny, N.J.-based Nabisco said today the  
action came after a company-wide review of plants showed Nabisco's 
capacity exceeded its needs and added to the cost of overall 
operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Nabisco, which said the plant's last day would be Nov. 20, said  
the factory's age makes it one of the oldest bakeries in the 
Nabisco system and that its production can be accommodated within 
other Nabisco plants. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said it would offer salaried employees a severance  
package, extended benefits and career planning services and would 
begin talks with union officials about severance benefits for 
hourly employees. 
</P>
<P>
	The company still has about 1,000 employees in Texas at sales  
offices and distribution centers in Houston, Dallas, El Paso, 
Irving, Lubbock, San Antonio and Corpus Christi. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 08:40:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
