<DOCNO> APW19990624.0288 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 02:20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Athletes Try To Turn Around Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Speckled with gold and wrapped in red, white  
and blue, more than 100 of America's Olympic heroes turned out to 
say that the games they love are more than a school for scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	Beneath a sweltering sun on the front steps of the Capitol, the  
athletes formed a portrait of what they, officials and sponsors 
hope the public sees when it thinks of the Olympics -- competition 
at its best, not corruption at its worst. 
</P>
<P>
	Wednesday was Olympic Day, a worldwide celebration to mark the  
birth of the modern Olympic movement 105 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Held annually for more than a decade, the observance took on  
added meaning this year in the wake of the million-dollar bribery 
scandal connected with the Salt Lake City Winter Games. The 
ceremony in Washington was part of the U.S. Olympic Committee's 
effort to shift the focus back to the athletes. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've had a few falters and a few stumbles,'' Sen. Ben  
Nighthorse Campbell, a Colorado Republican who was captain of the 
U.S. Olympic judo team in 1964, told more than 100 spectators. ``A 
few people gave us a black eye, but that's just a bump in the road. 
The U.S. Olympic team has done its best to reverse from that 
falter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Those on hand ranged from 76-year-old Horace Ashenfelter, a gold  
medalist in the 3,000-meter steeplechase in 1952, to Dominique 
Dawes, part of the gold-medal women's gymnastics team in 1992 when 
she was 15. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the 111 athletes who took part, 47 have won a total of 74  
gold medals. 
</P>
<P>
	``These are my heroes,'' said Herb Douglas, the 1948 long-jump  
bronze medalist. 
</P>
<P>
	Douglas, a successful business leader who started the annual  
Jesse Owens Award for athletic excellence, sat at a breakfast 
table, sharing eggs, sausage and hash browns with a group of fellow 
Olympians who counted 10 gold medals among them -- basketball's Ray 
Lumpp (1948) and track stars Harrison Dillard (four golds, 
1948-52), Charlie Jenkins (two, 1956), Madeline Manning Mims (one, 
1968) and Lindy Remigino (two, 1952). 
</P>
<P>
	They and others said it was important to remember that the  
scandal did not involve athletes, that relatively few stars made 
money from Olympic glory and that the lure of the games had nothing 
to go with personal gain. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love the Olympics,'' said Hilary Smart, a yachting gold  
medalist in 1948 who now gets around with the help of a wheelchair 
and an oxygen bottle. ``I was one of the amateur guys. I never was 
looking for money from it. Who cared?'' 
</P>
<P>
	John Naber, a quadruple gold medalist in swimming in 1976 and  
now a TV commentator, said he and his colleagues were ``ordinary 
people who accomplished extraordinary things. It is that which 
inspires others as they watch us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The head of the USOC's alumni organization, Naber urged fans and  
corporations not to allow the scandal to stop the flow of donations 
and sponsorships for the competitors. 
</P>
<P>
	``While major change is needed, it must be noted that it is the  
athletes who are paying the price for the deeds of others,'' he 
said. ``The clock continues to tick, wasting the athlete's most 
precious resource -- time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Capitol stage was limited to athletes. The only high-ranking  
officials among those donning red, white and blue windbreakers were 
there because of what they did in competition. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's great fun,'' said Anita DeFrantz, a vice president of he  
International Olympic Committee, but first a bronze medalist in 
rowing at the 1976 Games. ``I've seen some folks I've admired. It 
reminds us of what we are about.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 19:40:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Politics 2000 Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton, eyeing next year's  
Senate race in New York, will use government jets for her political 
trips to the state ``for as long as she is first lady,'' her 
spokeswoman said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Marsha Berry said the decision to continue using military  
aircraft was made on the advice of the Secret Service. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton's fund-raising committee, in the process of being  
set up, will reimburse the government for political travel, she 
said. That is already done by other campaign committees when the 
first lady travels to help candidates raise money. 
</P>
<P>
	``The strong recommendation of the Secret Service is that she  
continue to fly military aircraft for security reasons and she will 
follow their recommendations,'' Berry said. 
</P>
<P>
	New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, a prospective GOP challenger  
for the Senate seat being vacated next year by Democrat Daniel 
Patrick Moynihan, said only that he was unfamiliar with federal 
campaign finance rules. ``I think she should follow whatever the 
rules and the laws are,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton is expected to announce creation of an exploratory  
committee either late this month or early in July. It would be able 
to raise and spend money for a possible Senate race. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Democratic Party's campaign committees are  
working together to organize early in six states that will play a 
major role in the outcome of presidential, congressional and state 
legislative elections in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Democratic National Committee chairman Joe Andrew, in a meeting  
Friday of state party chairmen, is expected to announce plans to 
hire six grassroots organizers in Nevada, southern California, New 
Mexico, Michigan, Pennsylvania and New Jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	The operatives will work with local party officials to target  
key congressional races in the state and important legislative 
contests within those districts. 
</P>
<P>
	Party officials said the staff has not been hired, thus Andrew  
will not put a cost estimate on the project Friday. The national 
party will split the costs with the House and Senate campaign 
committees. Organizers should be in place by Labor Day, party 
officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- A proposal to scrap California's  
winner-take-all Republican presidential primary has cleared another 
hurdle. But it's unlikely to become law in time to affect the March 
7 primary next year. 
</P>
<P>
	The state Assembly's elections committee voted 7-0 on Thursday  
to send the proposal to the full body. But the sponsor, Sen. Ray 
Haynes, said the bill can't move fast enough to meet the national 
GOP's deadline next Thursday for changes in how states select 
presidential convention delegates. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Haynes' plan, the GOP candidate who draws the most primary  
votes statewide would no longer automatically walk away with all 
delegates. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, a victory in each of the state's 52 districts would be  
worth three delegates. An additional two dozen or so at-large 
delegates would go to the candidate with the most votes statewide. 
</P>
<P>
	Haynes said his hope was that candidates would organize earlier  
and more extensively. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush had himself a  
running mate Thursday, for 25 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	That's how long it took the Republican candidate and  
Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge to run together along the Susquehanna 
River after Bush spent the night at the state's executive mansion. 
</P>
<P>
	``A jogging mate,'' Bush said of his friend, who accompanied him  
during a two-day fund-raising swing. Pennsylvania Republicans 
consider Ridge a potential running mate for Bush in the political 
sense. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 300 people greeted the governors later in the morning  
at a $1,000-a-plate breakfast, and a similar crowd paid the same 
for lunch with Bush in Pittsburgh. In all, Bush raised some $1.3 
million in the state. 
</P>
<P>
	Later in Detroit, Bush visited Mexicantown, a mainly Hispanic  
neighborhood where he showcased his bilingual abilities. 
</P>
<P>
	Maria Elena Rodriguez, president of the Mexicantown Community  
Development Corporation, said the visit demonstrated the rising 
political power of Hispanics. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's fully aware of the fact that demographics are changing in  
this country,'' she said. ``That he has come here is significant 
because he knows we're on the way up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Associated Press writers Ron Fournier, Marc  
Humbert, Peter Durantine and Joseph Altman Jr. contributed to this 
report. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
