<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 09:00:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NASA Launches Ultraviolet Telescope </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- NASA today launched an ultraviolet  
telescope that will help astronomers better understand what the 
universe was like moments after creation. 
</P>
<P>
	The Far Ultraviolet Spectroscopic Explorer, better known as  
Fuse, took off aboard an unmanned Delta rocket. Its destination: a 
480-mile-high orbit from which it will peer into the corners of the 
Milky Way galaxy and beyond. 
</P>
<P>
	Fuse will spend at least three years measuring the abundance of  
deuterium, also known as heavy hydrogen, which was created along 
with the rest of the universe in the so-called Big Bang 12 billion 
or more years ago. Every day, deuterium is being consumed by stars 
and converted into helium. 
</P>
<P>
	By determining how much deuterium still exists and how much is  
regularly destroyed, astronomers can delve back in time and try to 
figure out the original makeup of the universe. 
</P>
<P>
	``Deuterium is a cosmic fossil. I think that's perhaps the best  
way I can describe it,'' said Warren Moos, the lead scientist for 
the project at Johns Hopkins University. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we knew the primordial abundance of deuterium, if we knew  
that, then we could figure out the average abundance of ordinary 
nuclear matter ... the ordinary matter that makes up oceans, that 
makes up people, that makes up stars.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The telescope's observations, expected to begin in about three  
months, also should help explain how stars and galaxies evolve and 
how the gas between galaxies changes over time. 
</P>
<P>
	Fuse will expand on ultraviolet observations by NASA's  
Copernicus observatory, launched in 1972, as well as the Hubble 
Space Telescope and small instruments occasionally flown on the 
space shuttle. 
</P>
<P>
	The $214 million mission will be operated entirely by Johns  
Hopkins, which also designed and built the 18-foot, 3,000-pound 
telescope for the National Aeronautics and Space Administration. 
It's the most involved a university has ever been in a NASA 
mission. 
</P>
<P>
	This is a streamlined version of the original project, which was  
twice as expensive for development and was intended for a 
considerably higher orbit. The basic scientific objectives survived 
despite the cost-cutting changes. 
</P>
<P>
	Fuse is part of NASA's Origins program to study the birth and  
evolution of stars and galaxies and to search for planets that 
might hold life. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
