<DOCNO> APW19990624.0294 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 15:50:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Justice Department Watchdog Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Michael Bromwich, the Justice Department's  
inspector general who criticized the FBI crime laboratory in 1997 
for shoddy work, is resigning effective Aug. 15. 
</P>
<P>
	Bromwich, the inspector general since 1994, said in a letter  
Thursday to Attorney General Janet Reno he was leaving to ``move on 
to other challenges.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Inspector generals are independent watchdogs who investigate  
waste, fraud and abuse. 
</P>
<P>
	Bromwich wrote a scathing 500-page report in April 1997 blasting  
the world-renowned FBI lab for flawed scientific work and 
inaccurate testimony biased in favor of the prosecution in major 
cases including the Oklahoma City and World Trade Center bombings. 
</P>
<P>
	Bromwich recommended major reforms. The lab changed some of its  
procedures and won accredition last year from a national standards 
board. 
</P>
<P>
	Bromwich also investigated whether the CIA was involved in a  
crack-cocaine epidemic in the 1980s after a series of newspaper 
articles about drug traffickers who were also leaders of a CIA-run 
guerrilla army in Nicaragua. 
</P>
<P>
	His report found no evidence to support the allegations.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 07:30:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Aerosmith Cancels Woodstock Concert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROME, N.Y. (AP) -- Aerosmith, one of the main acts scheduled to  
perform at Woodstock '99, has canceled its appearance at the rock 
festival because of scheduling conflicts. 
</P>
<P>
	The band -- Steven Tyler, Joe Perry, Brad Whitford, Tom Hamilton,  
and Joey Kramer -- said Wednesday it regretted the inconvenience to 
its fans and apologized to those who already had purchased tickets 
to the concert. 
</P>
<P>
	``What it came down to was scheduling conflicts and logistical  
problems with other gigs,'' said Ilene Marder, spokesperson for 
Woodstock '99. 
</P>
<P>
	Aerosmith becomes the second headliner to cancel because of  
scheduling problems. Last month, former Yardbirds guitarist Jeff 
Beck also pulled out. 
</P>
<P>
	Woodstock '99 will be held July 23-25 at the former Griffiss Air  
Force Base. More than 120,000 tickets already have been sold, and 
promoters expect 250,000 music lovers to attend. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
