<DOCNO> APW19990624.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 05:20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Researchers Using Faster Internet2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Astronomers on opposite sides of the  
Atlantic Ocean are already using it to simulate the collision of 
neutron stars, their screens filling with a pyrotechnic shower. 
</P>
<P>
	Biologists hundreds of miles apart are using it to manipulate a  
remote control microscope and get a closer look at how proteins 
function. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors separated by a mountain range are depending on it to  
receive and move three dimensional images in a virtual clinic. 
</P>
<P>
	These scientists and researchers are already using Internet2 --  
an experimental computer network with speeds 45,000 faster than the 
best telephone modems people now use to reach the cluttered old 
Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	A collaborative effort by more than 150 universities and leading  
high tech businesses, Internet2 will revolutionize cyberspace, 
according to its developers at the Washington-based University 
Corporation for Advanced Internet Development. 
</P>
<P>
	``With Internet2, we're able to make amazing leaps and advances  
that could never happen on the Internet,'' said Greg Wood, a 
spokesman the project. 
</P>
<P>
	Wood demonstrated the new capabilities -- including a system that  
allows physicists to access and analyze huge amounts of data 
resulting from atomic collider experiments -- at the Internet 
Society's Global Summit in San Jose this week. 
</P>
<P>
	The fast network is used solely by academics and other  
professional researchers, with no way for home users to dial in. 
But its benefits should trickle down to consumers in a few years as 
ways to use the unprecedented speeds are discovered 
</P>
<P>
	Douglas Van Houweling, CEO of the project, said the initial  
research using the system ``demonstrates how international 
cooperation can advance Internet technology.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said Internet2 should duplicate the success of today's  
Internet by renewing the partnership between private companies, the 
federal government and universities that launched the Web. 
</P>
<P>
	Corporate members include Microsoft, IBM Corp., Cisco Systems  
Inc., 3Com Corp., Apple Computers, Inc., Pacific Bell, Motorola, 
Sprint and Sun Microsystems. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0297 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 17:00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Yankees Recall Ledee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- The New York Yankees search for  
left-field production resulted in yet another roster move. 
</P>
<P>
	The Yankees recalled outfielder Ricky Ledee from Triple-A  
Columbus on Thursday and sent outfielder Tony Tarasco outright to 
the International League farm team. 
</P>
<P>
	Yankees manager Joe Torre said Shane Spencer will continue as  
the starting left fielder. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's getting there I think,'' Torre said. ``Right now, it's  
our biggest priority. You'd like to do it from within because you 
know the people. If it looks like it's don't getting done, you have 
do to something else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Should the Yankees' left-field output remain stagnant -- Chad  
Curtis' .216 average is the highest among five left fielders this 
season -- New York will seek a trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Ledee, considered one of the top prospects in the Yankees' minor  
league system the past several years, went 6-for-10 with four RBIs 
in New York's World Series sweep over San Diego last October but 
hit just .200 with five RBIs in 17 games earlier this year. 
</P>
<P>
	After this season, the Yankees won't be able to send him to the  
minors without placing him on waivers. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I go down, I'll go down swinging,'' Ledee said. ``I'm going  
to try and be as aggressive as I can. Whatever happens, it 
happens.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tarasco, who could refuse the outright assignment and opt for  
free agency, said he is 95 percent sure he will report to Columbus. 
He hit .161 with 3 RBIs in 14 games with the Yankees. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
