<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jagr wins Lester Pearson Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Jaromir Jagr of the Pittsburgh Penguins won the  
the NHL's Lester Pearson award today as the league's most 
oustanding player. 
</P>
<P>
	The award is presented by the NHL Players' Association.  
</P>
<P>
	Jagr, who was to receive his third Art Ross Trophy as the  
league's leading scorer at the NHL awards ceremony later Thursday, 
was also nominated for the Hart Trophy as the league's MVP. 
</P>
<P>
	The Czech forward led the league with 44 goals and 83 assists.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's very special to me,'' said Jagr. ``It's a trophy voted on  
by the players -- the players you play against, the players you face 
every night. That's why it's special.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jagr thanked Penguins general manager Craig Patrick for putting  
``such a good team together without using a lot of money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bankrupt Penguins were awaiting to learn their fate today. A  
bankruptcy court judge was expected to choose Mario Lemieux's plan 
to save the team or one from the NHL. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
