<DOCNO> APW19990624.0305 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 07:20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Teen Abortion Bill Clears Committee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A bill making it a crime to take a pregnant  
minor to another state for an abortion without a parent's knowledge 
is nearing a House vote. 
</P>
<P>
	The House Judiciary Committee voted 16-13, along party lines, in  
favor of the bill Wednesday. A vote on the House floor could occur 
as soon as next week. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate has yet to act on a companion measure.  
</P>
<P>
	The White House threatened last year to veto similar  
legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would make it illegal for someone other than a parent,  
guardian or legal custodian to take a pregnant girl under age 18 to 
another state for an abortion if it would violate parental 
involvement laws in the child's home state. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 30 states have laws requiring that at least one parent  
give consent or be notified when their minor daughter seeks to have 
an abortion. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation would not apply if the abortion would save the  
girl's life, and neither the girl nor any parent may be prosecuted 
or sued. 
</P>
<P>
	Violators face maximum penalties of a year in jail and $100,000  
in fines, and parents whose daughters had abortions could pursue 
civil action. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans portrayed the bill as an effort to uphold the rights  
of parents to be involved in decisions by their daughters to 
undergo the surgical procedure. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters also contend it would protect vulnerable girls from  
being taken away by older men who get them pregnant and then try to 
hide it. Most teen-age pregnancies are caused by adult men, said 
Rep. Charles Canady, R-Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats argued that girls who fear turning to their parents  
because of abuse or other reasons would suffer the most. They would 
have little option but to undergo the procedure alone or to seek 
unsafe abortions, they argued. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats also said the bill was constitutionally suspect.  
</P>
<P>
	Republicans defeated a slew of Democratic amendments, including  
proposals to exempt grandparents, adult siblings, other relatives 
and religious leaders from prosecution. They also rejected an 
amendment that would have barred prosecution in cases of incest. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House opposed similar legislation last year because,  
among other reasons, it did not exempt close family members from 
civil or criminal liability. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure passed the House, though without enough votes to  
overturn a threatened White House veto. It died in the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is H.R. 1218  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 23:30:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Faces States' Rights Disputes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court, having ended its 1998-99  
term by dramatically enhancing states' political power, will 
confront two new states' rights disputes in October. 
</P>
<P>
	The justices added one of those cases Thursday in an order  
issued among scores of others the day after they began a 
three-month recess from the bench. 
</P>
<P>
	The court agreed to use a Vermont dispute to decide whether  
people can sue a state they accuse of cheating the federal 
government. 
</P>
<P>
	Vermont's lawyers contend that the Constitution and federal law  
bar such lawsuits against states. Lower courts rejected that 
argument. 
</P>
<P>
	The justices had agreed in January to decide, sometime in 2000,  
whether state employees who say they were victims of age 
discrimination can make a federal case of it. Consolidated cases 
from Florida and Alabama will yield that decision. 
</P>
<P>
	In other orders Thursday, the court:  
</P>
<P>
	--Left intact a Pakistani man's Virginia death sentence for the  
1993 fatal shootings of two CIA employees outside the spy agency's 
headquarters. Mir Aimal Kasi had challenged his arrest by FBI 
agents in Pakistan following a global manhunt. 
</P>
<P>
	--Refused to let four Arkansas cities bar people from putting  
leaflets on cars parked on city streets. 
</P>
<P>
	--Refused to require a New York public elementary school to rent  
its building to a church for Sunday worship services even though 
the school rents the building to groups using it for nonreligious 
purposes. 
</P>
<P>
	--Carried over until the term that begins in October a  
potentially important Louisiana voting-rights case. At issue is how 
vigorously the federal government can protect minorities from 
election-system changes that might impede their voting power. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Vermont case, Jonathan Stevens was a lawyer for the state  
Agency of Natural Resources' water supply division when he sued the 
agency in 1995. He alleged that it had submitted false time records 
in connection with federal grant programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Stevens sued under the federal False Claims Act, which lets  
private citizens file lawsuits on the federal government's behalf 
alleging that someone committed fraud against the government. 
Private citizens whose lawsuits are successful can collect a share 
of any damages awarded. 
</P>
<P>
	Vermont officials asked a federal judge to dismiss the lawsuit,  
saying a state is not a ``person'' who can be held liable under the 
False Claims Act. They also invoked the protection of the 
Constitution's 11th Amendment, which the court has interpreted to 
generally bar states from being sued by individuals in federal 
court. 
</P>
<P>
	In three decisions earlier this week, the court extended the  
``sovereign immunity'' states enjoy against lawsuits by businesses 
and private citizens in federal and state courts, and enhanced the 
states' power in relation to the federal government. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0307 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 17:20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Orioles To Play Exhibition After All </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- The Baltimore Orioles will play their scheduled  
exhibition game against Triple-A Rochester on Monday, after all. 
</P>
<P>
	The players thought the game was canceled because they gave up  
an off day on May 3 to play Cuba. But the Orioles announced 
Thursday that Baltimore and its Triple-A farm team will play a 
seven-inning exhibition at Frontier Field in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are very pleased to be able to put this misunderstanding  
behind us, and we are excited about our traditional visit to 
Rochester,'' general manager Frank Wren said. ``When we met with 
our players to discuss the issue, the concern was with the fact 
that the only people who would be hurt by this are the fans of 
Rochester. As a result, we were able to come to a quick 
resolution.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Albert Belle put up a sign next to his locker this week seeking  
names on a petition to boycott the game. Wren said Belle and the 
rest of the 25-man roster will make the trip. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're playing the game because it's on the schedule. The  
players were under the impression the game was going to be 
scrapped, but it seems that there was a misunderstanding somewhere 
down the line,'' outfielder B.J. Surhoff said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has nothing to do with the people of Rochester. It's giving  
up another off day when we already gave up one,'' he added. 
</P>
<P>
	Off days are a rarity for major leaguers, who play 162 games  
over 183 days. The Orioles had only three scheduled in May and just 
four in June, and will end up losing two of them. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think there's any major league team in the world that  
wants to play exhibition games,'' manager Ray Miller said. ``It's a 
pretty brutal schedule, but these guys have been great.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Playing seven innings was a compromise, but a wise decision for  
everyone involved, Surhoff said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It doesn't make any sense to play nine. By the seventh inning  
most of the starters are out of the game anyway,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wren said the Orioles will not play any in-season exhibition  
games next year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
