<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stojko To Try for Fourth World Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Elvis Stojko, saying he has yet to reach his  
potential, will try for a fourth world figure skating championship. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to keep pushing myself as an athlete,'' Stojko said  
Thursday in announcing his rejection of offers to turn pro and his 
intention to continue on the top Olympic-eligible International 
Skating Union scene. ``I still believe I have a lot more to give on 
the amateur circuit. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe that in that realm it's much easier for me to push  
the envelope and show what I have.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stojko, 27, said that watching teens win the last two world  
titles hasn't discouraged him. Age is not a factor, he said. He can 
still be a contender. 
</P>
<P>
	The five-time Canadian champion won the world title in 1994,  
1995 and 1997, and Olympic silver in 1994 and 1998. He was fourth 
at the 1999 worlds, while struggling through that season 
recuperating from the groin and abdominal injuries that ruined his 
bid for Olympic gold at Nagano. He did not want to go out on that 
note. 
</P>
<P>
	``The last number of years, it's been difficult with the  
injuries,'' he said. ``I didn't feel I was given a fair shot for 
myself. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you're trying to deal with something during the season,  
you're not going full out. Now that I'm healed and 100 percent, 
I've got a clean slate and a good shot at it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Would he still be around in 2002 to try again for the elusive  
Olympic gold medal? 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe,'' he replied. ``I still want to take it year by year. I  
don't know if I'll be around for 2002, but it'd be kind of a nice 
thing to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His first competition will be Skate America in Colorado Springs,  
Colo., Oct. 28-31. Stojko will also compete in the Skate Canada 
meet in Saint John, New Brunswick on Nov. 4-7, and in the Canadian 
championships in Calgary on Jan. 26-30, which will be the qualifier 
for the Four Continents meet in Osaka, Japan, and the world 
championships in Brisbane, Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to feel what it's like to land harder jumps, to feel  
what it's like to be effortlessly skating, to feel what it's like 
to have that mastered and put it down at a world championship when 
every eye is watching you across the planet,'' Stojko said. 
``That's a thrill to me. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's something I don't want to give up yet.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
