<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> CompUSA To Cut up to 1,500 Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- The personal computer retailer CompUSA Inc. plans  
to cut 1,000 to 1,500 jobs, or up to 7 percent its work force, as 
part of an overhaul designed to boost profitability. 
</P>
<P>
	CompUSA, which operates 211 stores in 79 cities, also said in  
announcing its plans today that it will close four stores soon and 
was considering closing as many as 10 others. It currently employs 
about 21,000 people. 
</P>
<P>
	The moves result from an evaluation of its business and will  
result in ``fundamentally redefining CompUSA's entire business 
concept,'' said James F. Halpin, president and chief executive. 
</P>
<P>
	The changes, the company hopes, will reduce its dependence on  
low-margin personal computers. 
</P>
<P>
	The company announced plans to offer in-store centers where  
customers can choose specific build-to-order products. In addition, 
it will focus on promoting the sales of hand-held technology such 
as personal digital assistants and console-based computer 
entertainment games from Sony, Nintendo and Sega. 
</P>
<P>
	The stores will also delve into selling equipment and software  
for other entertainment formats, like DVD movies, MP3 Internet 
music distribution technology, as well as digital cameras and 
camcorders. 
</P>
<P>
	In its direct sales to business, government and educational  
customers, CompUSA plans to consolidate distribution and 
fulfillment at one site. Currently, it ships from stores and a 
distribution center in Grapevine, Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	The company estimated it will have onetime charges of $40  
million to $50 million as a result of these initiatives. It expects 
to record the charge in the fourth quarter ending June 26 and the 
first two quarters of fiscal year 2000. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
