<HEADLINE> More Charges in School Shooting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) -- A man already accused of selling a handgun  
that two teen-agers used in the Columbine High School massacre has 
been charged with possession of a sawed-off shotgun. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Manes, 22, sat quietly Wednesday as Jefferson County  
prosecutors laid out the second charge against him. Manes 
previously was charged with selling a TEC-DC9 9mm pistol that Eric 
Harris and Dylan Klebold used in the April 20 rampage. Harris and 
Klebold killed 12 students and a teacher before killing themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest charge is a felony that carries up to three years in  
prison upon conviction. The TEC-9 charge carries a sentence of up 
to six years, but could go as high as 12 years if a judge finds 
extraordinary circumstances. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense lawyer Bob Ransome said Manes is being made a scapegoat.  
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutor Steve Jensen said his office intends to hold Manes  
accountable. 
</P>
<P>
	``Making an example of people will hopefully prevent other  
wrongdoing,'' he said. ``If he claims we're making an example of 
him, I guess I plead guilty.'' 
</P>
<P>
	District Court Judge Francis Jackson ordered Manes to return to  
court Aug. 18 to enter a plea. He remains free on $15,000 bond. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
