<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 02:30:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Astros Manager Recovers at Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Larry Dierker's recollection of his last trip to  
the Astrodome is cloudy. 
</P>
<P>
	But Dierker's trademark Hawaiian shirt offered a clue Wednesday  
of the mental state that doctors want the Houston Astros manager to 
have for the next few months following brain surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have to be quiet for a few weeks and not do very much,''  
Dierker said. 
</P>
<P>
	He donned a baseball cap to cover his shaved head as he checked  
out of Methodist Hospital, eight days after undergoing the 
operation a day after suffering a grand mal seizure. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel good, and I'm going to be fine,'' said Dierker, smiling  
and joking. 
</P>
<P>
	Dierker, 52, is forbidden from driving for six months and must  
take anticonvulsant medication indefinitely. 
</P>
<P>
	The surgeon who performed the operation to remove a tangled mass  
of blood vessels from the front of Dierker's brain said he expected 
the manager to make a full recovery and return to the dugout after 
next month's All-Star break. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's coming along fine, but at this point it's hard to say how  
much more time he's going to need,'' Dr. Rob Parrish said. ``He's 
going to continue the medication, and we'll continue to evaluate 
how he responds.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dierker collapsed in the dugout June 13 with the grand mal  
seizure. He underwent 5 1/2 hours of surgery June 15 to remove the 
tangled vessels that caused the seizure. 
</P>
<P>
	``To be honest, I don't know what happened'' at the game,  
Dierker said. ``I heard a lot of people talking, but I don't 
remember much more than that. It was all like a blur. From the time 
I woke up and recovered from the sedatives, I have felt lucid and I 
have had my coordination and balance. I have been very much amazed 
at that. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know how it could have been a lot worse, so I feel very  
fortunate that the malformation wasn't in an area that was as 
complex as it could have been,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dierker suffered from arteriovenous malformation, a condition in  
which people are born with malformed, sometimes tangled, arteries 
or veins in the brain. Over time, the vessels can dilate, 
pressuring tissue or even bursting and bleeding into the brain. 
</P>
<P>
	After the surgery, an angiogram showed Dierker no longer had any  
of the clustered blood vessels. 
</P>
<P>
	He was the third member of the Astros staff to become ill this  
season. First-base coach Jose Cruz left the team May 10 because of 
an irregular heartbeat, and hitting coach Tom McCraw left six days 
later for prostate cancer treatment. Cruz has returned to the team. 
</P>
<P>
	Dierker said he continued to keep track of the game through his  
ordeal and now will convalesce at home. 
</P>
<P>
	``I haven't had the problem of getting emotionally stressed  
watching on television as I have sitting in the dugout,'' he said, 
joined by his wife Judy and Parrish at a news conference. ``I 
haven't had a problem relinquishing control or power; it's probably 
a function of my managerial style.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0322 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 15:30:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fewer People Watching NBA Finals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Fewer people are watching the NBA Finals this year and it's not  
just because Michael Jordan is gone. Some games have been too 
painful to watch. 
</P>
<P>
	Sure, Jordan's retirement may be the major reason that this  
year's audience has plummeted from 1998's record-setting TV 
ratings. 
</P>
<P>
	But the play these days isn't at the same level it was a decade  
or so ago with Larry and Magic. To call today's games ``sloppy'' 
would be a major understatement. 
</P>
<P>
	The lack of scoring and ugly play prompted NBA commissioner  
David Stern to assemble a 16-member committee to draft 
recommendations for making the game more attractive. 
</P>
<P>
	One of those on the task force is NBC analyst Doug Collins, a  
former NBA player and coach. His recommendation is simple: Stop the 
NBA from becoming the WWF. 
</P>
<P>
	The league needs less wrestling, holding and pushing -- and more  
passing, cutting and team play. 
</P>
<P>
	``The game has gotten too rough and it's been a gradual erosion,  
not something that happened overnight,'' Collins said Wednesday, a 
day after the committee met in New York. ``There's been more 
clutching and grabbing, and strength has eroded skill. ... The game 
has become stagnant.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Turner analyst Hubie Brown, another committee member, said the  
overly physical play was first on the agenda. But he doesn't 
believe that you can pinpoint the drop in viewers to Jordan or the 
rough play. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe the people just don't like the two teams in the  
finals,'' he said. ``Everybody's all bent out of shape, but our TV 
ratings were up this year and NBC's were close.'' 
</P>
<P>
	True, but those numbers came during a 50-game abbreviated  
regular season, where each game had added meaning. And there were 
more teams in the playoff hunt down the stretch, which translated 
to more fan interest throughout the country. 
</P>
<P>
	The playoffs were always when Jordan excelled -- not just on the  
court, but in luring viewers as well. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1998 NBA Finals recorded an all-time high 18.7 series  
rating. This year's four-game average is an 11.3. 
</P>
<P>
	The ratings for all four games in the finals have been  
considerably lower than last year. Game 1 fell 35 percent, Game 2 
had a 42 percent drop, Game 3 slipped 25 percent and Wednesday 
night's game sank 37 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Tim Duncan and the San Antonio Spurs just don't have the same  
appeal as Jordan and the Bulls. Even having the Knicks in the 
finals to draw the massive New York market is overrated. 
</P>
<P>
	``The key subtraction is Jordan,'' said Turner's Marv Albert.  
``Once you're in the playoffs, you're attracting the more casual 
fan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And Jordan did that better than anyone. Through the first three  
games, the New York market attracted 1.4 million viewers while 1.44 
million viewers watched in the Chicago market last year. 
</P>
<P>
	It's the rest of the country that just isn't watching.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *EQUALITY:* John McEnroe has changed his mind. Now he's all for  
women and men receiving equal prize money. 
</P>
<P>
	Currently, the U.S. Open is the only major tennis tournament  
that gives women the same prize money as the men. At the Australian 
Open, women get 94 percent, and at the French Open, it's 90 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	But McEnroe said it's just a matter of time before the women are  
given the same amount in the other three tournaments. 
</P>
<P>
	``The old argument is that we play five sets and they play  
three, but the bottom line is no one cares,'' said McEnroe, an 
analyst for NBC's Wimbledon coverage, which begins Saturday. ``The 
men should accept the deal before women start making more money 
than the men. Within the next six months or so, you're going to see 
it (equal money) happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chris Evert disagrees about the timing, mainly because Europe is  
much further behind the United States in women's equality. 
</P>
<P>
	``Wimbledon is lagging behind,'' she said. ``They pay women 79  
percent of what men make now. We haven't made any strides in the 
last five or six years.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *TUBE BITS:* ESPN, along with ABC, will televise the X Games  
beginning Sunday from San Francisco. ... Fox airs the NFL Europe 
title game Sunday at 1:30 p.m. EDT with Lawrence Phillips and the 
Barcelona Dragons against the Frankfurt Galaxy. ... ESPN's ``ESPY 
Awards'' will move to Las Vegas next year. ... ESPN hockey analyst 
Bill Clement wasn't certain Brett Hull's skate was in the crease in 
Game 6 of the Stanley Cup finals when he first saw the game-winning 
goal for Dallas over Buffalo, but he wouldn't have said anything 
even if he was sure. ``We absolutely have to follow the celebration 
on the ice,'' he said. ``There was zero point in me mentioning I 
saw a skate in the crease. It was a non-issue until someone else 
from either side said something about it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
