<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Arco, BP Amoco Defend Merger Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two corporations planning a merger that would  
create the world's second-largest oil company spent hours Thursday 
trying to assure senators the deal would benefit consumers and 
encourage competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Atlantic Richfield Co. Chairman Mike Bowlin told a Senate  
committee that the $25.6 billion stock deal that that would marry 
his company with BP Amoco would create a company that would invest 
in the latest and best technology and use it to develop new energy 
resources. 
</P>
<P>
	Even after hearing from Bowlin and Richard Olver, a BP Amoco  
group managing director, however, members of the Senate Energy and 
Natural Resources Committee questioned them closely on whether the 
merger would reduce competition and increase prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Committee Chairman Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska, said he didn't  
oppose the deal, but would look it over carefully. 
</P>
<P>
	Residents of his state are particularly concerned, he said,  
because the combined company would control 70 percent of oil and 
gas production from Alaska's North Slope and 72 percent of the 
Trans-Alaska Pipeline. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our obligation to future Alaskans is to ensure that this  
consolidation does not stifle competition for Alaskan oil and gas 
resources,'' he said. Under the deal, ``BP will become the largest 
non-governmental oil producer in the world. It will produce close 
to 20 percent of U.S. domestic crude oil and control 18.4 percent 
of West Coast gasoline markets and 14.2 percent of East Coast 
markets.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The rivalry between Arco and BP Amoco has been an important  
part of the competition that has served Alaska and the country 
well,'' Drue Pearce, president of the Alaska Senate, told the 
committee. ``With that rivalry possibly coming to an end, 
competition at virtually every phase is threatened.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The companies expect the merger to save them about $1 billion a  
year. When it was announced April 1, it was the eighth proposed 
merger of the previous past six months in an industry shaken by 
more than a year of plummeting oil prices and increasing demands 
for cleaner fuel. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposed merger between Exxon and Mobil, which would create  
the world's largest oil company, is awaiting regulatory approval. 
</P>
<P>
	Atlantic Richfield and BP Amoco say about the expect to  
eliminate about 2,000 jobs from a combined work force of 115,000, 
mainly in the United States outside Alaska. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Trade Commission, the state of Alaska and several  
other states are analyzing the deal's possible impact. 
</P>
<P>
	One committee member said he remained skeptical. ``All the signs  
are very, very ominous,'' Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., said. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
