<DOCNO> APW19990624.0329 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 14:10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Orders for Durable Goods Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Orders for big-ticket manufactured goods -- led  
by gains in aircraft and autos -- climbed 1.4 percent in May, a sign 
that the nation's battered manufacturing sector could be headed for 
a revival. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commerce Department said Thursday that orders for durable  
goods -- items expected to last at least three years -- increased 
$2.8 billion last month to a seasonally adjusted $197.6 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	May's increase was the ninth in the last 12 months and followed  
a steep 2.3 percent decline in April, the government said. Analysts 
expected May's turnaround, correctly predicting a rebound in orders 
for transportation products, which had suffered a sharp drop in 
April. 
</P>
<P>
	``The report indicates that manufacturing is going through a  
slow revival, but a revival nonetheless,'' said Mark Zandi, an 
economist with Regional Financial Associates. ``When you look at 
orders over a broader period, it shows a continuing modest 
improvement, indicating that manufacturers are past the worst of 
their problems.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Orders for transportation equipment rose a strong 9.5 percent in  
May, following a 12.6 percent decline in April. The transportation 
sector is often volatile from month to month because it includes 
such big ticket purchases as airplanes. 
</P>
<P>
	A big increase in orders for aircraft and airplane parts led the  
rebound in transportation orders, the Commerce Department said. 
U.S. automakers said they are enjoying record sales for cars and 
light trucks for the year ending May 31. 
</P>
<P>
	``U.S. consumers are not through shopping yet,'' said economist  
Paul Taylor with the National Automobile Dealers Association. ``A 
refinancing boom, which is coming to an end, has left many 
household budgets in better shape and that is giving people the 
room to go out and buy autos to fill up their two-car garages,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Excluding the strength in transportation, overall orders for  
durable goods would have fallen 0.7 percent in May, the biggest 
decline since a 2.7 drop in October 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Shipments of big-ticket durable goods, a good sign of current  
demand, increased 1 percent in May. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial markets have grown increasingly nervous in recent  
weeks that the Federal Reserve will begin raising interest rates at 
their meeting next week to slow growth and keep inflation under 
control. The Dow Jones industrial average closed at 10,534.83 on 
Thursday, down 132.03 for the fourth straight decline for the 
blue-chip index. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the nation's good economic health, American  
manufacturers have been battered by a global financial crisis that 
has cut sharply into their overseas sales, opened them up to 
stiffer competition from cheaper imports and led to a loss of 
453,000 jobs in the last 14 months. 
</P>
<P>
	One U.S. industry that has suffered the most from the global  
turmoil has been steel. But orders for primary metals, the category 
that includes steel, rose by 0.7 percent in May following a 1.4 
percent gain April, offering a glimmer of hope that the worst may 
be over. 
</P>
<P>
	However, steel coming into the United States from other  
countries continued to rise, according to preliminary figures 
contained in a second Commerce Department report released Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan, Brazil and other foreign countries shipped 3 million  
metric tons of steel to the United States in May. That's 30 percent 
higher than the final 2.3 million figure for April. Still, total 
shipments were 18 percent below November's levels. 
</P>
<P>
	In a blow to the U.S. steel industry, the Senate earlier this  
week blocked a bill that would have limited the amount of 
foreign-made steel sent to the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Even with the 1.4 percent rise in orders for big-ticket  
manufactured goods, orders for industrial machinery, which includes 
computers and office equipment, fell 2.5 percent in May after a big 
3.6 percent gain in April. Orders for electronic and other 
electrical equipment, including semiconductors, dropped 1.5 percent 
in May after a 0.6 percent April increase. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some may point to that as a sign of slowing in high-tech as  
Y2K nears. However, that also happened in February and then 
rebounded,'' said First Union economist David Orr. 
</P>
<P>
	In a third report, the Labor Department said the number of  
Americans filing new claims for unemployment benefits rose 3,000 to 
302,000 last week. However, economists said the job market remains 
healthy. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
