<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 15:30:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Spurs' Coach Has Style All His Own </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- During the early 1970s, San Antonio Spurs coach  
Gregg Popovich was in the Air Force, based in Eastern Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Since there were no American air bases behind the Iron Curtain  
at the time, one can only guess exactly what Pop was doing over 
there. 
</P>
<P>
	He could tell us, but then he'd have to kill us.  
</P>
<P>
	``In the military, he got a chance to do a lot of Soviet studies  
and special intelligence stuff,'' David Robinson said. ``That's 
part of what makes him such an interesting person.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There is a style to Popovich that's all his own, a manner that's  
equal parts Jerry Sloan, K.C. Jones and Pat Riley. 
</P>
<P>
	His brand of humor is similar to Sloan's, a self-depreciating,  
folksy blend of crudeness and blandness. 
</P>
<P>
	His style of coaching is similar to that of Jones, the former  
Boston Celtics coach who had a penchant for letting his players 
talk things out in the huddle rather than talking down to them. 
</P>
<P>
	His motivational methods are so far from the norm that they can  
only be compared to Riley's. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once in a while he'll do something kind of wacko just to shake  
us up a little,'' Steve Kerr said, relating a story about a game 
earlier this year in which San Antonio blew a 20-point 
fourth-quarter lead only to win at the buzzer on a shot by Sean 
Elliott. 
</P>
<P>
	``He came into the locker room and stripped down,'' Kerr said,  
``took all his clothes off and said `I've had it. I can't deal with 
you guys anymore.' We were all just kind of like, `Oh my God, the 
guy's naked.' We're supposed to be the ones naked, not the coach.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Popovich has been bared to the world during these NBA finals,  
handling himself splendidly off the court and on it, quietly making 
the needed adjustments to combat New York's advantage in backcourt 
scoring, attacking the Knicks' weak spots and rectifying his team's 
troubles in the rebounding department. 
</P>
<P>
	Since arriving in New York following Game 2, he has played the  
part of the happy tourist, smiling his way through mandatory 
interview sessions and exchanging lightheated barbs with people on 
the street who recognize his increasingly familiar face. 
</P>
<P>
	His haircut says military man. His manner is all civilian.  
</P>
<P>
	``Whenever I get asked about the military, I always smile. If  
you talk to anybody at the academy when I was there and you started 
talking about me as a military man, there would be guffaws 
everywhere. I wasn't great,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Nobody is laughing now, though, when Popovich's name is brought  
up among the best coaches and executives in the league. 
</P>
<P>
	Popovich is one of the few men in the NBA who is both general  
manager and coach, a dual role he has held since taking over the 
coaching duties from Bob Hill in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	His luckiest accomplishment was winning the draft lottery that  
brought the Spurs Tim Duncan in the 1997 draft, but Popovich has 
made some wise decisions, too. This season, he brought in Steve 
Kerr, Jerome Kersey and Mario Elie to give the team a dose of 
veteran leadership and toughness. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is new territory for me. I don't know what the hell I'm  
doing here,'' Popovich said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sure thing, Pop. Just like they taught you in the military.  
Admit nothing. Deny everything. Play dumb. Be smart. 
</P>
<P>
	One more win, and the only NBA coach who is fluent in Russian  
will become a champion -- and a little less of a mystery. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
