<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 02:30:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-AP Newsman Lee Linder Dead at 77 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Lee Linder covered post-World War II  
celebrations, the riot at Kent State and the aftermath of the Three 
Mile Island nuclear disaster. 
</P>
<P>
	He was bunker-side at the bombing of the radical MOVE compound  
in 1985 and dictated the obituary of one of Philadelphia's most 
well-known mayors, Frank Rizzo, from an Atlantic City phone booth 
while on vacation in 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	Linder earned his reputation as a brash, tireless reporter in a  
career that spanned a half century of covering news for The 
Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	He died Wednesday following a lengthy battle with cancer. He was  
77. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whenever there was a breaking story, he was the first to come  
to mind. He couldn't be exhausted, even well into his 60s,'' said 
George Zucker, former AP chief of bureau for Pennsylvania. 
</P>
<P>
	``And Lee never complained about anything -- except for one time  
when he was accepting a compliment from me, he said: 'I'm the most 
overpraised man in this bureau and also the most underpaid,''' 
Zucker said. 
</P>
<P>
	The slight but commanding man was well-known among  
Philadelphia's politicians. One time when Rizzo called a press 
conference, he looked out over the crowd of reporters and said: ``I 
guess this must be an important press conference. Lee Linder of The 
Associated Press is here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``If the AP was at any event, you could almost bank on it being  
Lee Linder,'' said Joseph A. Slobodzian, a Philadelphia Inquirer 
reporter for the past 17 years. ``He was AP's public face in 
Philadelphia.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Linder's news sources were legendary, earning him exclusives  
that won national and international display. They included a 1966 
exclusive interview with atomic spy Harry Gold, who evaded other 
reporters upon his prison release and met with Linder at a motel. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1967, he got a Glassboro, N.J., accountant to turn his home  
into a temporary AP bureau when President Lyndon Johnson and Soviet 
Premier Alexei Kosygin organized an impromptu summit. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was sent out to scout the home of the college president,  
Hollybush, and lucked out at the home of an accountant that lived 
across the street. He turned over his home to AP. ... For the next 
24 hours, that was the focus of the world,'' Linder said when he 
retired in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Linder's coverage of tropical storm Agnes in 1972 and a 12-part  
retrospective the following year earned him the Philadelphia Press 
Association award for the best news story. In 1986, Linder was the 
first recipient of the AP News Staffer of the Year award of the 
Pennsylvania Associated Press Managing Editors. 
</P>
<P>
	Linder was born in Philadelphia and graduated in 1943 from  
Temple University, where he was editor of the campus newspaper. 
Before joining the AP in 1945, Linder worked for International News 
Service in Philadelphia and Detroit, United Press in Cleveland and 
the Washington Star. 
</P>
<P>
	Linder also was active in many Jewish organizations.  
</P>
<P>
	He is survived by his wife, Thelma Elster, two daughters and six  
grandchildren. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0332 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 18:00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clapton Auctions Guitars for Charity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Eric Clapton parted with 100 stringed beauties  
Thursday, including a beloved Fender guitar he called ``Brownie'' 
that went for a record $497,500 at a charity auction. 
</P>
<P>
	In all, the Christie's sale generated $5 million for a Caribbean  
drug and alcohol clinic the rocker founded in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Clapton used ``Brownie,'' a 1956 sunburst Fender, to record his  
hit ``Layla.'' He played the guitar in other recording sessions and 
in concert. The amount paid for it -- by an unidentified telephone 
bidder -- surpassed the previous record paid at auction for a guitar 
-- $320,000 for one owned by Jimi Hendrix. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't believe it. I am totally overwhelmed,'' Clapton said  
in a statement released by Christie's after the sale. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he wanted to ``say thank you on behalf of all the  
patients who will get free treatment as a result of this sale.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clapton did not attend the auction.  
</P>
<P>
	Actor Michael J. Fox, bidding by telephone, bought a 1949  
Gibson-125 for $36,800 and a circa 1930s National Duolian for 
$42,500. Other buyers included Michael Malone, a Seattle music 
executive, and the Hard Rock Hotel in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	Most other buyers were not identified.  
</P>
<P>
	In addition to ``Brownie,'' Clapton sold a 1954 Fender  
Stratocaster for $211,500 and a 1974 Martin 000-28 for $173,000. 
Both were widely used for recording and stage work as Clapton rose 
to stardom during the 1970s. 
</P>
<P>
	A rare, 1958 Gibson Explorer with a solid-body design went for  
$134,500 and a red, 1991 Gibson Firebird given to Clapton by a fan 
went for $39,100. 
</P>
<P>
	A Christie's spokeswoman would not comment on reports that  
Clapton may have intended to secretly bid on at least one of his 
guitars after having a change of heart about parting with it. None 
of the buyers were identified by the auction house. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
