<DOCNO> APW19990624.0333 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 15:20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Congress Puts Off Y2K Bill Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congressional action on legislation to reduce  
Y2K-related lawsuits was put off Thursday so Congress and the White 
House could try a final time to resolve their differences and avoid 
a presidential veto. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right before the meltdown both sides pulled back,'' said Sen.  
Ron Wyden, D-Ore. House and Senate negotiators decided to wait 
until Tuesday before approving the final draft of the Y2K bill. 
</P>
<P>
	That decision came after lawmakers from both parties complained  
that the White House, while saying it wants a bill to stop 
frivolous lawsuits, had failed to offer ideas on what it could 
accept. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very unhappy,'' said Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., author of  
the Senate Y2K bill with Wyden and Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain said he had had heard nothing from the White House until  
Chief of Staff John Podesta called him 15 minutes before Thursday's 
House-Senate meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never seen such obdurate and non-communicative  
behavior,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dodd said that in the 10 days since the Senate passed its  
version, ``I haven't heard any specific objections.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Added Wyden: ``The White House has been waltzing around when  
they could have been working with us productively.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Before adjourning until Tuesday, the negotiators did agree to  
accept, with small changes, the Senate version, which is more 
moderate than the House bill and somewhat more acceptable to the 
White House. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure seeks to avoid a flood of economy-crippling lawsuits  
related to disruptions caused by the year 2000 computer bug by 
giving companies 90 days to fix computers before lawsuits can be 
filed and encouraging mediation. 
</P>
<P>
	It caps punitive damages for small businesses. The bill also  
tries to protect companies from predatory lawsuits by stating that 
in most cases a defendant will be held liable only for the share of 
damages it causes. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House, along with trial lawyer and consumer groups,  
says even the Senate bill goes too far in undermining the rights of 
people with legitimate grievances. 
</P>
<P>
	Podesta, in a letter Thursday to House Speaker Dennis Hastert,  
R-Ill., repeated the administration's veto threat but urged 
discussions. ``Rather than going down this destructive path, we 
should work together to find a bipartisan solution,'' Podesta 
wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	Larry Stein, congressional liaison for the White House, attended  
the meeting to tell the lawmakers that ``we stand ready to try to 
work things out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans went into Thursday's conference with the intention  
of agreeing on the Senate bill, sending it back to the House and 
Senate for quick approval and handing it to the president. 
</P>
<P>
	That would have forced him to make a decision about vetoing a  
bill keenly sought by the high tech industry, which has supported 
his presidency and is close to Vice President Al Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	Even with the delay, McCain said the Senate bill already was a  
``tremendous retreat'' from the stronger House-passed measure and 
there was little negotiating room. ``I do not think we should 
further emasculate this legislation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I want desperately to work something out with the  
administration,'' said Rep. Tom Davis, R-Va., chief sponsor of the 
House bill. ``But I am not going to surrender principle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The negotiators did agree to amend language in the Senate bill  
that would have protected people from mortgage foreclosures 
resulting from Y2K problems. 
</P>
<P>
	The banking industry and agencies such as the Federal Reserve  
Board said the provision, inserted by bill opponent Sen. Ernest 
Hollings, D-S.C., was too broadly written and could affect the 
soundness of the banking system. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0334 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 15:00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NiSource Pursues Columbia Energy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HERNDON, Va. (AP) -- In a bid to become one of the nation's  
largest gas companies, NiSource Inc. plans to pursue a $5.7 billion 
hostile takeover of Columbia Energy Group. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indiana-based utility company said Thursday that it plans to  
launch its tender offer on Friday. NiSource also said it will 
nominate a slate of directors to Columbia's board at Columbia's 
next annual meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe that your stockholders have lost faith in your  
Board's willingness to act in their best interests,'' NiSource 
chairman and chief executive Gary Neale said in a letter to Oliver 
G. Richard III, chairman and chief executive of Columbia Energy, 
which is based in Herndon. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbia's board has repeatedly rebuffed NiSource's attempts to  
purchase the natural gas company. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposed buyout would make NiSource, the parent company of  
Northern Indiana Public Service Co. and Bay State Gas Co. in 
Massachusetts, one of the nation's biggest natural gas companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbia Energy said it would review the bid, and urged its  
shareholders to take no action on the offer until it makes its 
recommendation, expected within 10 business days. 
</P>
<P>
	NiSource, based in Merrillville, Ind., disclosed earlier this  
month that it had made an unsolicited buyout offer of $68 a share 
for Columbia Energy, but that Columbia Energy had refused to 
schedule merger talks. 
</P>
<P>
	Two weeks ago, Columbia's board unanimously rejected the buyout,  
saying the company isn't for sale. 
</P>
<P>
	But Neale said in his letter that NiSource ``will not be  
deterred by the actions of your board ... We have made it clear 
that we intend to pursue this transaction to its end.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NiSource has said it is willing to increase its offer if  
Columbia Energy's board ``agrees to cooperate with us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Columbia Energy had 1998 revenues of nearly $6.6 billion. It is  
involved in natural gas exploration, production, transmission, 
storage and distribution as well as propane sales and electric 
power generation, sales and trading. 
</P>
<P>
	In April, Columbia Energy attempted to buy Pittsburgh-based  
Consolidated Natural Gas. But Consolidated Natural Gas last month 
rejected the offer and chose to proceed with an previously-planned 
merger with Richmond, Va.-based Dominion Resources Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of NiSource fell 43 3/4 cents to close at $26.93 3/4 on the New  
York Stock Exchange, while shares of Columbia fell 18 3/4 cents to 
$63.56 1/4. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0335 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 16:10:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Mistrial Called in Reggie Lewis Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A judge declared a mistrial in the Reggie Lewis  
malpractice case Thursday after a jury deadlocked over whether a 
cardiologist's diagnosis led to the death of the Boston Celtics 
star. Two consulting physicians were cleared of wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision came after the jury, for the second day in a row,  
couldn't decide on Dr. Gilbert Mudge's responsibility. Mudge had 
treated Lewis before he dropped dead of a heart condition while 
shooting baskets in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Thayer Fremont-Smith declared the mistrial after the jury  
had deliberated about 35 hours over six days. In order to reach a 
verdict, agreement was needed among 13 of the 15 jurors, who heard 
nearly seven weeks of testimony. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis' wife, Donna Harris-Lewis, sued Mudge and the consultants,  
Drs. Mark Creager and Peter Friedman, claiming they misdiagnosed 
and mistreated her husband's heart condition. A third consultant 
settled for an undisclosed sum before trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Harris-Lewis sought at least $75 million, saying that was the  
sum Lewis would have earned if he hadn't died. 
</P>
<P>
	``I take tremendous comfort and pride in the fact that Reggie's  
reputation and legacy has emerged from this stronger than ever,'' 
she said. ``And there's no telling how much good he could have done 
if he had been treated properly and lived.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Her lawyer, Robert Harley, said he will seek a retrial.  
</P>
<P>
	Lewis collapsed during a playoff game in 1993 and was diagnosed  
with a life-threatening, potentially career-ending heart rhythm 
disturbance by a team of top doctors from New England Baptist 
Hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lewises then turned to Mudge, of Brigham and Women's  
Hospital, who examined Lewis and announced at a news conference 
that the player instead had a benign neurological condition that 
causes fainting spells. Mudge said Lewis could probably return to 
basketball. 
</P>
<P>
	Two months later, Lewis died at 27.  
</P>
<P>
	At the trial, Mudge maintained that two weeks before his death,  
Lewis admitted using cocaine. The doctor said the belated 
confession made an accurate diagnosis impossible. Lewis' widow 
bitterly denied her husband used cocaine. 
</P>
<P>
	After the verdict, Mudge refused to answer questions.  
</P>
<P>
	``We don't want to portray it any other way than the way it  
turned out,'' said his lawyer, William Dailey. ``We hope, perhaps, 
when everyone has a chance to think about the situation there may 
not be another trial.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The doctor's lawyers called several criminals to testify that  
Lewis used cocaine and marijuana. 
</P>
<P>
	Mudge also had said he privately suspected the player might have  
a serious heart condition -- and was treating him with beta blockers 
that addressed both the fainting condition and the possible cardiac 
problem. He said he told the family and the Celtics of his 
concerns, but both groups disputed that claim. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for Harris-Lewis suggested that Mudge's judgment had  
been clouded by his search for glory as the man who proved the 
other doctors wrong. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0336 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 08:40:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
