<P>
	At the trial, Mudge maintained that two weeks before his death,  
Lewis admitted using cocaine. The doctor said the belated 
confession made an accurate diagnosis impossible. Lewis' widow 
bitterly denied her husband used cocaine. 
</P>
<P>
	After the verdict, Mudge refused to answer questions.  
</P>
<P>
	``We don't want to portray it any other way than the way it  
turned out,'' said his lawyer, William Dailey. ``We hope, perhaps, 
when everyone has a chance to think about the situation there may 
not be another trial.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The doctor's lawyers called several criminals to testify that  
Lewis used cocaine and marijuana. 
</P>
<P>
	Mudge also had said he privately suspected the player might have  
a serious heart condition -- and was treating him with beta blockers 
that addressed both the fainting condition and the possible cardiac 
problem. He said he told the family and the Celtics of his 
concerns, but both groups disputed that claim. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for Harris-Lewis suggested that Mudge's judgment had  
been clouded by his search for glory as the man who proved the 
other doctors wrong. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0338 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 08:50:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fieldcrest Cannon Workers OK Union </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KANNAPOLIS, N.C. (AP) -- A textile union that has struggled for  
25 years to represent workers at six Fieldcrest Cannon plants 
claimed victory after a two-day election. 
</P>
<P>
	Workers voted, 2,270 to 2,102, to be represented by the Union of  
Needletrades Industrial and Textile Employees, but both the company 
and union challenged about 285 votes each, National Labor Relations 
Board officials said early today. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is tied up on challenges. We cannot determine the winner,''  
said NLRB election overseer Gary Stiffler. 
</P>
<P>
	He couldn't say how long it would take to officially declare a  
winner because of the potential for litigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Voting began Tuesday and ended Wednesday night.  
</P>
<P>
	``We won here,'' said UNITE organizer Mike Zucker. ``It's a  
historic victory. It's been a long time coming.'' 
</P>
<P>
	UNITE already represents 4,000 Pillowtex workers at nine plants  
in the United States and Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	Pillowtex Chairman Chuck Hansen Jr., whose company bought  
Fieldcrest Cannon after the last union vote in 1997, told about 60 
cheering employees the election provided no mandate for either 
side. He estimated as many as 500 eligible employees didn't vote. 
</P>
<P>
	Advocates for the union erupted with cheers when the vote total  
was announced. About a dozen supporters ran outside of the A.L. 
Brown High School auditorium where everyone had gathered. 
</P>
<P>
	``Thank God we won,'' said Ruth Crisco, a folder at plant No. 6  
in Concord. 
</P>
<P>
	Anti-union workers showed little emotion. Some were defiant.  
</P>
<P>
	``We ain't lost yet,'' said Thelma Honeycutt, a weaver for 47  
years at the No. 6 plant. 
</P>
<P>
	Fieldcrest Cannon workers have rejected union organizing efforts  
four times, beginning in 1974. A court ordered an election in 1997 
after the union claimed it lost a close 1991 vote because 
Fieldcrest intimidated and fired workers. The union lost the 1997 
election by 369 votes out of 4,757 cast, and the NLRB again found 
irregularities. 
</P>
<P>
	Dallas-based Pillowtex bought Fieldcrest Cannon shortly  
thereafter for $700 million, creating one of the world's largest 
makers of bed and bath linen. The top issues in this election were 
the estimated $50 million in modernization and job changes that 
have occurred since Fieldcrest was sold. UNITE said change was 
displacing workers. 
</P>
<P>
	Fieldcrest Cannon makes towels, sheets and comforters under the  
names Royal Velvet, Cannon, Touch of Class and Charisma. Pillowtex 
makes bed pillows, mattress pads, blankets and down comforters 
under the Ralph Lauren, Disney and Martha Stewart names. 
</P>
<P>
	North Carolina has 166,800 textile jobs, more than any state.  
But textile employment has declined for six decades because of 
improved technology and increased manufacturing overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	Job losses accelerated in the past year as the Asian financial  
crisis boosted imports. U.S. mills also have been moving production 
to Mexico to cut costs by taking advantage of lower wage rates. 
</P>
<P>
	North Carolina has the lowest proportion of union members in the  
country; unions represent just 4.2 percent of wage and salary 
workers. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0339 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 02:20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Golfer Webb Having Dream Season  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) -- When Karrie Webb says she is having a  
dream year on the LPGA Tour, she's not kidding. 
</P>
<P>
	The 24-year-old Australian is building on her modern LPGA record  
of 16 consecutive finishes in the top 10, has already won five 
times this year and is on the verge of becoming the first woman to 
go over $1 million before July. 
</P>
<P>
	But on the eve of the LPGA Championship, Webb revealed she has  
had some ``really weird dreams'' the last couples of weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	The most recent one involved her in a playoff with fellow Aussie  
Rachel Hetherington. Tournament officials made them walk up and 
down a steep hill before they could hit their tee shots, and Webb 
was out of breath. 
</P>
<P>
	``Then I woke up,'' she said. ``I woke up before I had the  
playoff because I didn't want to know who won.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Like that would have been a big surprise.  
</P>
<P>
	Webb isn't winning every week on the LPGA Tour, it just seems  
that way. In 13 tournaments this year, she has won five times and 
been in contention on Sunday in all but three of them. 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, two of those happened to be majors. She was among  
those in the wake left by Dottie Pepper in her record-setting 
victory in the Dinah Shore, and she finished 10 strokes behind Juli 
Inkster in the U.S. Women's Open. 
</P>
<P>
	At 24, Webb has already accomplished more than she could have  
dreamed with 14 victories and already enough earnings to rank 12th 
on the career money list. All that remains is that first major, and 
she will certainly be one of the favorites at Dupont Country Club. 
</P>
<P>
	Not that she would consider herself a failure if it doesn't  
happen this week. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe if I was 40 years old and heading on the way out,'' she  
said. ``But I'm still on the way. I know I have a lot of golf ahead 
of me. Three and a half years ago, if someone told me I had won 
this many times out here, I would never have believed them. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just living the dream now.''  
</P>
<P>
	The biggest dream of all this week belongs to Inkster.  
</P>
<P>
	Winning two major championships as a rookie 15 years ago -- the  
Dinah Shore and du Maurier Classic -- only made Inkster hungry to 
win them all. Perhaps that's why the LPGA Championship means more 
to her now than ever. 
</P>
<P>
	Having won the U.S. Open at Old Waverly three weeks ago, Inkster  
could join Pat Bradley as the only women to complete the modern 
LPGA career Grand Slam. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to have to have another great week to do it,''  
Inkster said. ``It's been a little hectic in my lifestyle, and I 
just have to focus on my golf game. But I think I can do it. I 
think I have as good a chance as anybody else out there right 
now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mickey Wright, whose swing Ben Hogan said was the best he ever  
saw, is the only other woman to win all four majors, which from 
1955-66 consisted of the U.S. Open, the LPGA Championship, the 
Titleholders and the Western Open. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a pretty difficult task,'' Bradley said. ``You're dealing  
with majors, which aren't your everyday, ordinary tournaments. But 
I think if anybody has the savvy to do it, Juli is perfectly 
qualified for that task.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The problem is, Inkster isn't the only player capable of winning  
this week. 
</P>
<P>
	The defending champion is Se Ri Pak, who won last week in  
Absecon, N.J., for the first time this year. All four of Pak's 
victories in 1998, when she became the first rookie since Inkster 
to win two majors, came during a 10-week stretch. 
</P>
<P>
	``It makes a good feeling to this week,'' Pak said.  
</P>
<P>
	And Webb seems to have good feelings every time she tees it up.  
She is coming off a memorable victory two weeks ago in Rochester, 
where she birdied the last three holes to win by one stroke. 
</P>
<P>
	Webb decided to take last week off -- as hot as she is, she  
probably could have made a fortune in the casinos of Atlantic City. 
</P>
<P>
	``I set my schedule up around the majors,'' she said. ``I'm  
trying to peak at the right time. I feel my game is in pretty good 
shape. I have never had as much confidence as I have right now on 
the golf course.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The only place her confidence seems to be lacking is in her  
dreams. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
