<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean Leader To Visit Clinton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- South Korean President Kim Dae-Jung will visit  
President Clinton at the White House next week. 
</P>
<P>
	Kim's visit comes at a time of renewed belligerence between  
North Korea and South Korea. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House said Thursday that Kim would visit the United  
States July 2-5, paying a working visit to Clinton on July 2. Over 
the weekend, he plans to travel to Philadelphia to receive the 
Philadelphia Liberty Medal. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton and Kim are expected to discuss security, economic and  
political matters. 
</P>
<P>
	North Korea accused South Korea this week of deliberately  
pushing their rivalry ``to the brink of war,'' marring the highest 
level talks between the two governments in 14 months. 
Representatives of the two nations met briefly in Beijing on 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	North Korea, in its fourth year of widespread food shortages,  
needs aid to repair its ruined economy. But South Korea's president 
needs tangible evidence that his more open policy toward North 
Korea is working. 
</P>
<P>
	After just 90 minutes of talks, the North Korean delegation said  
it would not meet again with South Korean officials until Seoul was 
ready to apologize for a naval clash last week in disputed waters 
of the Yellow Sea. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
