<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NHL Draft Is Strong on Defense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Don't expect the Atlanta Thrashers to stockpile  
scorers Friday in the NHL expansion draft. 
</P>
<P>
	So, when they pick their 26 players, the emphasis will be on  
defense and goaltending. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's not a whole lot of guys who scored a bunch of goals,''  
on the list of available players, said Atlanta general manager Don 
Waddell. ``Maybe the few that are on there are older players who 
are carrying big salaries.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a mock draft done by the Thrashers after the NHL released the  
list of unprotected players on Tuesday, the highest goal scorer 
chosen had 11 last season, Waddell said. 
</P>
<P>
	That means such unprotected players as Wendel Clark of Detroit,  
who had 32 goals, Ray Sheppard of Carolina and Joe Murphy of San 
Jose, who had 25 each, and Derek King of Toronto, who had 24, 
aren't likely to become Thrashers. In fact, only six unprotected 
players had 20 goals or more last season. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're in a marketplace where we have to win a fan base,''  
Waddell said. ``We're not going to score a lot of goals, but, 
hopefully, we'll play a style that's entertaining.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Thrashers must choose at least three goalies, eight  
defensemen and 13 forwards. Since defense is the strongest position 
in the draft, the other two players to bring the total to 26 will 
be either two defensemen or a defenseman and a goalie, Waddell 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Each team will lose one player except for Nashville, which  
doesn't lose any because it was an expansion team last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the better known unprotected players are Paul Coffey of  
Carolina, Dale Hunter of Colorado, Guy Carbonneau of Dallas, Igor 
Larionov of Detroit, and goalies Grant Fuhr of St. Louis, Mike 
Vernon of San Jose and Ron Tugnutt of Ottawa. 
</P>
<P>
	But Atlanta already has its starting goaltender, trading last  
week for Damian Rhodes, who had a 2.44 goals against average in 45 
games with Ottawa last season. 
</P>
<P>
	Waddell would like to draft younger goalies, hoping to find a  
backup who ``can challenge Damian Rhodes because I also believe 
it's good competition to have somebody who can push your number one 
guy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Goaltending may be critical if, as expected, the Thrashers are  
short on offense. But Waddell could pick up some scorers by trading 
some of Friday's choices between the expansion draft and Saturday's 
entry draft in which Atlanta has the second pick. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would see us making five to six deals,'' he said. ``We also  
have an obligation to make sure we keep the best players for our 
team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Waddell anticipates two players in the entry draft can play  
immediately in the NHL -- center Patrik Stefan, who spent the past 
two seasons with Long Beach of the International Hockey League, and 
right wing Pavel Brendl, who had 73 goals in 68 games for Calgary 
of the Western Hockey League. 
</P>
<P>
	``This pick is very important to the organization for a number  
of reasons,'' Waddell said. ``We're not actively shopping our pick 
(in trade talks), by any means.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His immediate focus is on putting together a team of current NHL  
players in the expansion draft. While the emphasis should be on 
young players who can develop, Waddell said that's not enough. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel that we need a balance. Three or four veteran players  
that we bring in to be the guidance for our young hockey players is 
the key,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The toughest (challenge), I think, is just getting it all  
going,'' he added. ``We're in it for the long haul. We have solid 
ownership, a new building, the whole bit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And soon he'll have his players.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
