<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> CBOT Members OK Alliance With Eurex </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Chicago Board of Trade members have  
overwhelmingly approved a broad alliance with a rival 
all-electronic exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	The board's members voted 750-126 in favor of the deal with the  
Frankfurt-based Eurex -- less than six months after narrowly 
rejecting a similar alliance. The combination will allow the two 
exchanges to cross-trade their contracts electronically starting in 
the middle of next year. 
</P>
<P>
	The vote represents a change of heart for the membership.  
Members had been hesitant to stray from the Board of Trade's 
151-year-old tradition of open outcry, which lets traders yell and 
gesture to set the prices for everything from corn to U.S. Treasury 
bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	``This alliance will secure our global leadership position,  
strengthen our world-class trading system for open outcry and 
electronic markets and bring global business opportunities to our 
members,'' Board of Trade Chairman David P. Brennan said in a 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Brennan urged a go-slow approach to an alliance with Eurex in  
December during his campaign for the board's chairmanship. That 
platform helped him edge out incumbent Patrick Arbor, a vocal 
supporter of the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	But Brennan reversed course this spring after a power struggle  
within the leadership ranks left his position weakened. 
</P>
<P>
	Large trading firms have migrated to computer-based trading,  
saying it is easier and cheaper because they no longer have to keep 
expensive staff at individual exchanges. Board of Trade competitors 
have moved quickly to profit from the trend. 
</P>
<P>
	``This decision brings us another step forward in our endeavor  
to build a bridge across the Atlantic together with our American 
colleagues,'' Eurex CEO Jorg Franke said. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Brennan urged approval of the Eurex alliance and said  
a decision to ultimately abandon the exchange's own electronic 
trading platform, known as Project A, would save money. 
</P>
<P>
	A deal between the two exchanges will cost $50 million over the  
next 18 months, but developing a new screen-based system alone 
would cost far more, Brennan said. 
</P>
<P>
	The exchange also is reconsidering becoming a for-profit venture  
to provide cash and governance to allow for quicker decisions on 
changes in the future. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990624.0362 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 10:40:19 </DATE_TIME>
