<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wimbledon Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WIMBLEDON, England (AP) -- Three-time runner-up Goran Ivanisevic  
is back at Wimbledon and into the third round for the seventh time 
in eight years. 
</P>
<P>
	Hope springs eternal for the Croatian.  
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody tells me, it's about time'' he wins, he said after  
beating Australian Sandon Stolle in four sets on Thursday. ``I 
think I'm the next one they (fans) would like to see win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ivanisevic lost a dramatic five-set final to Pete Sampras a year  
ago and was also runner-up in '94 and '92. And he's always highly 
quotable, partly on the strength of his slightly fractured English. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yes, I think I'm playing good tennis, very concentrated. I'm  
not losing my mind,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Last year was one too short,'' he added. ``If I get another  
chance, hopefully that time I should win.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *OUR GENERATION:* Andre Agassi is getting nostalgic about  
American tennis. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our generation is at the tail end,'' he said after beating  
Guillermo Canas 6-3, 6-4, 6-3. ``We're old enough now to realize 
that there are a lot of great memories that we've given to each 
other -- me, Jim (Courier), Pete (Sampras), Michael (Chang), Todd 
(Martin), all the guys on and off the court ... I think now we wish 
we would have done more.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *BIG MAC:* Playing mixed doubles at Wimbledon with Steffi Graf  
was John McEnroe's second choice. His first was playing doubles on 
the U.S. Davis Cup team, which hasn't worked out. 
</P>
<P>
	``Quite honestly, I try to stay as far away as possible from  
mixed doubles,'' said McEnroe, who is also doubling as a tennis 
commentator for NBC. ``I haven't played mixed doubles in a major in 
20 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't one of my priorities. Even this year I was hoping to  
beg my way onto the Davis Cup team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The three-time Wimbledon champion said he had ``kidded about''  
teaming with Graf, but hadn't played on grass in years ``except one 
day last week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be a bit of a crap shoot,'' he added. ``But the  
upside seemed to outweigh the negatives. ... It won't be easy 
because we'll have high expectations, but hopefully we'll have some 
fun.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *ODDS:* After ousting top-seeded and top-ranked Martina Hingis  
and then gaining a place in Wimbledon's third round, 16-year-old 
Jelena Dokic is now a 25-1 bet to go all the way and win the title. 
</P>
<P>
	A qualifier, Dokic came into the tournament as a 100-1 outsider  
with bookmaker Ladbrokes. But her amazing 6-2, 6-0 victory over 
Hingis on the Centre Court has sent her odds tumbling. 
</P>
<P>
	After a 6-0, 4-6, 8-6 victory over Katarina Studenikova of  
Slovakia on Thursday, the Serb-born Australian is tied with 
17th-seeded Anna Kournikova at 25-1. Seven-time champion Steffi 
Graf is the 2-1 favorite, Venus Williams is 4-1, defending champion 
Jana Novotna is 5-1, Lindsay Davenport is 6-1 and Monica Seles 8-1. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *0-0-0-0:* German Marlene Weingartner was drubbed 6-0, 6-0 on  
Wednesday by Monica Seles. It didn't get better on Thursday as she 
lost again 6-0, 6-0 playing doubles with Maria Fernanda Landa 
against Americans Lindsay Davenport and Corina Morariu. Without 
winning a game, she still picked up 7,920 pounds, or about $12,672, 
at Wimbledon. In 20 singles matches this season, she's lost nine 
sets 6-0. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *ODDS AND ENDS:* Former stars like Martina Navratilova and  
Billie Jean King are wearing a silver pin to show their support for 
equal money for men and women in the four Grand Slam tournaments. 
Navratilova has lashed out at Wimbledon chairman John Curry, saying 
she was amazed at the club's ``stubbornness'' on the issue. ... 
London's The Express newspaper says Martina Hingis' falling out 
with her mother has to do with the larger role her mother's 
boyfriend -- Mario Widmer -- is playing in the 18-year-old star's 
business deals. Other reports say she's angry at her mother for 
inviting Dokic to practice at their home in Switzerland, apparently 
wanting to take the young Australian under her coaching wing. ... 
Boris Becker and Michael Stich want to buy their old lockers at 
Wimbledon. The dressing room will be moved to a new player complex. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *AWARD WINNER:* Bud Collins, a Boston Globe correspondent and  
NBC television commentator, received the Red Smith Award on 
Thursday from The Associated Press Sports Editors. 
</P>
<P>
	``I always thought writing sports was fun,'' Collins said via  
satellite from Wimbledon to about 150 editors and writers who 
watched him on a big screen at the national convention in Phoenix. 
``It was better than working for a living. It is a wonderful, 
wonderful way to go. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't tell you how flattered and honored I am, not only  
because this award was named for the great Red Smith, but because 
it was voted on by my peers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His son, Rob, accepted the award on his behalf.  
</P>
<P>
	Collins has written for the Globe since 1963 and is best known  
for his tennis coverage. But he has written about everything from 
baseball to boxing. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1974, he led the way for writers showcasing their talents as  
broadcasters when he left the Globe as a full-time employee to do 
television work. 
</P>
<P>
	Collins, who describes himself as a ``scribbler and a babbler,''  
was inducted into the International Tennis Hall of Fame in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Smith Award recognizes writers who have made ``major  
contributions to sports journalism.'' APSE established the award in 
1981 and named Smith, a Pulitzer Prize-winning columnist for The 
New York Times, the first winner. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
