<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 09:50:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Paper: Lewinsky Questioned on Tripp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Maryland prosecutors have questioned Monica  
Lewinsky as part of their wiretapping case against Linda Tripp, 
whose tapes of telephone conversations with the former White House 
intern triggered the presidential sex scandal, The Baltimore Sun 
reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	Maryland forbids anyone from taping phone conversations without  
the other party's consent. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors turned over Ms. Lewinsky's answers last week to a  
Howard County grand jury investigating Ms. Tripp, the newspaper 
said, quoting unnamed sources. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Tripp secretly taped conversations in which Ms. Lewinsky  
discussed her affair with President Clinton. Ms. Tripp gave the 
tapes to Whitewater prosecutor Kenneth Starr, who detailed the 
affair in evidence he presented to Congress. The president was 
impeached, but escaped removal from office. 
</P>
<P>
	State Prosecutor Stephen Montanarelli and one of Ms. Lewinsky's  
lawyers, Nathaniel Speights, refused to tell the Sun whether Ms. 
Lewinsky had been questioned. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Tripp has admitted in federal grand jury testimony that she  
taped Ms. Lewinsky in 1997 after she was warned that doing so was 
illegal in Maryland. Montanarelli has been seeking those tapes 
since the state's case began last July. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Tripp, who lives in Columbia, received federal immunity for  
her testimony, but she is not spared from state prosecution. The 
maximum penalty is five years in prison and a $10,000 fine for each 
wiretapping offense. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
